uneventful. Did everyone that went there eat a lot of turkey before the =
party? I was very suprised to see such a calm crowd given the trance and =
happycore being played. I think ya guys were half awake out there! Maybe =
it was because the party started at 7pm and it was 10pm or so when we =
showed up. By that time it seemed like people were all tuckered out. I =
must say that was a flashback set in the back room. I think it was =
Tracer spinning all the old 1999/2000 trance. Took me back to days of E =
and puddling out upstairs at that venue. Those were the crazy days of =
that space. Cool to see it once again. Looked like a sell out party.=20

From: "innocentchild" <innocentchild@hotmail.com>

Subject: [sfraves] Devotion


Funny shit to end up back at that space again. Poor girl that was driving
shuttle kept getting lost. Cops came and went which was uneventful. Did
everyone that went there eat a lot of turkey before the party? I was very
suprised to see such a calm crowd given the trance and happycore being
played. I think ya guys were half awake out there! Maybe it was because the
party started at 7pm and it was 10pm or so when we showed up. By that time
it seemed like people were all tuckered out. I must say that was a flashback
set in the back room. I think it was Tracer spinning all the old 1999/2000
trance. Took me back to days of E and puddling out upstairs at that venue.
Those were the crazy days of that space. Cool to see it once again. Looked
like a sell out party.

pictures: www.viberation.com/ryan/devotion

ryan.bailey

From: "Happy" <happy@happycandykid.com>
To: "Raver Steve" <ravinaznguy@hotmail.com>,
	<sfraves@hyperreal.org>
References: <OE68hN2aQjUeHlYm4qB00006564@hotmail.com> <DAV147nlT2NqFJ3sl3x000114cb@hotmail.com>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Devotion

Nope, that wasn't it. People just weren't that into it, in either room. I've
seen hardcore rooms bounce for hours without stopping. Same with jungle. It
wasn't that people were tired from dancing their asses off. It was that it
was crowded, and the HC room had a lot of cross traffic leaving little room
to dance, while the other room was pretty hot. Not too bad though, it wasn't
like the last Imagine. I remember thinking, "Hmmmm, maybe I should have
dropped a pill; I would probably enjoy the party more." But then I thought,
"No, I just need to go to the right parties." This wasn't bad, and I did
dance my ass off, but I did miss the vibe.

    Side Note: I've been learning how to spin, and had a couple of
observations tonight. One was how much more critical I am now about the way
a song sounds, now that I'm used to being able to adjust it. Someone spun
one of my favorite tracks in my miniscule vinyl collection; the label just
says "Holligans of the New School 2." When I heard the beginning of the song
being mixed in, I knew it instantly. The only problem was that it was being
spun waaaaaaay pitched up, like on 45 at the top of the pitch range, while I
spin it on 33. It's a breaks track. It sounds like shit played at HHC speed.
The vocals could shatter glass, and all the sounds of the song are smashed
together. I felt very confident that it was being spun wrong, and that I
knew how to fix it! Lol!
    Also, I was watching someone in the trance room, and within about 10
minutes I saw him NOT mix twice. Meaning, he let one track run out then
started the next one. I felt like that was cheap and that I, as the
audience, deserved more! What makes this all important is the realization
that before I started to learn how to spin, I wouldn't have noticed some of
these things, and while at some level ignorance is bliss, I find that I
enjoy the music so much more now that I've begun to learn the secrets of the
man behind the green curtain.

Happy  :-)

"A happy person is not a person in a certain set of circumstances,
but rather a person with a certain set of attitudes." -Hugh Downs

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Devotion

Yah Devotion was jammed packed.

It was good talking to everyone though.  Even though the cops came and let
the party keep going, it was alright. I'm guessing it's because my car got
broken into which is why i'm dampered into my mood.  Not a lot was taken
though because the car alarm was going off.  I guess the music prevented
anyone from hearing it.  It's all good..shit happens.  Either way my vinyl
is still in my hands and nothing is missing from there..

My guess is that the dj you saw let the track run out was Tracer.  He had an
intro to the song he was playing to be heard..hence he let it play out. The
one set i have to compliment is Majerie.  Always giving the "I want to kill
you and put you in a blender mood" type of dark trance.  Made me wanna pound
something and grind it to a pulp.  God I love dark trance..hehe.. anyway
long night.. goodnight. see ya all in the morning.

Pictures are up though..
http://www.ravepicures.net

- Charlie
charlie@ravepictures.net

> as someone who is intermittently making her way
> through college, i feel that "higher" education is a
> tried-and-true obstacle course that is not only about
> learning a trade but also about teaching us to follow
> rules in a society that operates on a toil-reward
> mindset, such that few people actually think about
> what the toil is for or what the reward means to them.
> 
> so, i think that most people (at least on this list)
> have no reason to pay such close attention to spelling
> and grammar, since what they are trying to communicate
> is fairly clear.  if someone uses "our" instead of
> "are" or vice versa, generally you know what they
> meant to say.  
> 
> email lists have much more casual an atmosphere than
> an english class.  you wouldn't go to a rave and
> correct the way people speak, the vernacular is
> different and so the way we write i think would be
> just as lax.  i think anything we can to do to
> encourage communication rather than discourage it is
> the way to go as far as posting here goes.
> 
> mormon boy, if you knew jennifer in person you would
> know that "scared for our future" is one of her ways
> of joking around, clearly to me (because i know her),
> she is not sitting at home biting her nails because
> someone didn't conjugate a verb properly.  
> 
> "You must be the change you wish to see in the world."
> 
> besides being a schoolteacher, jenn takes great care
> to communicate clearly using good grammar and spelling
> herself, so i'd say she is taking ol' mahatma's
> advice.  we are all insecure in our own ways, that's
> what's fun about airing and sharing pet peeves. 
> 
> her "blatant disregard for other people's feelings"
> just tells someone else who wants to be equally
> psychoanalytical about it that she poked you where you
> felt insecure and she didn't know it.  i don't know if
> i would call that a blatant disregard.  jennifer is
> one of the most sensitive, thoughtful people i know.
> 
> but then again, how would you know that?  her
> disregard was no more blatant than yours, and your
> facade is no more or less sincere than hers or mine
> for that matter. 
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] good record stores in SJ area?

Well as being a long tim patron of Solid and friends with most of the 
co-workers and owners I will try to give an un-biased opinion.

in terms of timeline I could be off here but I dont think solid was even 
around 9 years ago.. I could be mistaken. But I use to buy records from 
Brandon when solid grooves, at that time called "Outer rythm" was run out of 
his own home with Andrian and Joe Harp. And Im thinking it was more like 7 
or 8 years ago? But at anyrate he had a solid underground selection at that 
time even selling lots of tracks from his own personal collection which is 
fucking Awesome I might add. I remember picking up lion rocks Packets of 
Peace remix.. when most other stores couldnt even get it. Or the awesome 
aresnal of Nation 12 records etc.. as far as now.. you have to understand 
business and demographics.. San Jose is a backwaters dip shit city with a 
bunch of dick wads running around it. So they have to take lots of 
consideration when ordering on what will sell etc.. also current trends (I.E 
Happy hardcore etc) and try to order a wide array of music to suit everyones 
needs.

I personally think they do a decent job considering the area and wide 
assortment of music they sell. Yes people may say "They are No clear 
records" or They are no "Frequency-8" but you also have to understand that 
stores in the city or other areas only sell one type of genere. And in the 
southbay that would kill your business cause there isnt enough traffic to 
sustain a certain genre I don't think.. And I do alot of shopping in various 
areas (I.E Online,SF,Berkeley SJ etc) and compared to most other stores 
stock or online it isnt half bad.

So just cause they didn't have your paticular records or Genere doesn't mean 
that a store sucks.. Hell I think Sub Sonic underground sucks a Fat dick 
cause they sell a bunch of Happy hardcore crap.. Does that mean the store 
actually sucks? No im sure it is a Damn good store stocking some of the best 
in HHC. But I don't like that genre does that give me the right to condemn a 
store or it's business NO.


OK im done babbling...

Macadio "Solid grooves supporter since ?? "

areas (I.E Online,SF,Berkeley SJ etc) and compared to most other stores

records" or They are no "Frequency-8" but you also have to understand that 
stores in the city or other areas only sell one type of genere. And in the 
southbay that would kill your business cause there isnt enough traffic to 
sustain a certain genre I don't think.. And I do alot of shopping in various 
areas (I.E Online,SF,Berkeley SJ etc) and compared to most other stores 
stock or online it isnt half bad.

So just cause they didn't have your paticular records or Genere doesn't mean 
that a store sucks.. Hell I think Sub Sonic underground sucks a Fat dick 
cause they sell a bunch of Happy hardcore crap.. Does that mean the store 
actually sucks? No im sure it is a Damn good store stocking some of the best 
in HHC. But I don't like that genre does that give me the right to condemn a 
store or it's business NO.


OK im done babbling...

Macadio "Solid grooves supporter since ?? "

> > "No, I just need to go to the right parties." This wasn't bad, and I did

> >
> >     Side Note: I've been learning how to spin, and had a couple of
> > observations tonight. One was how much more critical I am now about the
> way
> > a song sounds, now that I'm used to being able to adjust it. Someone
spun
> > one of my favorite tracks in my miniscule vinyl collection; the label
just
> > says "Holligans of the New School 2." When I heard the beginning of the
> song
> > being mixed in, I knew it instantly. The only problem was that it was
> being
> > spun waaaaaaay pitched up, like on 45 at the top of the pitch range,
while
> I
> > spin it on 33. It's a breaks track. It sounds like shit played at HHC
> speed.
> > The vocals could shatter glass, and all the sounds of the song are
smashed
> > together. I felt very confident that it was being spun wrong, and that I
> > knew how to fix it! Lol!
> >     Also, I was watching someone in the trance room, and within about 10
> > minutes I saw him NOT mix twice. Meaning, he let one track run out then
> > started the next one. I felt like that was cheap and that I, as the
> > audience, deserved more! What makes this all important is the
realization
> > that before I started to learn how to spin, I wouldn't have noticed some
> of
> > these things, and while at some level ignorance is bliss, I find that I
> > enjoy the music so much more now that I've begun to learn the secrets of
> the
> > man behind the green curtain.

>
> > Nope, that wasn't it. People just weren't that into it, in either room.
> I've
> > seen hardcore rooms bounce for hours without stopping. Same with jungle.
> It
> > wasn't that people were tired from dancing their asses off. It was that
it
> > was crowded, and the HC room had a lot of cross traffic leaving little
> room
> > to dance, while the other room was pretty hot. Not too bad though, it
> wasn't
> > like the last Imagine. I remember thinking, "Hmmmm, maybe I should have
> > dropped a pill; I would probably enjoy the party more." But then I
> thought,
> > "No, I just need to go to the right parties." This wasn't bad, and I did
> > dance my ass off, but I did miss the vibe.
> >
> >     Side Note: I've been learning how to spin, and had a couple of
> > observations tonight. One was how much more critical I am now about the
> way
> > a song sounds, now that I'm used to being able to adjust it. Someone
spun
> > one of my favorite tracks in my miniscule vinyl collection; the label
just
> > says "Holligans of the New School 2." When I heard the beginning of the
> song
> > being mixed in, I knew it instantly. The only problem was that it was
> being
> > spun waaaaaaay pitched up, like on 45 at the top of the pitch range,
while
> I
> > spin it on 33. It's a breaks track. It sounds like shit played at HHC
> speed.
> > The vocals could shatter glass, and all the sounds of the song are
smashed
> > together. I felt very confident that it was being spun wrong, and that I
> > knew how to fix it! Lol!
> >     Also, I was watching someone in the trance room, and within about 10
> > minutes I saw him NOT mix twice. Meaning, he let one track run out then
> > started the next one. I felt like that was cheap and that I, as the
> > audience, deserved more! What makes this all important is the
realization
> > that before I started to learn how to spin, I wouldn't have noticed some
> of
> > these things, and while at some level ignorance is bliss, I find that I
> > enjoy the music so much more now that I've begun to learn the secrets of
> the
> > man behind the green curtain.
> >
> > Happy  :-)
> >
> > "A happy person is not a person in a certain set of circumstances,
> > but rather a person with a certain set of attitudes." -Hugh Downs

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"; format=flowed

Totally Idiotic Americans

By Ted Rall, AlterNet
November 27, 2002

The official seal of the Pentagon's new Total Information Awareness Office=
=20
(TIA) bears a spooky eye above a pyramid =96 you know the one, it's on the=
=20
back of the one-dollar bill =96 peering at the globe. The fact that the TIA=
=20
was quietly funded under the auspices of the bill creating the new=20
Department of Homeland Security suggests that its mission is a vital part=20
of the war on terrorism. But Europe and Asia, the two main continents of=20
the eastern hemisphere, which appear on the TIA logo, are not in fact its=20
principal targets. You are.


Rear Admiral John Poindexter, the scandal-scarred Iran-Contra figure who=20
heads the $62.9 million "data mining" operation for the Defense Department,=
=20
says that the TIA's mission is "to detect, classify and identify foreign=20
terrorists =96 and decipher their plans =96 and thereby enable the U.S. to=
 take=20
timely action to successfully preempt and defeat terrorist acts." Sounds=20
like a magnificent idea. So why do such unusual allies as the American=20
Civil Liberties Union, The New York Times, William Safire and Republican=20
senator Charles Grassley say it's dangerous?


According to the TIA's website, Poindexter's new office will "develop=20
architectures for a large-scale counter-terrorism database, for system=20
elements associated with database population, and for integrating=20
algorithms and mixed-initiative analytical tools ... invent new algorithms=
=20
for mining, combining, and [refining] ... revolutionary new models,=20
algorithms, methods, tools, and techniques for analyzing and correlating=20
information in the database to derive actionable intelligence."


In English: Total Information Awareness will use sophisticated=20
computer-modeling programs to search every database they can get their=20
hands on. They'll scan credit card receipts, bank statements, ATM=20
purchases, Web "cookies," school transcripts, medical files, property=20
deeds, magazine subscriptions, airline manifests, addresses =96 even=20
veterinary records. The TIA believes that knowing if and when Fluffy got=20
spayed =96 and whether your son stopped torturing Fluffy after you put him=
 on=20
Ritalin =96 will help the military stop terrorists before they strike.


Most of this raw data is already available to businesses trying to market=20
their products. The TIA represents the first full-scale attempt by a=20
government agency =96 the Department of Defense =96 to collect and analyze=
 that=20
information. "There has obviously been a growing problem within the private=
=20
sector over collection of information for targeted marketing," says David=20
Sobel, general counsel at the Electronic Privacy Information Center.=20
"What's different now is the government is putting major resources into=20
getting access to privately collected data."


Critics are understandably anxious that the TIA is merely the Bush=20
Administration's latest effort to emulate the most unsavory aspects of=20
Soviet society. "If the Pentagon has its way, every American =96 from the=20
Nebraskan farmer to the Wall Street banker =96 will find themselves under=
 the=20
accusatory cyber-state of an all-powerful national security apparatus,"=20
warns Laura Murphy of the ACLU.


Is Poindexter more interested in digging up dirt on Bush's political foes=20
than fighting Islamist terrorism? Should we believe him when he says that=20
he respects the Fourth Amendment? Short of running a TIA profile on the=20
man, there's no way to know whether he's hoping to turn the United States=20
into a police state. For the sake of argument, let's assume that the TIA=20
plans to respect our privacy rights and that it won't yield to the=20
temptation to use its findings to smear political opponents.


Even if Poindexter and his domestic spying operation means well =96 and=20
that's a big if =96 the TIA is a classic case of fighting your last battle=
=20
all over again.


Like Attorney General John Ashcroft's Operation TIPS (Terrorism Information=
=20
Prevention System) =96 the Orwellian Justice Department program that asks=20
cable installers, postal workers and meter readers to turn in their=20
customers if they see any suspicious behavior =96 the TIA assumes that the=
=20
next big attack will be committed by members of Arab "sleeper cells" living=
=20
in the United States. Why do we assume this? Because that is what happened=
=20
on Sept. 11, 2001.


Presuming there will be an exact replay of Sept. 11 has led to long=20
security lines at airports and no screenings whatsoever at train stations=20
and bus depots. Which targets would you go after if you were a terrorist?


As proven by their ability to elude arrest, Osama bin Laden and his allies=
=20
are no fools. As Al Qaeda operatives plot their next attack against the=20
United States, they will exploit the weaknesses we aren't aware of or have=
=20
chosen to ignore. Another plane hijacking is unlikely, at least for the=20
foreseeable future. So are strikes carried out by illegal-immigrant=20
operatives with a fondness for strip joints living in the United States.=20
Terrorists are opportunists, not serial killers predictably utilizing=20
identical methods for each act.


Whatever you least expect: expect.


Since most of the data the TIA analyzes relates to loyal American citizens,=
=20
Total Information Awareness creates the potential for abuse of governmental=
=20
power on an unprecedented scale. Because it won't track the most likely=20
future terrorists =96 people who live in, for example, Pakistan, Egypt and=
=20
Saudi Arabia =96 it's a waste of money that furthers the illusion that our=
=20
government is protecting us.


Since Sept. 11, George W. Bush has asked us to trade our precious freedoms=
=20
for a little security. The TIA forces Americans to sacrifice privacy for=20
nothing.



Moksha Tribe

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Many persons have a wrong idea of what constitutes true happiness.  It is=
=20
not attained through self-gratification, but through fidelity to a purpose."
-Helen Keller

"How could there be any question of acquiring or possessing, when the one=20
thing needful for a man is to become--to be at last, and to die in the=20
fullness of his being."
-Antoine De Saint-Exupery

"Chaos often breeds life, where order breeds habit."
-Henry Adams

Subject: [sfraves] Racine, Wisconsin: "Disorderly House" Citations First Day in
  Court

--=====================_2997103==_.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

  Racine, Wisconsin: "Disorderly House" Citations First Day in Court

On Monday, December 2nd, the first 206 of 441 persons cited for
attending a November 2nd, benefit concert in Racine Wisconsin were
scheduled to enter pleas in court.  In an attempt to dissuade
individuals from challenging the $968 citations in court, Daniel Wright,
the City Attorney for Racine, offered to reduce fines to $100 for anyone
who pled "no contest."  Mr. Wright made it clear that the deal would not
apply to anyone who challenged the citations in court and subsequently
lost, they would have to pay the full $968 amount.

But only 19 people took the city attorney up on his offer and pled "no
contest."  More than 70% (147) of those who appeared in court pled "not
guilty" and demanded trials!  Another 40 individuals failed to appear in
court and were found "guilty" by default.

Last week the ACLU of Wisconsin urged the Racine City Attorney to
dismiss the disorderly house citations "in the interest of resolving
this matter quickly and avoiding a tremendous waste of public
resources."  If a similar percentage of the remaining 235 persons
scheduled to appear in court on December 9th and 16th plea "not guilty"
the City Attorney's office will face the logistical nightmare of having
to prepare and try hundreds of cases.

The City of Racine will likely be forced to hire a special prosecutor to
work full time on the disorderly house cases, police officers called to
testify in court will likely be paid overtime - unless police services
in the community are to suffer, and additional court staff may have to
be hired.  In all, the City of Racine may need to try 300+ people.

EM:DEF STRONGLY URGES ALL THOSE CITED TO FIGHT FOR THEIR RIGHTS AND
CHALLENGE THESE MERITLESS CITATIONS.

For more info, visit:  http://www.emdef.org/racine


"Ravers Appear In Court"
  Racine Journal Times, Dec. 3, 2002
     http://www.journaltimes.com/articles/2002/12/02/headlines/news.txt



"Irate Rave-goers Plead Not Guilty In Racine Bust"
  Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, Dec. 2, 2002
     http://www.jsonline.com/news/racine/dec02/100387.asp





Moksha Tribe

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Chaos often breeds life, where order breeds habit."
-Henry Adams

Subject: [sfraves] not enough jail space: how 'bout dr. phil instead nrr

--0-2130577165-1038939301=:88610
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii

i was just thinking, since there isn't and never will be enough jail space for all of the people who belong in there, do you think shows like dr. phil might do the trick? for example, there are tons of people on that show who have abused their children, and then their children who are in their 40's show up on the show with the parent. the adult child is in pain still and the abusive parent is suddenly just realizing that what they did wasn't the right thing, because of some isolated time that they were actually able to hear their child in adulthood...oh, i didn't know that if i hurt my child that the pain would carry on way past the moment! wow, here's to rehabilitation! how about those child development programs too? do you think if someone who has repeatedly commited criminal offense against a child watches child development programs that they will be rehabilitated and therefore, maybe it will be alright for you to stand next to that person in line at the grocery store without being subjected to some random verbal attack at some point? do you think if someone represses their hate so that for all practical appearances, via silence, that everything might be okay? like maybe you could eat breakfast with this person and not feel a hint of tension? i probably shouldn't be watching dr. phil, but i can't help but wonder about this kind of thing, because these are the people who are also on the roads driving next to the people that i care about....also, since i am now on the road, i see that you can send e-mail from you cell phone now. that is a nice option, however, i hope that no one will send e-mails while driving. pay attention to the road your on. :)

> > > > > Nope, that wasn't it. People just weren't that into it, in
> either
> > room.
> > > > I've
> > > > > seen hardcore rooms bounce for hours without stopping. Same
with
> > jungle.
> > > > It
> > > > > wasn't that people were tired from dancing their asses off. It
> was
> > that
> > > it
> > > > > was crowded, and the HC room had a lot of cross traffic
leaving
> little
> > > > room
> > > > > to dance, while the other room was pretty hot. Not too bad
> though,
> it
> > > > wasn't
> > > > > like the last Imagine. I remember thinking, "Hmmmm, maybe I
> should
> > have
> > > > > dropped a pill; I would probably enjoy the party more." But
then
> I
> > > > thought,
> > > > > "No, I just need to go to the right parties." This wasn't bad,
> and I
> > did
> > > > > dance my ass off, but I did miss the vibe.
> > > > >
> > > > >     Side Note: I've been learning how to spin, and had a
couple
> of
> > > > > observations tonight. One was how much more critical I am now
> about
> > the
> > > > way
> > > > > a song sounds, now that I'm used to being able to adjust it.
> Someone
> > > spun
> > > > > one of my favorite tracks in my miniscule vinyl collection;
the
> label
> > > just
> > > > > says "Holligans of the New School 2." When I heard the
beginning
> of
> > the
> > > > song
> > > > > being mixed in, I knew it instantly. The only problem was that
> it
> was
> > > > being
> > > > > spun waaaaaaay pitched up, like on 45 at the top of the pitch
> range,
> > > while
> > > > I
> > > > > spin it on 33. It's a breaks track. It sounds like shit played
> at
> HHC
> > > > speed.
> > > > > The vocals could shatter glass, and all the sounds of the song
> are
> > > smashed
> > > > > together. I felt very confident that it was being spun wrong,
> and
> that
> > I
> > > > > knew how to fix it! Lol!
> > > > >     Also, I was watching someone in the trance room, and
within
> about
> > 10
> > > > > minutes I saw him NOT mix twice. Meaning, he let one track run
> out
> > then
> > > > > started the next one. I felt like that was cheap and that I,
as
> the
> > > > > audience, deserved more! What makes this all important is the
> > > realization
> > > > > that before I started to learn how to spin, I wouldn't have
> noticed
> > some
> > > > of
> > > > > these things, and while at some level ignorance is bliss, I
find
> that
> > I
> > > > > enjoy the music so much more now that I've begun to learn the
> secrets
> > of
> > > > the
> > > > > man behind the green curtain.
> > > > >
> > > > > Happy  :-)
> > > > >
> > > > > "A happy person is not a person in a certain set of
> circumstances,
> > > > > but rather a person with a certain set of attitudes." -Hugh
> Downs
> > > > >

Mailing-List: contact sfraves-help@hyperreal.org; run by ezmlm
Precedence: bulk

Received: (qmail 13823 invoked from network); 3 Dec 2002 22:33:44 -0000
Message-ID: <20021203223351.17637.qmail@web10503.mail.yahoo.com>
Date: Tue, 3 Dec 2002 14:33:51 -0800 (PST)
From: Phaedrus <polykleitus@yahoo.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] EDM and music in general (was: Devotion)

I've been at this DJ thing in various levels of involvement for almost three
years now... I've been through the "I only spin trance" phase, the "I don't
spin that trance crap, I spin jungle!" phase, I've been through the "I'm a DJ
on hiatus" phase.

Through it all, I ask this of DJ's:  What is the point of music (especially
dance music) if it doesn't make you shake your ass?  Who gives a rat's ass if
it's the "correct" speed is 33 1/3, 45, or 78?  Collage makers don't care if
the face they just cut out came from a perfume ad when they glue a military
helmet from an army ad over the top.  Who cares if it's progressive house or
progressive trance?  Wet'n'hard or just a novelty version of trance? 
Happycore, terrorcore, minimalist... It sounds like a recipe for musical
jambalaya for cryin' out loud.

If it sounds good, spin it.  If it makes you shake your ass, spin it.  If it's
your favorite digeridoo (sp?) and it sounds good in the middle of your set,
shit man, let the record play out for your digeridoo solo!  Genre, genre,
genre.  Play your sappytrance back to back with that kinda-evil sounding breaky
stuff you've got, and then explain to me why some Kraftwerk would not work? 
Sound is painting emotions that one perceives with the ears.  DJs are the
performance collage artists of the world of sound.  Why would you blow such a
wonderful gift on these notions of formula and rules that are frighteningly
reminiscent of recording industry chart strategy?

And as for you dancers... expand your damn horizons.  Seriously.  I hear
stories about happycore freaks booing non-happycore DJ's off the tables at
house parties.  C'mon guys - that's not just rude, it's narrow-minded.  There
really is as much music out there as there are emotions.  Man, you don't even
have to stick to EDM!  Try some Sinatra, some Benny Goodman, or Dave Brubeck. 
Shed your fear of disco and kazaa yourself some songs, just so you know what
people your age were listening to in the 70's.  Look up "Northern Soul" on the
web and get a taste of UK Raving's great great grand-daddy.

I'm by FAR not the greatest DJ in the bay area, and let's not even talk about
beyond that.  But I take my records with me, I play 'em, and I dance to 'em. 
And folks seem to like it.  And if they don't, they go to another room.  I
still wreck on a somewhat regular basis, but DJing isn't all about
beatmatching.  It's about your collage.  It's about the whole thing when it's
said and done.  That said, may I quote the great and wise Obi-Wan Kenobi: "Let
go, Luke!  Trust your feelings!"

Oh... and PLAY IT LOUD!

- G



=====

> house parties.  C'mon guys - that's not just rude, it's narrow-minded.
There
> really is as much music out there as there are emotions.  Man, you don't
even
> have to stick to EDM!  Try some Sinatra, some Benny Goodman, or Dave
Brubeck.
> Shed your fear of disco and kazaa yourself some songs, just so you know
what
> people your age were listening to in the 70's.  Look up "Northern Soul" on
the
> web and get a taste of UK Raving's great great grand-daddy.
>
> I'm by FAR not the greatest DJ in the bay area, and let's not even talk
about
> beyond that.  But I take my records with me, I play 'em, and I dance to
'em.
> And folks seem to like it.  And if they don't, they go to another room.  I
> still wreck on a somewhat regular basis, but DJing isn't all about
> beatmatching.  It's about your collage.  It's about the whole thing when
it's
> said and done.  That said, may I quote the great and wise Obi-Wan Kenobi:
"Let
> go, Luke!  Trust your feelings!"
>
> Oh... and PLAY IT LOUD!

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: webcams and posting nude photos [was RE: [sfraves] Why sooooo sloooooow??]

Hmmm, I have something off-topic that is somewhat interesting. I visited an
old friend over the holidays, and he is new to the computer scene, having
just bought a PC about 4 weeks ago. Now, he is totally depraved and hooked
on the latest and greatest time-waster, web cams and dirty pictures.

Apparently, there are several web sites where you can post pictures of
yourself (live or still) and everyone else can see you. Moreover, you can
share pictures through email. Fun, fun, fun--but everyone lies like hell.

He actually got an old nude photo (not of himself)--just of a hunky guy, and
aimed his web cam towards the shot. Now he gets hundreds of emails every day
from guys all over the globe, talking about how "hot" he is and wanting more
pictures.

All I could think of this entire aspect of the Internet was: how perverted.
Although, I have not minded the few photos that he has forwarded to me! It
is just that I cannot help but think about how saturated we are with visual
imagery, versus real life.

I bet that these guys would not do such a thing if there were no Internet
anonymity. (No one knows who you are). Well, actually, some of the dudes
were bold enough to include a face shot! I guess they just want to show it
all. Who knows what they want. My friend says that many of these peeps are
just straight guys getting their thrills. He said that once, he was watching
a live web cast where a guy was "getting off" (while IMing/chatting) and the
dude thought that he was a girl! (Then my friend said his name, whereupon
the other guy immediately terminated the Internet connection). Man, this is
just a crazy world of peeping toms.

Well, that is my take on off-topic threads today.

Greg

Subject: Re: [sfraves] EDM and music in general (was: Devotion)

Amen. 

The way I see it, and for whatever that's worth, the
most innovative people and artists are the ones we
respect, the ones that all of the other people
emulate.  What would this scene be like without
pioneers like Kraftwerk, Underworld or even 808 State?
 Why not play with the genre? Who likes big white
lines anyway? Record Companies and glossy magazines
(ecstacy pop?) who can market big divides! Isn't
change the only way the scene will survive without
being co-opted? If not, we will hear the same 'four on
the floor' or the same 303 bassline over and over and
over again in those damn car commercials. Take the
chance of being booed. If it happens, ah well, genius
is never recognized immediately. 

And why hasn't someone made a Jungle/D&B remix of Take
Five by The Dave Brubeck Quartet?  It's the right
rhythm for it...up the tempo and damn... 

HappyAcidpsydrumtrancecoreJungletablisminthedark

B- 
 
--- Phaedrus <polykleitus@yahoo.com> wrote:
> I've been at this DJ thing in various levels of
> involvement for almost three
> years now... I've been through the "I only spin
> trance" phase, the "I don't
> spin that trance crap, I spin jungle!" phase, I've
> been through the "I'm a DJ
> on hiatus" phase.
> 
> Through it all, I ask this of DJ's:  What is the
> point of music (especially
> dance music) if it doesn't make you shake your ass? 
> Who gives a rat's ass if
> it's the "correct" speed is 33 1/3, 45, or 78? 
> Collage makers don't care if
> the face they just cut out came from a perfume ad
> when they glue a military
> helmet from an army ad over the top.  Who cares if
> it's progressive house or
> progressive trance?  Wet'n'hard or just a novelty
> version of trance? 
> Happycore, terrorcore, minimalist... It sounds like
> a recipe for musical
> jambalaya for cryin' out loud.
> 
> If it sounds good, spin it.  If it makes you shake
> your ass, spin it.  If it's
> your favorite digeridoo (sp?) and it sounds good in
> the middle of your set,
> shit man, let the record play out for your digeridoo
> solo!  Genre, genre,
> genre.  Play your sappytrance back to back with that
> kinda-evil sounding breaky
> stuff you've got, and then explain to me why some
> Kraftwerk would not work? 
> Sound is painting emotions that one perceives with
> the ears.  DJs are the
> performance collage artists of the world of sound. 
> Why would you blow such a
> wonderful gift on these notions of formula and rules
> that are frighteningly
> reminiscent of recording industry chart strategy?
> 
> And as for you dancers... expand your damn horizons.
>  Seriously.  I hear
> stories about happycore freaks booing non-happycore
> DJ's off the tables at

> it's narrow-minded.  There
> really is as much music out there as there are

> Goodman, or Dave Brubeck.

> songs, just so you know what
> people your age were listening to in the 70's.  Look

> web and get a taste of UK Raving's great great
> grand-daddy.

> > > > > wasn't

> > should
> > > have

> > > > > thought,
> > > > > > "No, I just need to go to the right parties." This wasn't bad,
> > and I
> > > did
> > > > > > dance my ass off, but I did miss the vibe.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >     Side Note: I've been learning how to spin, and had a couple
> > of
> > > > > > observations tonight. One was how much more critical I am now
> > about
> > > the
> > > > > way
> > > > > > a song sounds, now that I'm used to being able to adjust it.
> > Someone
> > > > spun
> > > > > > one of my favorite tracks in my miniscule vinyl collection; the
> > label
> > > > just
> > > > > > says "Holligans of the New School 2." When I heard the beginning
> > of
> > > the
> > > > > song
> > > > > > being mixed in, I knew it instantly. The only problem was that
> > it
> > was
> > > > > being
> > > > > > spun waaaaaaay pitched up, like on 45 at the top of the pitch
> > range,
> > > > while
> > > > > I
> > > > > > spin it on 33. It's a breaks track. It sounds like shit played
> > at
> > HHC
> > > > > speed.
> > > > > > The vocals could shatter glass, and all the sounds of the song
> > are
> > > > smashed
> > > > > > together. I felt very confident that it was being spun wrong,
> > and
> > that
> > > I
> > > > > > knew how to fix it! Lol!
> > > > > >     Also, I was watching someone in the trance room, and within
> > about
> > > 10
> > > > > > minutes I saw him NOT mix twice. Meaning, he let one track run
> > out
> > > then
> > > > > > started the next one. I felt like that was cheap and that I, as
> > the
> > > > > > audience, deserved more! What makes this all important is the
> > > > realization
> > > > > > that before I started to learn how to spin, I wouldn't have
> > noticed
> > > some
> > > > > of
> > > > > > these things, and while at some level ignorance is bliss, I find
> > that
> > > I
> > > > > > enjoy the music so much more now that I've begun to learn the
> > secrets
> > > of
> > > > > the
> > > > > > man behind the green curtain.
> > > > > >
> > > > > > Happy  :-)
> > > > > >
> > > > > > "A happy person is not a person in a certain set of
> > circumstances,
> > > > > > but rather a person with a certain set of attitudes." -Hugh
> > Downs
> > > > > >

----- Original Message -----
From: "Phaedrus" <polykleitus@yahoo.com>
To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: December 03, 2002 2:33 PM
Subject: [sfraves] EDM and music in general (was: Devotion)


> I've been at this DJ thing in various levels of involvement for almost
three
> years now... I've been through the "I only spin trance" phase, the "I
don't
> spin that trance crap, I spin jungle!" phase, I've been through the "I'm a
DJ
> on hiatus" phase.
>
> Through it all, I ask this of DJ's:  What is the point of music
(especially
> dance music) if it doesn't make you shake your ass?  Who gives a rat's ass
if
> it's the "correct" speed is 33 1/3, 45, or 78?  Collage makers don't care
if
> the face they just cut out came from a perfume ad when they glue a
military
> helmet from an army ad over the top.  Who cares if it's progressive house
or
> progressive trance?  Wet'n'hard or just a novelty version of trance?
> Happycore, terrorcore, minimalist... It sounds like a recipe for musical
> jambalaya for cryin' out loud.
>
> If it sounds good, spin it.  If it makes you shake your ass, spin it.  If
it's
> your favorite digeridoo (sp?) and it sounds good in the middle of your
set,
> shit man, let the record play out for your digeridoo solo!  Genre, genre,
> genre.  Play your sappytrance back to back with that kinda-evil sounding
breaky
> stuff you've got, and then explain to me why some Kraftwerk would not
work?
> Sound is painting emotions that one perceives with the ears.  DJs are the
> performance collage artists of the world of sound.  Why would you blow
such a
> wonderful gift on these notions of formula and rules that are
frighteningly
> reminiscent of recording industry chart strategy?
>
> And as for you dancers... expand your damn horizons.  Seriously.  I hear
> stories about happycore freaks booing non-happycore DJ's off the tables at
> house parties.  C'mon guys - that's not just rude, it's narrow-minded.
There
> really is as much music out there as there are emotions.  Man, you don't
even
> have to stick to EDM!  Try some Sinatra, some Benny Goodman, or Dave
Brubeck.
> Shed your fear of disco and kazaa yourself some songs, just so you know
what
> people your age were listening to in the 70's.  Look up "Northern Soul" on
the
> web and get a taste of UK Raving's great great grand-daddy.
>
> I'm by FAR not the greatest DJ in the bay area, and let's not even talk
about
> beyond that.  But I take my records with me, I play 'em, and I dance to
'em.
> And folks seem to like it.  And if they don't, they go to another room.  I
> still wreck on a somewhat regular basis, but DJing isn't all about
> beatmatching.  It's about your collage.  It's about the whole thing when
it's
> said and done.  That said, may I quote the great and wise Obi-Wan Kenobi:
"Let
> go, Luke!  Trust your feelings!"
>
> Oh... and PLAY IT LOUD!
>
> - G
>
>
>

Date: Tue, 03 Dec 2002 17:16:20 -0800
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
Message-ID: <F441M22bOf4YvJBjBu50001527c@hotmail.com>
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 04 Dec 2002 01:16:20.0797 (UTC) FILETIME=[C0F866D0:01C29B32]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] EDM : tempo (and we don't mean Fords !)

slow it down, speed it up, do what you want.

but the real deal is slowing down *v o c a l s*

it can extenuate subtleties that are almost entirely lost at real-time...   
a perfect example is Puretone's Addicted To Bass... even if it's not your 
bag, compare the orig to the Different Gear mix and you'll see what i mean.  
it's not a very interesting remix to say the least (except maybe for the 
awesome bassdrops at the end) but the slow down turns an already compelling 
voice into a raw sultry calling with sibilance that just haunts you to the 
bone.  yeah, recording female vocals at +5-15% then tempo them down that 
much for the final... *fans himself*

-=dave

>From: Brynne and Hernan <cortezco@pacbell.net>
>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: [sfraves] Dancers strategy
>Date: Sat, 09 Nov 2002 01:42:20 -0800
>
>
>Make your vote count for more.
>If you voted take the time to tell Politicians that you voted. Tell 
>everyone
>you meet, that you are a member of the dance music community and you vote.
>
>Your vote counts as one vote if you vote.
>Yet, if you tell people (politicians), that you vote, it counts for more
>than just one vote.
>It is time to assume our rightful place in this community.
>We as a group are a substantial part of the whole community.
>We contribute in multiple positive ways. Giving of our time and dollars to
>make this world a much better place.
>We, as a group, are a considerable portion of the work force, and we create
>more than our fair share of art.
>
>We will not be denigrated for our love of dancing.
>And we deserve a voice.
>
>Who is this voice of the dance culture?
>
>You.
>
>Ultimately, you are the one who must speak up.
>And if you are lucky other brave souls will stand with you.
>The strategy is to inform the legislative body of the numbers of voting
>dancers. Then, use this knowledge. Use it as a method of obtaining pro 
>dance
>legislation.
>
>
>As a community we must (together) decide what we want from our community 
>our
>city, state and nation.
>But they may include these things....
>
>Iron clad city policy treating Night Clubs as welcome, necessary, and
>beneficial to the community. City policy that welcomes outdoor dance 
>events.
>With a certain amount of city resource allotted to the use of public lands
>and buildings. Restructuring Law Enforcement agendas and strategy to put
>public safety and crime prevention on the forefront. Not a redefinition of
>public safety to mean 'incarcerate drug dealers' and harass citizens. But
>truly to make it safe to walk down the street, to go to an event and feel
>secure that the cops are reducing violence and theft. Public Safety means
>Safety in Public.
>
>I guess there is lots more but I thought I could put some stuff out there.
>Please feel free to show me the weaknesses in strategy.
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Devotion

If it's a breaks track, but at happycore/hardcore speed is it not a breaks
track? This is where genre classification falls apart. I was there and
remember hearing breakneck speedbreaks that were bouncy as hell. Happycore,
yes. Breakbeats, yes. Perspective makes all the difference. I always find it
cool when I hear a remix of a track done in another genre (assuming it's
done well and has a good spin on the original). Yes a *core label released
this track, but if Happy can spin it at ~75% of it's original speed and make
it work, well, that's great because it's different. Much in the way that
pitching up Metallica to 170bpm is amusing and fun to mix in for a moment.

keep it fun and different!

(please)

ryan.bailey
sninesix.design
www.sninesix.com
www.innocentchild.com

Yeah exactly!!! : )

Remember the "I have a dog and I vote"    bumper stickers.


When you and I speak up they wont bully us anymore.

**Curfews**club closures** fucked up permitting process**
that is all an infringement on the pursuit of MY LIBERTY.


Don't make me exercise my rights, bitch.


Oops, pardon the anger.


This is the main issue. Property owner's rights are paramount within the
present political values system.

If we as a community remain silent and inactive, we will forever be clubbed
to death, (with property owners rights).

I am willing to work together to make this world livable for us all.
And I am truly sorry for the people  who bought condos right next to a
thriving club district.

But I am not going to let these slightly ignorant people throttle the very
life out of our town.
Can I define ignorance as not knowing the damage that they do?


Okay, sorry, decaf, please. (Hey wait a minute I don't need to apologize!)

Hernan

>From: Brynne and Hernan <cortezco@pacbell.net>
>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: [sfraves] Dancers strategy
>Date: Sat, 09 Nov 2002 01:42:20 -0800
>
>
>Make your vote count for more.
>If you voted take the time to tell Politicians that you voted. Tell
>everyone
>you meet, that you are a member of the dance music community and you vote.
>
>Your vote counts as one vote if you vote.
>Yet, if you tell people (politicians), that you vote, it counts for more
>than just one vote.
>It is time to assume our rightful place in this community.
>We as a group are a substantial part of the whole community.
>We contribute in multiple positive ways. Giving of our time and dollars to
>make this world a much better place.
>We, as a group, are a considerable portion of the work force, and we create
>more than our fair share of art.
>
>We will not be denigrated for our love of dancing.
>And we deserve a voice.
>
>Who is this voice of the dance culture?
>
>You.
>
>Ultimately, you are the one who must speak up.
>And if you are lucky other brave souls will stand with you.
>The strategy is to inform the legislative body of the numbers of voting
>dancers. Then, use this knowledge. Use it as a method of obtaining pro
>dance
>legislation.
>
>
>As a community we must (together) decide what we want from our community
>our
>city, state and nation.
>But they may include these things....
>
>Iron clad city policy treating Night Clubs as welcome, necessary, and
>beneficial to the community. City policy that welcomes outdoor dance
>events.
>With a certain amount of city resource allotted to the use of public lands
>and buildings. Restructuring Law Enforcement agendas and strategy to put
>public safety and crime prevention on the forefront. Not a redefinition of
>public safety to mean 'incarcerate drug dealers' and harass citizens. But
>truly to make it safe to walk down the street, to go to an event and feel
>secure that the cops are reducing violence and theft. Public Safety means
>Safety in Public.
>
>I guess there is lots more but I thought I could put some stuff out there.
>Please feel free to show me the weaknesses in strategy.
>
>

Message-ID: <20021204191902.45253.qmail@web40711.mail.yahoo.com>
Date: Wed, 4 Dec 2002 11:19:02 -0800 (PST)
From: Susan Gwartney <sooziqueue@yahoo.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
In-Reply-To: <20021203223351.17637.qmail@web10503.mail.yahoo.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] EDM and music in general (was: Devotion)

> Through it all, I ask this of DJ's:  What is the
> point of music (especially
> dance music) if it doesn't make you shake your ass?

as a dj-in-training (slowly but surely), and as an
ardent music-lover of many different genres, i'd like
to argue that there is so much more value to music
than just moving people to dance.

there are a number of songs that i really enjoy just
listening to, i call them my "will-to-live" songs.
some of them are great dance music but nonetheless i
also enjoy lying in my room with the lights out and
the headphones on, feeling a connection with the
artists and the inspiration that moved someone to
create those songs.  

in fact, call me a big corny cheesehead because i am,
but some songs make me want to sit still and just
listen.  and when i go to a party and i get to hear
those songs played on a big booming system, all the
better.  nothing against dancing, i love to dance as
well but dancing to music is such a different
experience for me, i tend to alternate between dancing
phases and listening phases depending on my mood.
 
> Who gives a rat's ass if
> it's the "correct" speed is 33 1/3, 45, or 78? 

as someone who also loves to study and discuss
philosophy and psychology, i often get told by my
friends, "who cares what you call it, it is what it
is!  why do you need to talk about all this shit, why
not just go out and live your life, JUST DO IT instead
of wasting all these words and moments trying to
dissect and analyze and verbalize etc etc etc??"

the truth is, i enjoy talking about the bits and
pieces, that is me living my life and loving it just
as much anyone else going out and just doing what
other people are talking about.

while learning to spin, i've gotten lots of technical
pointers from friends, that take a lot of the effort
out of trying to "feel" your way around to the right
speeds.  intuition is an important factor, surely, but
not everyone knows how to be intuitive (i most
certainly didn't at first), and skills that are
learned and practiced, using logic, memory, and reason
are as equally invaluable as intuition.  

i think you make many excellent points, graham, which
i am not trying to overlook - most importantly, to me,
that guidelines are helpful, especially for relative
newcomers to the dj arena like myself, but it is not
all there is to know.  "let go" is good advice, to
that i would add "know when."  

;)sooz

> community.
> > >We contribute in multiple positive ways. Giving
> of our time and dollars 
> >to
> > >make this world a much better place.

> work force, and we

> > >more than our fair share of art.

> > >dance
> > >legislation.

> > >beneficial to the community. City policy that

> > >events.

> to the use of public 
> >lands
> > >and buildings. Restructuring Law Enforcement

> > >public safety and crime prevention on the

> >of
> > >public safety to mean 'incarcerate drug dealers'

> > >secure that the cops are reducing violence and

> > > > >
> > > > > >From: Brynne and Hernan
> > <cortezco@pacbell.net>
> > > > > >To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> > > > > >Subject: [sfraves] Dancers strategy
> > > > > >Date: Sat, 09 Nov 2002 01:42:20 -0800
> > > > > >
> > > > > >
> > > > > >Make your vote count for more.
> > > > > >If you voted take the time to tell
> > Politicians
> > > > that you voted. Tell
> > > > > >everyone
> > > > > >you meet, that you are a member of the
> dance
> > > > music community and you
> > > > >vote.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >Your vote counts as one vote if you vote.
> > > > > >Yet, if you tell people (politicians), that
> > you
> > > > vote, it counts for more
> > > > > >than just one vote.
> > > > > >It is time to assume our rightful place in
> > this
> > > > community.
> > > > > >We as a group are a substantial part of the
> > whole
> > > > community.
> > > > > >We contribute in multiple positive ways.
> > Giving
> > > > of our time and dollars
> > > > >to
> > > > > >make this world a much better place.
> > > > > >We, as a group, are a considerable portion
> of
> > the
> > > > work force, and we
> > > > >create
> > > > > >more than our fair share of art.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >We will not be denigrated for our love of
> > > > dancing.
> > > > > >And we deserve a voice.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >Who is this voice of the dance culture?
> > > > > >
> > > > > >You.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >Ultimately, you are the one who must speak
> > up.
> > > > > >And if you are lucky other brave souls will
> > stand
> > > > with you.
> > > > > >The strategy is to inform the legislative
> > body of
> > > > the numbers of voting
> > > > > >dancers. Then, use this knowledge. Use it
> as
> > a
> > > > method of obtaining pro
> > > > > >dance
> > > > > >legislation.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >
> > > > > >As a community we must (together) decide
> what
> > we
> > > > want from our community
> > > > > >our
> > > > > >city, state and nation.
> > > > > >But they may include these things....
> > > > > >
> > > > > >Iron clad city policy treating Night Clubs
> as
> > > > welcome, necessary, and
> > > > > >beneficial to the community. City policy
> that
> > > > welcomes outdoor dance
> > > > > >events.
> > > > > >With a certain amount of city resource
> > allotted
> > > > to the use of public
> > > > >lands
> > > > > >and buildings. Restructuring Law
> Enforcement
> > > > agendas and strategy to put
> > > > > >public safety and crime prevention on the
> > > > forefront. Not a redefinition
> > > > >of
> > > > > >public safety to mean 'incarcerate drug
> > dealers'
> > > > and harass citizens. But
> > > > > >truly to make it safe to walk down the
> > street, to
> > > > go to an event and feel
> > > > > >secure that the cops are reducing violence
> > and
> > > > theft. Public Safety means
> > > > > >Safety in Public.
> > > > > >
> > > > > >I guess there is lots more but I thought I
> > could
> > > > put some stuff out
> > > > >there.
> > > > > >Please feel free to show me the weaknesses
> in
> > > > strategy.

Subject: [sfraves] This is Not a Rave by Tara MacCall

hey West Coast peeps!

stocking stuffer for ravers  :)

i am falling in love with this book for the intelligence, research, pas=
sion
and love that clearly went into it, and the photography.

large square paperback (8.5" x 8.5"), $19.95

it has a bit of a canadian spin (there needs to be some homegrown ameri=
can
books written about our scene, yo! :), but rave is universal in experie=
nce
and this is closer to home than "generation ecstasy" and "altered state=
."

big up to Tara MacCall.  nice job!

respectfully,
mary  :)

press release below:

THIS IS NOT A RAVE
IN THE SHADOW OF A SUBCULTURE
Tara McCall

The word "rave" instantly conjures a multitude of images, attitudes and=

reactions. It is a scene that is ripe with dichotomies: beautiful, utop=
ian
moments that exist in tandem with accusations of underworld criminal
activity. Raves have been accused by some of enticing society's youth t=
o
mass-scale "crack houses," with the drug ecstasy as the Pied Piper of t=
he
decade. Others have praised this dance playground as a creative space f=
or
youth identity and exploration.

Raves are the modern party scene with ideal locales ranging from tents =
to
empty, large warehouses decorated with swirling lights and fluorescent
paint. These are the places where teenagers and young adults come to un=
wind
and release all of their pent-up energy in wild dancing, swaying and
jumping to the feeling that the power of the music gives them.  Because=
 of
the unique role they play in the lives of young partygoers, rave cultur=
e is
a worldwide phenomenon of unprecedented mass-appeal.  Its catalyst drug=
,
MDMA/Ecstasy, its fashion of defiant adolescence, and its unofficial cr=
edo
of Peace, Love, Unity and Respect are typical features of the atmospher=
e at
raves. In This is Not A Rave, Tara McCall explores raves from their ear=
ly
underground days in places like Ibiza and London, to the emergence of
commercial mega-raves that now attract tens of thousands of revelers in=

every corner of the globe and illuminates the wild fashion, drugs, and
hypnotic music and most importantly, she discusses the hedonistic dance=
 of
a subculture that is now being driven back to the underground.

The voices of hundreds of young dancers who tell their own stories
supplements McCall's personal tour of rave culture as well as exclusive=

interviews with well-known DJs and producers like Juan Atkins, David
Mancuso, Larry Heard, and a Guy Called Gerald. Challenging and
entertaining, This Is Not a Rave makes room for the many voices of this=

global phenomenon.

Tara McCall wrote her masters thesis on rave culture at McGill Universi=
ty.
She has taught dance for several years and now works in television.  Sh=
e
lives in Toronto.
=



---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

From sfraves-return-96532-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org Wed Dec 04 21:30:48 2002
Return-Path: <sfraves-return-96532-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org>
Delivered-To: sfraves-archive@hyperreal.org
Received: (qmail 42510 invoked by uid 1103); 4 Dec 2002 21:30:46 -0000
Mailing-List: contact sfraves-help@hyperreal.org; run by ezmlm
Precedence: bulk
X-No-Archive: yes
list-help: <mailto:sfraves-help@hyperreal.org>
list-unsubscribe: <mailto:sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org>
list-post: <mailto:sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Delivered-To: mailing list sfraves@hyperreal.org
Received: (qmail 42443 invoked from network); 4 Dec 2002 21:30:45 -0000
X-Originating-IP: [132.241.246.192]
From: "crazy legs" <waltzingvish@hotmail.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Cc: sacraves@hyperreal.org
Bcc: 
Date: Wed, 04 Dec 2002 13:30:52 -0800
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
Message-ID: <F756beUzmRf6Ci6nx8d0002f69c@hotmail.com>
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 04 Dec 2002 21:30:52.0364 (UTC) FILETIME=[6BCF18C0:01C29BDC]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] my neulight blazed!

So there I was driving down once again to sf on a friday evening.
All excited ,all charged up for the weekend once again!
there was virtually no traffic at all just because it was the holiday
weekend. I was very keen and excited about this because it was supposed to 
have some really fine techno and then psy trance for the rest of the 
evening!
Oh my gosh, what more could I ask for:)
I got to the map point and then took the shuttle from over there.
While on the shuttle, I got to talk with the drivers, and then while
introducing themselves, one of them goes, I'm Andy. And I say, the same
Andy as in the one playing there later on. He smiles & says yeah!
Him & Megan were very nice, we had a fine but short conversation till they 
dropped us off. They never really got to be there for most part of the night 
since they were in charge of the shuttle.
It seemed to be like some office complex where we went into. It seemed
very posh & I was quite impressed that they had managed to find something 
like that. It opened out into a huge hall, it seemed like a warehouse but 
not quite like it , only better. A better version of one:)
And then, the restrooms were sooo nice too.
There were quite a few people there already. But as expected, every single 
one of them was sitting down on the couches and chairs spread out all around 
the periphery of the hall. The decorations consisted of some drawings pinned 
on the walls all around and then there was a giant screen off to the left 
side where they had the usual graphics that were supposed to add to a raving 
atmosphere heh heh.
I went and sat down on one of the couches to soak in the whole ambience
before I started off my night. This short haired blonde comes to sit by me & 
immediately starts speaking to me. Later on, I ask her name, its Susan.
And I did not connect it to anyone either. Till she posted about the party 
the next day. Another fellow sfraver! :)
Mike Liu also came over to me & we started talking. Maybe he recognized me 
from the couple of emails I had sent him. He was also very friendly and he 
pointed out the various people who would be spinning later on in the evening 
and introduced me to some of them.
And after dilly dallying for a few minutes, I decided to get up and start 
dancing on the wide empty floor. I went right up there to the front of the 
decks & then I realised something. Ah ha, this time I did buy some earplugs, 
I had them in the bag but never thought of putting those on.
Chris the Neoangelic had told me about those. I knew I would not get a
piar in time if I tried to get it online. So I tried my luck at a Tower
record store. And voila, they did have some, under the brand name of
Hearos. It seemed the same as the etymotic earplugs that I had seen
online. These are rated at 12 db noise reduction and are supposed to
attenuate equally across the entire frequenct spectrum more or less.
Yeah, they did seem to work pretty good. But then, I do this other weird
thing, if I inhale in suddenly & sharply, I always manage to sort of close 
my ears to a certain extent. And then I can make them pop if I exhale fast. 
I'm sure some people know exactly what I am talking about.
So anyway, combining both this & the earplugs, for the first time in my
raving life, my ears felt fine at the end of the night!
I really, highly recommend to everyone to get a pair, because even if you 
dont feel it right now, that damage is taking place, & the scary part is 
,that process is kind of irreversible.
Back to the rave,  I went up to the decks, asked the guy who was spinning, 
who are you. He was nonplussed and then I clarified, like what name do you 
play under. He was Atum, one of the thump radio dj's; several of whom would 
be playing for the night.
Yes, the cycle repeats itself, I stood there, slowly getting into my
groove and then I broke out with my trademark crazy legs heh heh.
He was spinning some fine psytrance! For a while, there was just another
dude who came up & started dancing a little bit after I started. And then, 
people eventually started getting up from their (warm?) couches and came 
over to the floor too. Not a big crowd at all, but I loved it. The few 
people that were indeed dancing, they were so much enjoying themselves.
A good vibe existed! And there I was, wondering earlier, like uh oh is
this going to be like my prvious Sac experiences?  My fears were pretty
much assuaged.
The clock hands crept up to half before the witching hour, and I was
waiting so anxiously for Chris Jackson. I had such an INCREDIBLE time when 
he spun for an hour. I wanted him to go on for way more than that!
He was his usual cool self, totally concentrating on spinning his music.
But I'm sure from the corner of his eyes, he was watching everything else 
around him. Fine, wicked, dark, complex strains of melodies flowed and I was 
in rave heaven. He also got into this breaks section for part of the mix and 
that was awesome too. That was when, he was kind of grooving away too:) Too 
bad, very few people were up and dancing. They didnt know what they were 
missing out on or perhaps they were so overwhelmed by the beautifulness that 
they forgot to get up heh heh. whatever it was, I danced my butt off. I was 
spinning round and round, contorting my body into crazy angles and just 
being so wild in general. And I could not help yelling out now & then during 
the downtempo parts to show how much I was loving it. Though, I did not yell 
out full blast. For some strange reason, I was wondering if that might be 
too loud (because I could not tell the volume since I had earplugs) Quite 
funny heh heh.
I was so exhausted with the frenzy that was all Chris J's fault that I had 
to take a breather. I went over & flopped down on the couch, too bad I could 
not keep up my frenzy, because Dutch was spinning some neat psytrance too!  
Sometimes I wish, I had a piar of reserve legs, which I could put on & 
continue on without a break:)
While sitting there, I spied a pair of glowing green pants with a familiar 
design on it. It sparked off something in my brain & then I knew it was 
neoangelic Chris!! I was so pleased to see him, I had to get up & drag my 
tired butt over to say hi. He wondered when Chris Jackson was coming on, I 
said he had already missed him. Too bad, he said he was driving with someone 
who drove like a grandma hahahaha. I wonder if he had known when Chris J 
spinning, if he would have gone out of control & taken over the reins ahem 
wheels heh heh.
I pretty much stayed on the couch for most of his set, there was this guy 
roaming around , checking up on people to make sure that no one was
smoking.  No offense to any smokers but yes, the smoke kind of bothers me 
when I am dancing in there. I mean its alright to do their thing, but they 
could always do it in a seperate lounge or something, and come back inside 
to dance some more. That guy was really taking his task seriously, when I 
happened to glance at him. He would be shinning the light now & then, 
wherever he thought he should. Too cool! I saw him on my way out, and by the 
time I was out, I realised I should have stopped & lauded him on his 
efforts:)
I got over some my exhaustion and then, I went back on to the floor to
dance to the last few minutes of that set.  There were actually way more
people than the last hour. Obviously they must be very familiar with that 
strain of electronica or the thump radio parties. I really, really hope 
techno becomes a big & viable part of the scene. I dont see why that wont 
happen. Its only a matter of time...
Mike was trying to decide when he should have Mr Steve Ronan spin. He
wanted as many people to see him, hance the reasoning. Steve came on after 
all, at half past one.  Yeah, he was the other big part of the night that I 
had been looking forward too!!!
He is a short bloke & he looked like he had stayed up too long & had been 
drinking too much coffee heh heh.
He lived up to his reputation too(whatever that be, I have no idea:) I
just loved the music so much. He did not man the turntables, instead
choosing to bypass that with cd's. At the end of the night, he said he was 
just feeling a wee bit lazy heh heh.
People were falling away like flies as his set and the night went on.
Maybe a handful of us were dancing away and we were going strong.
During the set, there was this tall, thin girl with tiny pigtails whirling 
in front of the decks in a swoop and dancing away wildly & then swirling out 
of sight. Yeh, she had the groove alright!!! Naturally, I talked to her, 
she's Franceska?  And then, there was this other curly haired brunette 
dancing oh so smoothly. I would almost say that she was doing the Liquid, 
but it was quite close. I was like, wow, I want to learn how to do that! She 
was Nicole.
And then Chris had said he would come right to the very front to dance
when Steve spun. He did try alright, but only for a while. He had
unfortunately not brought his ear plugs along. So he stayed a fair
distance for the rest of the evening. Though for the instances when we
danced around in proximity, I had fun. I always have fun, he goes into all 
kinds of exotic moves, and I imitate that. And then, I do something & he 
follows. Its too cool kicking it with him! Ooh he told me about the rave 
store where he bought his pants, I need to ask him again because maybe some 
time I might be able to afford getting something fancy like that. I like 
dressing up when going dancing!
This gorgeous ravishing readhead was taking pictures left & right, I went up 
to ask her if it was for some website, & she says sfraves. She said her name 
is Karina, and then I recognized her from that.
All of Steve Ronan's set was a delight, I dont know how I managed to keep 
dancing all the time, but how could I resist!  He must have stopped at maybe 
a little bit after 3. I thought, Mike and Andy would come on next.
But Atum came on again, he was spinning so good that Mike let him come on 
again. I groaned to Mike, I thought you were coming on next. And he's
teasing me saying that if he did, the rest of the people left in the room 
would flee heh heh. He did come on for a very few minutes, Andy did not at 
all. I guess I will have to wait till the next time.
It all ended at 4 (because they could not get the venue for later than
that time)  I still hung around for maybe another half an hour.
I had fun speaking with Steve some more. He said that he had played in
Bombay when I said where I was from.
I did not want to leave even though it was over. I still wanted to be
around them. Hang around & talk with them forever. Though I knew every
single person in there just like that night, they were all so nice, it
seemed like I had known them forever.  Sigh, I am getting sentimental.
I ws about to go off to the restroom and Steve asked, you leaving?
I smiled and said no, I'm coming back. And I said, I'm going to tell you
when I go.
And yeah, I came back, I talked with them even more. Its kind of a blur
about exactly what we talked about. But I will remember the feeling, it
was so wonderful. It was with an ache in my heart that I realised that it 
was finally time to go home. I shook his hand, said goodbye and started 
walking away. And when I reached the entrance, I knew I had to do this...I 
went back, I said i want a picture with all of you. And so, there we were 
sitting all in a bunch and smiling away. Me in the middle, surrounded by 
Steve, Dutch, Atum and Mike who was crouching above my head to be in the 
pic. Click!!! went the camera and yet another moment was captured on print 
locking up an entire chain of memories that shall be triggered time after 
time when I look at it.
And then, I took the shuttle back to my car, I was the last one. Megan was 
saying she thought everyone had already left. While she was driving me back, 
we were talking about our dreams of travelling all over the world.

vj
