To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Cc: sacraves@hyperreal.org
Bcc: 
Date: Wed, 04 Dec 2002 13:47:58 -0800
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
Message-ID: <F71dhQMZYfEzFlTHoyV00016b5a@hotmail.com>
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 04 Dec 2002 21:47:58.0489 (UTC) FILETIME=[CF6D5890:01C29BDE]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] my Devotion  (aka  discovering hardcore)

Saturday evening crept up & started passing by, I tried calling the info 
line for Midnight recess and there was nothing at all. I actually pulled 
over & thought for a few minutes before getting on the
freeway once again. OH boy, what a dilemna.
And then I still did not sense anything concrete. the next best thing was to 
be rational & choose what was certain:) I mean there would be hardcore 
there, but I saw it this way..maybe it was time for me to give it a try:)
And besides I could check out Molly Mush.
And then I flew away to Oakland, I actually got lost trying to find
Skills! I really & truly got lost due to some stupid block numbering. down 
that street(Telegraph ave) So I went the wrong way and then it was almost 9. 
Like 10 minutes to 9. And I was literally crying, I mean I wanted to go, I 
did not want to be stranded & go to some stupid club in the city!
In sheer desperation, I kind of stopped every couple of blocks & asked
every person I encountered about Skills! See I did not have their phone
number either, silly me.
And then, I saw this internet cafe, I thought maybe I could try there.
The girl managing the store was so nice! She said, yes I could use her
account & look for it. My fingers flew over the keyboard....and the
strange thing was that Skills does not have a website with a phone
number! 5 minutes to 9 & ticking....(the shop supposedly closed at 9)
And finally, where do I find a number, in one of lines listed in a hit
result on some random website which had a comment on Skills!
Relieved, I rushed over to her, again she was so awesome. She let me use
the phone and I dialed the digits. The clock said 9, and I was relieved
when I heard someone pick up. I said everything about me & they gave me
directions, & said they would wait for me. Putting down the phone, I was
so relieved, I had a huge sigh of relief and there was a big big smile on my 
face. If it werent for the counter behind which that girl was, I would have 
given her a big hug. So all I said was thank you so much & skipped out of 
the cafe.
They gave me my ticket, & then there was this other guy there, he was up
here for Thanksgiving & was trying to figure on what party to go for.
The Skills guy said there was exactly one more ticket left(for Devotion)
if he wanted it. He started thinking hard, & then he says but how do I get 
there. Automatically it came from me, sure I can take you there & then drop 
you off for your greyhound bus.
He made up his mind & got the very last ticket. There was even more
confusion to follow. When we called for directions from his cell, we
could barely decipher it. The girl was speaking way too fast for us to
pick it up. And then, he had this idea of going over to a coffee shop he
had been to around the uc berkeley campus. His reasoning was that there
were plenty of people there and someone should know! He was going to make 
someone listen to the directions and then ask them to help us heh heh.
And then, we get a hold of one of the guys managing the shop. He is all
serious & then he goes gets someone else. So he kind of understands &
tells us how to go about the first half.
Truthfully, when I listened to it again (for a few times) it did become
clear to me. I dont know who was recording on that, but they better not
carry the theme of a hardcore party too far, making the directions stick
to that speed is not nice:):)
Yay, we finally got there, only to find that this was a map point. And
there were tons of people already waiting to be shuttled. People was
desperately even looking for tix but there were none to be had.
We somehow could sneak past the whole line, because when they called for
people to start getting in the back of one truck. No one started, & then
the girl in there looked at me & motioned us to go ahead. Haha , as we
were getting in, she says if they dont start getting in, its their fault.
We had to lie down low to avoid being seen since there like 8? people in
the back. Oooh, that was so exciting. I was day dreaming that hopefully we 
might see some action as in a cop chasing us. I am just kidding.
We arrived at the venue and we were quickly ushered inside.
Oh yeah, it was a proper warehouse. There were tons of people, the
lightening was quite garish. There had been a feeble attempt at
decorations. I dont mean in a bad way, it just added to how the ambience
in there was. Yep, happy hardcore was ripping out of the speakers in that 
main room. I did not see a lot of people dancing. Almost all of them were 
standing around & hanging out. I went on to the other room, I figured this 
was the trance/house room. It was even more crowded. Was it Majere spinning 
when I got in? We must have got there like a little bit before 11. I wanted 
to know who was playing when, but had little luck in finding that out.
Though I did get to know about some of the sets I really wanted
to see. Miss Molly Mush was going to come on an hour or so later on.
Yeah, I knew I had to check her out. Her mixing and of course her:)
Frankly I have never been to any party which did have hardcore. This was
my first time, I did not know how it would go. I really thought it was not 
meant for me. But anyway I wanted to try it out.
I danced for a while in the house room, I got on the elevated space at the 
back, to my delight I found the floor was wooden and it was truly springy.
Oh joy! this was the best floor I had been to. It had the right amount of 
the tiniest spring which was good for jumping around.
I had a good time dancing away on that platform till I somehow knew it was 
time to go to the other room.
I was really excited & agog with curiousity about my first exposure to
hardcore. I slowly edged my way through the crowd(a very still standing
crowd) to kind of in the front as someone before Molly was finishing up
his set.  I have been to her website but did not care to glance much at
pics so I did not recognize her till she stepped up.
Everyone around me erupted in a cheer, I joined in. And then the music
started flowing, the beats started building up, faster & faster. And wow, I 
was actually dancing to it. Moving in time to the beat, equally fast. I had 
always, always thought for long about how it would be insane to keep up with 
that tempo. But this was wonderful, my body was just doing it automatically. 
I did not really have to make too much effort.
So there I was, my feet not doing much(they would wear out so fast
otherwise!) while from the waist up, I was a mini tornado. Twisting &
turning & writhing & gyrating. My brain was overflowing with the lovely
music and I was smiling. And at this point, I had an awesome realisation.
Yes!! I indeed do like happy hardcore, I fell in love with yet another
style of electronika:):)!!! The music spun on, a couple of guys were mcing 
while Molly spun. Oh yeah, they were so totally enthusiastic and trying to 
urge the crowd on to some serious dancing. Too bad, still most of them were 
just standing there. A handful of us were indeed dancing though, that was 
cool. I found to my wonder, that I could just keep going, I mean keep 
dancing at that tempo for as long as I wanted. How fun! One of them(Cliff) , 
pointed at me and something about how I was dancing so much and that I was 
hardcore. Something like that. I was pleased.  Yep I was the dude dancing 
out there, in my "leave no trace" ethics dark green t shirt.
The cops came(they always have to huh) and for a few minutes the music was 
turned down as they announced that they would shut the whole thing down at 
1! And then, they said they would let it go on if everyone disposed their 
drinks, smokes,etc.  How cool, I mean I did not have to deal with that, but 
atleast getting rid of the smoke in the air, I would like that(not that I 
have anything against those people, its just their own thing!)
A collective roar went up from the crowd as the music started thumping &
shaking the room once again!  Oh yeah I did forget my earplugs that night( 
how very dumb! I forgot to take em in a hurry)
I loved Molly's set, it was too bad it was over quite soon. I hope I get a 
chance to see her again sometime ! And there's another thing, the way I was 
located, when she had her head slightly bent down while mixing.
I thought it was cool, the way I could not see her eyes, but only her
eyelids and eyebrow. I aint being weird, that pose just struck me:)
I cheered as she got done, I was going to go up say hi, but she
apparently was in a hurry and so I did not go up as she headed out.
But anyway, thanks to her, I am into happy hardcore!!!!!!!!!!!!!
That I think was the best part of my night, the highest note.
I left the room feeling so high. I went back to the other room and stayed 
there for the rest of the night. I did want to see Valerie Sparks, I dont 
think she did come?
Back on the springy floor, I was jumping around, when this guy comes up to 
me. I did not place him at first though he seemd familiar. It was Dustin 
from my very first rave, ETA Neo Tokyo 3000!! It was grand to see him.
He had this kind of a turban hat on heh heh.  One of the tnings that came up 
as we talked...I happened to ask if he knew who was spinning right then. And 
he says, "I dont know, I am not here to see someone specific spin, if I like 
the music, I just dance. I can dance to this music anywhere, but raves are 
special because its only there that I can
experience the exact kind of atmosphere which is so perfect for listening 
and dancing to that music."
Maybe not his exact words, but that's what I kind of remember. I said how 
true....how can I not keep going back; where else could I ever find the vibe 
that existed there. And the whole ambience or aura or atmosphere.
Only to be found at raves like this!!!:) And I guess that's why I keep
coming back time after time, from far, far away.
My life would definitely have a void if I stopped or if I cant go anymore.
So, there was this girl dressed up like a cheerleader? I am bad at
recognizing costumes. The people who were there will know what I mean, the 
redhead in a white shirt & blue tie, a teeny weeny red skirt & sexy laced 
white stockings. She was part of the crew & oh yeah , she was so cheerful & 
playing her role to the hilt & loving every moment of it. She would flit 
around from room to room, always smiling always yelling out , shaking her 
lil butt & then flitting to another corner:) I didnt even ask her name heh 
heh.
Yeah, I met more awesome people, again I'm bad with names so dont remember 
too much. There was this guy who maybe recognized me from my postings & he 
says, are you crazy legs?  I said yeah, & he laughs & says, I cant believe 
it, I met Crazy legs. He kept going on with that for a few minutes. Neither 
sarcastically either, that was nice & funny heh heh. Oh yeah, if he gets 
this, he better email me back because we were talking about possible 
software jobs in Berkeley. Hey, write me asap!!
And from him, I came to know this was called the crackhouse.  He had
bought a large couch kind of thing. He said he always brought something or 
the other with him every time he went raving & left it behind.
I started tiring out as the night wore on, though I had to keep dancing
because I was also waiting to hear the hard house spun by Denise.
That was a fine set, she was mxing along with someone else. I dont know
his name but he was good too. I really did try to dance hard, I guess
somehow I carried on for that entire hour. Arrrgh, I really wanted to
dance, but my body could not keep up the frenzy. I crashed down at the end 
of that set, it was 3 in the morning.
The crowd was thinning out, & I decided to take off. I knew I could not go 
on anymore! I crashed in the car as usual, snuggling beneath my sleeping 
bag. Then, I heard a knock on the window, it was Jeremy, he was back too.
There was a house party going on somewhere in So SF . I said let me sleep & 
maybe I will be up for driving. Never happened heh heh, I could not get up 
till like 6 or so.
I dropped him off at the bus station and then headed over to The End up.
Once again I had fun dancing in there, this time getting worn out even
quicker at maybe 2 in the afternoon.

vj

Subject: RE: [sfraves] SFLNC Bumper Stickers

Ya know, this thread brings back some memories...

When I first got involved with DanceSafe, one of the things we were thinking of
at the time was getting volunteers certified to register people to vote (like
they do on those clipboards at rallys and such), and actually having voter
registration at the booths.  Eventually, IIRC, tho we determined that doing so
would be too political of an action, and therefore jeopardise our 501(c)3
status.

Sometimes, tho, I've toyed with the idea of spinning off a seperate group
myself to so so.  After all, wouldn't it have been nifty if all 10K 18+ ravers
at the last Skills party had walked out of there registered to vote?  I know in
a city of 700K, 10K is only a small blip.  But every little bit would help, eh?

And, of course, a part of that would be to hand out stickers that say something
like: "I'm a raver, and I VOTE!".

The optimisic part of me really does want to believe that that would put a bit
of the fear of god into the pigs.

Anyway, my main contribution to the discussion on the topic at DanceSafe was a
hold back from my punk rock days and to suggest thet we use the sticker guy:

http://www.stickerguy.com/menu.html

I think better than half the punk rock bands in the US get their stickers
through him.  Of the cliche: "Fast, good, cheap; pick two", he is good and
cheap.  He's just a bit slow.  Good people too... it's a small, independant
company, not beholden to the big corperate players.  And they really do top
notch work.  And they even donate a fair bit of their profits to charity:

http://www.stickerguy.com/charities.htm

(Is it obvious yet that I think pretty highly of these guys?  But wait...)

What else is nifty, is that in addition to your standard black, white, and red
vinyl stickers; they also have metallic foil backgrounds, GLITTER backgrounds,
brushed chrome, prismatic, and even GLOW IN THE DARK vinyl!  All of these are
the high-quality stuff that could be used for bumper stickers!

Would it not be nifty to have a GLOW IN THE DARK "voting raver" or SFLNC bumper
sticker???


cya,
john

> Saturday evening crept up & started passing by, I tried calling the info
> line for Midnight recess and there was nothing at all. I actually pulled
> over & thought for a few minutes before getting on the
> freeway once again. OH boy, what a dilemna.
> And then I still did not sense anything concrete. the next best thing was
to
> be rational & choose what was certain:) I mean there would be hardcore
> there, but I saw it this way..maybe it was time for me to give it a try:)
> And besides I could check out Molly Mush.
> And then I flew away to Oakland, I actually got lost trying to find
> Skills! I really & truly got lost due to some stupid block numbering. down
> that street(Telegraph ave) So I went the wrong way and then it was almost
9.
> Like 10 minutes to 9. And I was literally crying, I mean I wanted to go, I
> did not want to be stranded & go to some stupid club in the city!
> In sheer desperation, I kind of stopped every couple of blocks & asked
> every person I encountered about Skills! See I did not have their phone
> number either, silly me.
> And then, I saw this internet cafe, I thought maybe I could try there.
> The girl managing the store was so nice! She said, yes I could use her
> account & look for it. My fingers flew over the keyboard....and the
> strange thing was that Skills does not have a website with a phone
> number! 5 minutes to 9 & ticking....(the shop supposedly closed at 9)
> And finally, where do I find a number, in one of lines listed in a hit
> result on some random website which had a comment on Skills!
> Relieved, I rushed over to her, again she was so awesome. She let me use
> the phone and I dialed the digits. The clock said 9, and I was relieved
> when I heard someone pick up. I said everything about me & they gave me
> directions, & said they would wait for me. Putting down the phone, I was
> so relieved, I had a huge sigh of relief and there was a big big smile on
my
> face. If it werent for the counter behind which that girl was, I would
have
> given her a big hug. So all I said was thank you so much & skipped out of
> the cafe.
> They gave me my ticket, & then there was this other guy there, he was up
> here for Thanksgiving & was trying to figure on what party to go for.
> The Skills guy said there was exactly one more ticket left(for Devotion)
> if he wanted it. He started thinking hard, & then he says but how do I get
> there. Automatically it came from me, sure I can take you there & then
drop
> you off for your greyhound bus.
> He made up his mind & got the very last ticket. There was even more
> confusion to follow. When we called for directions from his cell, we
> could barely decipher it. The girl was speaking way too fast for us to
> pick it up. And then, he had this idea of going over to a coffee shop he
> had been to around the uc berkeley campus. His reasoning was that there
> were plenty of people there and someone should know! He was going to make
> someone listen to the directions and then ask them to help us heh heh.
> And then, we get a hold of one of the guys managing the shop. He is all
> serious & then he goes gets someone else. So he kind of understands &
> tells us how to go about the first half.
> Truthfully, when I listened to it again (for a few times) it did become
> clear to me. I dont know who was recording on that, but they better not
> carry the theme of a hardcore party too far, making the directions stick
> to that speed is not nice:):)
> Yay, we finally got there, only to find that this was a map point. And
> there were tons of people already waiting to be shuttled. People was
> desperately even looking for tix but there were none to be had.
> We somehow could sneak past the whole line, because when they called for
> people to start getting in the back of one truck. No one started, & then
> the girl in there looked at me & motioned us to go ahead. Haha , as we
> were getting in, she says if they dont start getting in, its their fault.
> We had to lie down low to avoid being seen since there like 8? people in
> the back. Oooh, that was so exciting. I was day dreaming that hopefully we
> might see some action as in a cop chasing us. I am just kidding.
> We arrived at the venue and we were quickly ushered inside.
> Oh yeah, it was a proper warehouse. There were tons of people, the
> lightening was quite garish. There had been a feeble attempt at
> decorations. I dont mean in a bad way, it just added to how the ambience
> in there was. Yep, happy hardcore was ripping out of the speakers in that
> main room. I did not see a lot of people dancing. Almost all of them were
> standing around & hanging out. I went on to the other room, I figured this
> was the trance/house room. It was even more crowded. Was it Majere
spinning
> when I got in? We must have got there like a little bit before 11. I
wanted
> to know who was playing when, but had little luck in finding that out.
> Though I did get to know about some of the sets I really wanted
> to see. Miss Molly Mush was going to come on an hour or so later on.
> Yeah, I knew I had to check her out. Her mixing and of course her:)
> Frankly I have never been to any party which did have hardcore. This was
> my first time, I did not know how it would go. I really thought it was not
> meant for me. But anyway I wanted to try it out.
> I danced for a while in the house room, I got on the elevated space at the
> back, to my delight I found the floor was wooden and it was truly springy.
> Oh joy! this was the best floor I had been to. It had the right amount of
> the tiniest spring which was good for jumping around.
> I had a good time dancing away on that platform till I somehow knew it was
> time to go to the other room.
> I was really excited & agog with curiousity about my first exposure to
> hardcore. I slowly edged my way through the crowd(a very still standing
> crowd) to kind of in the front as someone before Molly was finishing up
> his set.  I have been to her website but did not care to glance much at
> pics so I did not recognize her till she stepped up.
> Everyone around me erupted in a cheer, I joined in. And then the music
> started flowing, the beats started building up, faster & faster. And wow,
I
> was actually dancing to it. Moving in time to the beat, equally fast. I
had
> always, always thought for long about how it would be insane to keep up
with
> that tempo. But this was wonderful, my body was just doing it
automatically.
> I did not really have to make too much effort.
> So there I was, my feet not doing much(they would wear out so fast
> otherwise!) while from the waist up, I was a mini tornado. Twisting &
> turning & writhing & gyrating. My brain was overflowing with the lovely
> music and I was smiling. And at this point, I had an awesome realisation.
> Yes!! I indeed do like happy hardcore, I fell in love with yet another
> style of electronika:):)!!! The music spun on, a couple of guys were mcing
> while Molly spun. Oh yeah, they were so totally enthusiastic and trying to
> urge the crowd on to some serious dancing. Too bad, still most of them
were
> just standing there. A handful of us were indeed dancing though, that was
> cool. I found to my wonder, that I could just keep going, I mean keep
> dancing at that tempo for as long as I wanted. How fun! One of them(Cliff)
,
> pointed at me and something about how I was dancing so much and that I was
> hardcore. Something like that. I was pleased.  Yep I was the dude dancing
> out there, in my "leave no trace" ethics dark green t shirt.
> The cops came(they always have to huh) and for a few minutes the music was
> turned down as they announced that they would shut the whole thing down at
> 1! And then, they said they would let it go on if everyone disposed their
> drinks, smokes,etc.  How cool, I mean I did not have to deal with that,
but
> atleast getting rid of the smoke in the air, I would like that(not that I
> have anything against those people, its just their own thing!)
> A collective roar went up from the crowd as the music started thumping &
> shaking the room once again!  Oh yeah I did forget my earplugs that night(
> how very dumb! I forgot to take em in a hurry)
> I loved Molly's set, it was too bad it was over quite soon. I hope I get a
> chance to see her again sometime ! And there's another thing, the way I
was
> located, when she had her head slightly bent down while mixing.
> I thought it was cool, the way I could not see her eyes, but only her
> eyelids and eyebrow. I aint being weird, that pose just struck me:)
> I cheered as she got done, I was going to go up say hi, but she
> apparently was in a hurry and so I did not go up as she headed out.
> But anyway, thanks to her, I am into happy hardcore!!!!!!!!!!!!!
> That I think was the best part of my night, the highest note.
> I left the room feeling so high. I went back to the other room and stayed
> there for the rest of the night. I did want to see Valerie Sparks, I dont
> think she did come?
> Back on the springy floor, I was jumping around, when this guy comes up to
> me. I did not place him at first though he seemd familiar. It was Dustin
> from my very first rave, ETA Neo Tokyo 3000!! It was grand to see him.
> He had this kind of a turban hat on heh heh.  One of the tnings that came
up
> as we talked...I happened to ask if he knew who was spinning right then.
And
> he says, "I dont know, I am not here to see someone specific spin, if I
like
> the music, I just dance. I can dance to this music anywhere, but raves are
> special because its only there that I can
> experience the exact kind of atmosphere which is so perfect for listening
> and dancing to that music."
> Maybe not his exact words, but that's what I kind of remember. I said how
> true....how can I not keep going back; where else could I ever find the
vibe
> that existed there. And the whole ambience or aura or atmosphere.
> Only to be found at raves like this!!!:) And I guess that's why I keep
> coming back time after time, from far, far away.
> My life would definitely have a void if I stopped or if I cant go anymore.
> So, there was this girl dressed up like a cheerleader? I am bad at
> recognizing costumes. The people who were there will know what I mean, the
> redhead in a white shirt & blue tie, a teeny weeny red skirt & sexy laced
> white stockings. She was part of the crew & oh yeah , she was so cheerful
&
> playing her role to the hilt & loving every moment of it. She would flit
> around from room to room, always smiling always yelling out , shaking her
> lil butt & then flitting to another corner:) I didnt even ask her name heh
> heh.
> Yeah, I met more awesome people, again I'm bad with names so dont remember
> too much. There was this guy who maybe recognized me from my postings & he
> says, are you crazy legs?  I said yeah, & he laughs & says, I cant believe
> it, I met Crazy legs. He kept going on with that for a few minutes.
Neither
> sarcastically either, that was nice & funny heh heh. Oh yeah, if he gets
> this, he better email me back because we were talking about possible
> software jobs in Berkeley. Hey, write me asap!!
> And from him, I came to know this was called the crackhouse.  He had
> bought a large couch kind of thing. He said he always brought something or
> the other with him every time he went raving & left it behind.
> I started tiring out as the night wore on, though I had to keep dancing
> because I was also waiting to hear the hard house spun by Denise.
> That was a fine set, she was mxing along with someone else. I dont know
> his name but he was good too. I really did try to dance hard, I guess
> somehow I carried on for that entire hour. Arrrgh, I really wanted to
> dance, but my body could not keep up the frenzy. I crashed down at the end
> of that set, it was 3 in the morning.
> The crowd was thinning out, & I decided to take off. I knew I could not go
> on anymore! I crashed in the car as usual, snuggling beneath my sleeping
> bag. Then, I heard a knock on the window, it was Jeremy, he was back too.
> There was a house party going on somewhere in So SF . I said let me sleep
&
> maybe I will be up for driving. Never happened heh heh, I could not get up
> till like 6 or so.
> I dropped him off at the bus station and then headed over to The End up.
> Once again I had fun dancing in there, this time getting worn out even
> quicker at maybe 2 in the afternoon.
>
> vj

X-Spam-Rating: localhost.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] SFR PDA Calendar v. 2.0

Dear SFRaves Community -

The SFR PDA Calendar data has been successfully migrated to the new SFR
Calendar interface.

Please help me test the calendar output. To test the PDA Calendar, follow
these instructions.

SFRaves.org PDA Calendar v.2.0

REQUIREMENTS: To use the SFRaves.org PDA Calendar and AvantGo.com, you
need a PDA which runs Palm OS 4.x or above, supports synchronization on
http port 80, and an OS supported by AvantGo.com Software.

What is Avant Go?  http://www.avantgo.com

- Avant Go is PDA software with dual interfaces: a web application
interface coupled with the functionality of Avant Go Sofware to sync any
device running Palm OS. Avant Go provides access to online web content via
Avant Go web Channels. These channels point to content which is hosted and
maintained by outside sources. SFRaves.org PDA Calendar content source is
@ http://www.sfraves.org/calendar/sfrcalpda.txt

What is the SFRaves.org PDA Calendar?

- A condensed ascii text format of the SFRaves.org Calendar, coupled with
the functionality of Avant Go Software and a Palm OS Device.

TO ACCESS THE SFRAVES.org PDA CALENDAR

AVANT GO USERS
New Users Sign Up HERE http://avantgo.com/setup/index.html
Existing Users login HERE: http://avantgo.com/login/index.html

Go to the following AvantGo URL to add the SFRaves.org PDA Calendar to
your account and PDA device.

http://avantgo.com/mydevice/autoadd.html?title=SFRaves.org%20Calendar&url=http%3
A%2F%2Fwww.sfraves.org%2Fcalendar%2Fsfrcalpda.txt&max=175&depth=0&images=0&links=0&refresh=alway
s&hours=2&dflags=127&hour=0&quarter=00&s=00

PALM OS USERS

You can download the most current SFR PDA Calendar @:
http://www.sfraves.org/calendar/sfrcalpda.txt

Note: The limitations of most PDA devices and Operating Systems is file
size, type and memory allocation. As a result, the event listings on
calendar are condensed to include listings for December 2002.

Please send feedback and bugs to karina@hyperreal.org

Regards,

Karina

> Saturday evening crept up & started passing by, I tried calling the 
> info line for Midnight recess and there was nothing at all. I actually 
> pulled over & thought for a few minutes before getting on the
> freeway once again. OH boy, what a dilemna.
> And then I still did not sense anything concrete. the next best thing 
> was to be rational & choose what was certain:) I mean there would be 
> hardcore there, but I saw it this way..maybe it was time for me to 
> give it a try:)

> And then I flew away to Oakland, I actually got lost trying to find
> Skills! I really & truly got lost due to some stupid block numbering. 
> down that street(Telegraph ave) So I went the wrong way and then it 
> was almost 9. Like 10 minutes to 9. And I was literally crying, I mean 
> I wanted to go, I did not want to be stranded & go to some stupid club 
> in the city!
> In sheer desperation, I kind of stopped every couple of blocks & asked
> every person I encountered about Skills! See I did not have their phone
> number either, silly me.
> And then, I saw this internet cafe, I thought maybe I could try there.
> The girl managing the store was so nice! She said, yes I could use her
> account & look for it. My fingers flew over the keyboard....and the
> strange thing was that Skills does not have a website with a phone
> number! 5 minutes to 9 & ticking....(the shop supposedly closed at 9)
> And finally, where do I find a number, in one of lines listed in a hit

> Relieved, I rushed over to her, again she was so awesome. She let me 
> use
> the phone and I dialed the digits. The clock said 9, and I was relieved

> directions, & said they would wait for me. Putting down the phone, I 
> was
> so relieved, I had a huge sigh of relief and there was a big big smile 
> on my face. If it werent for the counter behind which that girl was, I 
> would have given her a big hug. So all I said was thank you so much & 
> skipped out of the cafe.
> They gave me my ticket, & then there was this other guy there, he was 
> up
> here for Thanksgiving & was trying to figure on what party to go for.
> The Skills guy said there was exactly one more ticket left(for 
> Devotion)
> if he wanted it. He started thinking hard, & then he says but how do I 
> get there. Automatically it came from me, sure I can take you there & 
> then drop you off for your greyhound bus.
> He made up his mind & got the very last ticket. There was even more
> confusion to follow. When we called for directions from his cell, we
> could barely decipher it. The girl was speaking way too fast for us to
> pick it up. And then, he had this idea of going over to a coffee shop 
> he
> had been to around the uc berkeley campus. His reasoning was that there
> were plenty of people there and someone should know! He was going to 
> make someone listen to the directions and then ask them to help us heh 
> heh.
> And then, we get a hold of one of the guys managing the shop. He is all
> serious & then he goes gets someone else. So he kind of understands &
> tells us how to go about the first half.
> Truthfully, when I listened to it again (for a few times) it did become
> clear to me. I dont know who was recording on that, but they better not
> carry the theme of a hardcore party too far, making the directions 
> stick
> to that speed is not nice:):)
> Yay, we finally got there, only to find that this was a map point. And
> there were tons of people already waiting to be shuttled. People was
> desperately even looking for tix but there were none to be had.
> We somehow could sneak past the whole line, because when they called 
> for
> people to start getting in the back of one truck. No one started, & 
> then
> the girl in there looked at me & motioned us to go ahead. Haha , as we
> were getting in, she says if they dont start getting in, its their 
> fault.
> We had to lie down low to avoid being seen since there like 8? people 
> in
> the back. Oooh, that was so exciting. I was day dreaming that 
> hopefully we might see some action as in a cop chasing us. I am just 
> kidding.
> We arrived at the venue and we were quickly ushered inside.
> Oh yeah, it was a proper warehouse. There were tons of people, the
> lightening was quite garish. There had been a feeble attempt at
> decorations. I dont mean in a bad way, it just added to how the 
> ambience
> in there was. Yep, happy hardcore was ripping out of the speakers in 
> that main room. I did not see a lot of people dancing. Almost all of 
> them were standing around & hanging out. I went on to the other room, 
> I figured this was the trance/house room. It was even more crowded. 
> Was it Majere spinning when I got in? We must have got there like a 
> little bit before 11. I wanted to know who was playing when, but had 
> little luck in finding that out.
> Though I did get to know about some of the sets I really wanted
> to see. Miss Molly Mush was going to come on an hour or so later on.
> Yeah, I knew I had to check her out. Her mixing and of course her:)
> Frankly I have never been to any party which did have hardcore. This 
> was
> my first time, I did not know how it would go. I really thought it was 
> not meant for me. But anyway I wanted to try it out.
> I danced for a while in the house room, I got on the elevated space at 
> the back, to my delight I found the floor was wooden and it was truly 
> springy.
> Oh joy! this was the best floor I had been to. It had the right amount 
> of the tiniest spring which was good for jumping around.
> I had a good time dancing away on that platform till I somehow knew it 
> was time to go to the other room.
> I was really excited & agog with curiousity about my first exposure to
> hardcore. I slowly edged my way through the crowd(a very still standing
> crowd) to kind of in the front as someone before Molly was finishing up
> his set.  I have been to her website but did not care to glance much at
> pics so I did not recognize her till she stepped up.
> Everyone around me erupted in a cheer, I joined in. And then the music
> started flowing, the beats started building up, faster & faster. And 
> wow, I was actually dancing to it. Moving in time to the beat, equally 
> fast. I had always, always thought for long about how it would be 
> insane to keep up with that tempo. But this was wonderful, my body was 
> just doing it automatically. I did not really have to make too much 
> effort.
> So there I was, my feet not doing much(they would wear out so fast
> otherwise!) while from the waist up, I was a mini tornado. Twisting &
> turning & writhing & gyrating. My brain was overflowing with the lovely
> music and I was smiling. And at this point, I had an awesome 
> realisation.
> Yes!! I indeed do like happy hardcore, I fell in love with yet another
> style of electronika:):)!!! The music spun on, a couple of guys were 
> mcing while Molly spun. Oh yeah, they were so totally enthusiastic and 
> trying to urge the crowd on to some serious dancing. Too bad, still 
> most of them were just standing there. A handful of us were indeed 
> dancing though, that was cool. I found to my wonder, that I could just 
> keep going, I mean keep dancing at that tempo for as long as I wanted. 
> How fun! One of them(Cliff) , pointed at me and something about how I 
> was dancing so much and that I was hardcore. Something like that. I 
> was pleased.  Yep I was the dude dancing out there, in my "leave no 
> trace" ethics dark green t shirt.
> The cops came(they always have to huh) and for a few minutes the music 
> was turned down as they announced that they would shut the whole thing 
> down at 1! And then, they said they would let it go on if everyone 
> disposed their drinks, smokes,etc.  How cool, I mean I did not have to 
> deal with that, but atleast getting rid of the smoke in the air, I 
> would like that(not that I have anything against those people, its 
> just their own thing!)
> A collective roar went up from the crowd as the music started thumping 
> &
> shaking the room once again!  Oh yeah I did forget my earplugs that 
> night( how very dumb! I forgot to take em in a hurry)
> I loved Molly's set, it was too bad it was over quite soon. I hope I 
> get a chance to see her again sometime ! And there's another thing, 
> the way I was located, when she had her head slightly bent down while 
> mixing.
> I thought it was cool, the way I could not see her eyes, but only her
> eyelids and eyebrow. I aint being weird, that pose just struck me:)
> I cheered as she got done, I was going to go up say hi, but she
> apparently was in a hurry and so I did not go up as she headed out.
> But anyway, thanks to her, I am into happy hardcore!!!!!!!!!!!!!
> That I think was the best part of my night, the highest note.
> I left the room feeling so high. I went back to the other room and 
> stayed there for the rest of the night. I did want to see Valerie 
> Sparks, I dont think she did come?
> Back on the springy floor, I was jumping around, when this guy comes 
> up to me. I did not place him at first though he seemd familiar. It 
> was Dustin from my very first rave, ETA Neo Tokyo 3000!! It was grand 
> to see him.
> He had this kind of a turban hat on heh heh.  One of the tnings that 
> came up as we talked...I happened to ask if he knew who was spinning 
> right then. And he says, "I dont know, I am not here to see someone 
> specific spin, if I like the music, I just dance. I can dance to this 
> music anywhere, but raves are special because its only there that I > can
> experience the exact kind of atmosphere which is so perfect for 
> listening and dancing to that music."
> Maybe not his exact words, but that's what I kind of remember. I said 
> how true....how can I not keep going back; where else could I ever 
> find the vibe that existed there. And the whole ambience or aura or 
> atmosphere.
> Only to be found at raves like this!!!:) And I guess that's why I keep
> coming back time after time, from far, far away.
> My life would definitely have a void if I stopped or if I cant go 
> anymore.
> So, there was this girl dressed up like a cheerleader? I am bad at
> recognizing costumes. The people who were there will know what I mean, 
> the redhead in a white shirt & blue tie, a teeny weeny red skirt & 
> sexy laced white stockings. She was part of the crew & oh yeah , she 
> was so cheerful & playing her role to the hilt & loving every moment 
> of it. She would flit around from room to room, always smiling always 
> yelling out , shaking her lil butt & then flitting to another corner:) 
> I didnt even ask her name heh heh.
> Yeah, I met more awesome people, again I'm bad with names so dont 
> remember too much. There was this guy who maybe recognized me from my 
> postings & he says, are you crazy legs?  I said yeah, & he laughs & 
> says, I cant believe it, I met Crazy legs. He kept going on with that 
> for a few minutes. Neither sarcastically either, that was nice & funny 
> heh heh. Oh yeah, if he gets this, he better email me back because we 
> were talking about possible software jobs in Berkeley. Hey, write me 
> asap!!
> And from him, I came to know this was called the crackhouse.  He had
> bought a large couch kind of thing. He said he always brought 
> something or the other with him every time he went raving & left it 
> behind.
> I started tiring out as the night wore on, though I had to keep dancing
> because I was also waiting to hear the hard house spun by Denise.
> That was a fine set, she was mxing along with someone else. I dont know
> his name but he was good too. I really did try to dance hard, I guess
> somehow I carried on for that entire hour. Arrrgh, I really wanted to
> dance, but my body could not keep up the frenzy. I crashed down at the 
> end of that set, it was 3 in the morning.
> The crowd was thinning out, & I decided to take off. I knew I could 
> not go on anymore! I crashed in the car as usual, snuggling beneath my 
> sleeping bag. Then, I heard a knock on the window, it was Jeremy, he 
> was back too.
> There was a house party going on somewhere in So SF . I said let me 
> sleep & maybe I will be up for driving. Never happened heh heh, I 
> could not get up till like 6 or so.
> I dropped him off at the bus station and then headed over to The End 
> up.
> Once again I had fun dancing in there, this time getting worn out even
> quicker at maybe 2 in the afternoon.

--0-1073868875-1039109749=:51412
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii


If you're looking for somewhere to buy toys, visit www.givingtree.org 
This is The Salvation Army's online Giving Tree program.  Here's how it works:  you buy one of the toys on the website, then WalMart.com ships it to a Salvation Army community center in your neighborhood (based on your zip code).  From there, the toy you buy will be given to a needy child.  It's that simple. 
I don't know if SFRaves is planning any sort of toy drive of their own, but I couldn't resist this chance to plug givingtree.org.  It's a great program, and it's our first year doing it online.  
Happy Holidays!! 
Susan

The Ambient Mafia's Sinful Sag Soiree
Friday, Dec. 6

Jezebel's Joint
510 Larkin St. @ Turk, San Francisco

9:30-2
$3
21+

Hey kids!

Come celebrate a buncha Sagittarius birthdays with us as we unleash the
Ambient Mafia's Sinful Sag Soiree! Don't let the name fool ya - there
won't be much ambient this night, more like an assortment of deliciously
evil breaks, techno and house. And as anyone who's seen us in
all-too-rare action will attest, we know how to rumble ya ass!

For anyone who hasn't been there, Jezebel's is a really cool bar in the
city. Nicknamed 'the bar for doms & daddies, strippers & trannies' - a
perfectly decadent spot for the Mafia to celebrate all things Sag.

Hope to see you all there! Since this is a public party, feel free to
invite whoever you want ... especially sags!

Lineup:
Upstairs: Shane; Derek Fieldsoe; Michael, the Red Stickman

Downstairs Lounge: Zac, Harken, Boomerang Fidget, Skye, Speakeasy Ray

every year every cosmetics company puts out some holiday makeup.  what that means is that there are a bunch of new shades of both matte and sparkling girly things that are either not in your personal collection or just slight variations of what you might already have and shouldn't you have those too? or that brand too? and doesn't the case look nice too? and look at that! it looks like a museum display under glass with really pretty lighting...fine art for purchase! estee lauder has two such things right now...like two really nice collections with 2 or 3 three lipsticks in each set and each set has what you know you already have or don't really need but might like to try and some nice brushes which we could all use constantly and oh my gosh, how to pick just one and be satisfied? especially when one of the collections is soooooooooooooooo huge and is only $45.00 for all the stuff, but you have to buy a fragrance to get that one for that price, and i already have a few estee lauder perfumes and many other perfumes and oils, so i wasn't planning on buying any perfume, and i wasn't really planning on buying a whole bunch of their makeup considering that i have some things that i was planning on buying already from another makeup company...some basics that will cost me fine, but i will use them up at least and that is good.....oh my gosh!!!!! AND i was trying to talk myself out of the first estee lauder kit when i saw the second one today that comes in a little red bag too and of course really pretty lipstick and some other goodies. shit!  i was trying to talk myself out of it, and trying to convince myself that i don't need all of those eyeshadows, and then i found myself reading the french version of elle and i saw all sorts of pictures with THOSE colors or similar ones, and maybe i have those colors too, i probably do, but this is high-end makeup for cheap. SHIT, especially in the first package i was looking at...it has this shimmery beige/pink powder in there with a soft fluffy little estee lauder brush...SHIT. :)

Then the details for those who care to read:

Flux is going strong into its 8th month, and we're excited to bring in one
of the strongest forces in the SF scene as our guest, DJ Push [Future Breaks
FM, True Intent, XLR8R]. For the last umpteen years (that's a long time,
folks), this man has been quietly, methodically pushing the music scene in
all the right directions. Whether it be laying down the latest and greatest
breakbeat jams of all flavors for the KUSF radio airwaves (Future Breaks FM)
or rocking the crowds down at The Top for True Intent Saturdays or giving
you the latest dish in the ever-essential music rag, XLR8R -- Push comes
correct each and every time.  You know the deal: breaks vs. house/tech, low
cover, cheap, stiff drinks, patio, drunk people.

Stir-Fri-Day - With DJs Jason Fluid and Maneesh the
Twister plus weekly guests stirring beats & rhythms.
Stir-Fri-Day is a free gathering of friends and
strangers at a down-low crossroads gallery. Designed to
be a recurring occasion for mental, personal, and
spiritual expansion and expression, Stir-Fri-Day offers
a sensory collage to entice the soul into action.
Stir-Fri-Day has hosted more than 200 DJs and
performers in many musical and visual styles over the

(Percussion SF)

Heroine Please join us the second Friday night of the
month at Sno-Drift for our next dose of Heroine, an
all-female DJ line-up. The term heroine was originally
brought to India by Alexander The Great. The Ancient
Greeks used the word to describe those goddesses who
descended from the heavens to vanquish evil wherever it
was present in the mortal realm. These heroines are
still amongst us... We welcome the following goddesses

-------------------------------------------------------
Administrative Notes
-------------------------------------------------------

SFRaves serves the greater SF Bay Area, but reaches
beyond the local scene to all corners of the Terra
Firma - thanks to everyone whose support of and
contribution to the SFRAVES.org community - locally
--> to both poles ---> to all points along the
equator ---> as well as each longitude and latitude
perspective that makes this beautiful place we know
as Earth our home.

Please notify me regarding new events, event
changes, deprecated event information, or any other
information pertaining to events in the greater SF
Bay Area and beyond.

I look forward to hearing from you @
karina@hyperreal.org

THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every
week.

To subscribe to the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a message
to:  sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this
list:  sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or
sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

Faithfully yours, -- Karina Powers
karina@hyperreal.org

Copyright: All trademarks, product or service names,
brand names and/or logos appearing on
http://www.sfraves.org site, calendar and archives
are the property of their respective owners.

change the batteries and get the same effects of glowsticks. It's a cost

EzUP would rock for all night long illumination at a campout...

Subject: Re: [sfraves] glow stick alternative

On Thu, 5 Dec 2002, Rayn wrote:

> Man, you have to have a hardcore week of raving planned before you drop $50
> for two of these bad boys.  Definitely cool though.. they'd stay bright all
> night at least.

Well, me n my grrl own a whole bunch of coltronix streetlights. They are 
battery powered LED based glowsticks. They use camera batteries, which I 
don't think there is any way to recharge, but they are much brighter than 
any krill light I've seen so far

www.coltronix.net is the manufacturer, they have links to people who sell 
them.

   Cormac

Conservative Leader's Son Jailed In Road Rage Case

(CNSNews.com) - The son of a prominent Washington, D.C. conservative =
leader is scheduled to attend a hearing in federal court later this =
month after being arrested and charged with shooting at a driver. =20

Federal Magistrate Judge T. Rawls Jones, Jr., Friday scheduled a Dec. 17 =
hearing for David Michael Keene, son of American Conservative Union =
Chairman David A. Keene.

U.S. Park Police said the 21-year-old Keene was arrested Wednesday =
evening and is accused of firing a gun at another motorist while driving =
on a suburban Washington parkway last weekend.

Keene is scheduled to attend a preliminary and detention hearing on the =
17th , according to Sam Dibbley, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorneys =
Office in Alexandria, Virginia.

The preliminary and detention hearing will determine whether Keene will =
remain in his Alexandria, Va. jail cell and whether there is enough =
evidence for the case to proceed.=20

If there is sufficient evidence, the judge is expected to schedule a =
status hearing at which point, a trial date would be set.=20

Keene was being held Friday on federal charges involving "the use of a =
firearm during a crime of violence," according to U.S. Park Police Sgt. =
Scott Fear.

Fear said Keene allegedly shot a bullet into another car Dec. 1 while =
traveling along a stretch of the George Washington Memorial Parkway, =
shattering the car's rear window.=20

The bullet lodged in the driver's seat and came within inches of =
striking the driver, police said.

The driver of the other vehicle took down the license plate number of =
the car from which the shot was allegedly fired and called police, who =
later arrested Keene. Fear said a weapon was found in Keene's =
possession, but Fear declined to offer any information about it.

Keene's father, besides being chairman of the ACU, is also on the board =
of directors of the National Rifle Association, which said the group's =
thoughts and prayers go out to the Keene family, according to NRA =
spokesman Andrew Arulanandam.

"This matter is in the hands of law enforcement and if any laws are =
broken, it has to be dealt with just like any other case," Arulanandam =
said. "Celebrity parents have to deal with these issues all the time and =
during this difficult time, our hearts go out to the parents."

If convicted, Keene could face up to 10 years in prison.

E-mail a news tip to Jim Burns.



------=_NextPart_000_0005_01C29E22.55801810--

Subject: [sfraves] (BSP) Marvelous at POW! tonight

Be sure to stop by POW tonight for another installment of our monthly,
Marvelous!  You know the place; artwork from Sebaztien and Roderic
Crooks, playstations at the bar and a comic book theme.  Best of all,
there's no cover tonight.

This time around we're bringing in guest DJs H.O.P. (The Icons - hip-hop
and turntablism) and Kaution (hip-hop and house.)  Residents are Oliver
Orzal, DJ Balou and myself.  I'm planning on staying on the techy side
of house myself this time around, and it's hard to predict what Oliver
or Balou might be in the mood for any given time.

Hope to see you there.  More info can be found here:
http://www.sfstation.com/clubs/pow.htm#marvelous

Subject: [sfraves] nrr:sociopath president?

I found this really disturbing but still fascinating  I
shall be looking at Bush's verbal mistakes more
carefully. Interesting how he cannot verbalize feelings
that are not congruent with him to come out correctly.
It makes me wonder if I do that too.


Bush anything but moronic, according to author
Dark overtones in his malapropisms
MURRAY WHYTE -- ENTERTAINMENT REPORTER

When Mark Crispin Miller first set out to write
Dyslexicon:  Observations on a National Disorder", about
the ever-growing catalogue of President George W.
Bush's verbal gaffes, he meant it for a laugh. But what
he came to realize wasn't entirely amusing.

Since the 2000 presidential campaign, Miller has been
compiling his own collection of Bush-isms, which have
revealed, he says, a disquieting  truth  about what lurks
behind the cock-eyed leer of the leader of the free
world.
He's not a moron at all. On that point, Miller and
Prime Minister Jean Chretien agree.

But according to Miller, he's no friend.

"I did initially intend it to be a funny book. But that
was before I  had a chance to read through all the
transcripts," Miller, an American author and a
professor of culture and communication at New York
University, said recently in Toronto.

"Bush is not an imbecile. He's not a puppet. I think
that Bush is a sociopathic personality. I think he's
incapable of empathy. He has an inordinate sense
of  his own entitlement, and he's a very skilled
manipulator. And in all the snickering about his alleged
idiocy, this is what a lot of people miss."

Miller's judgment, that the president might suffer from
a bona fide personality disorder, almost makes one long
for the less menacing nbotion currently making the
rounds: that the White House's current occupant is, in
fact,  simply an
idiot.

If only.  Miller's rendering of the president is
bleaker than that.  In studying Bush's various adventures
in oration, he started to see a pattern emerging.

"He has no trouble speaking off the cuff when he's
speaking punitively, when he's talking about violence,
when he's talking about revenge.

"When he struts and thumps his chest, his syntax and
grammar are fine," Miller said. "It's only when he leaps
into the wild blue yonder of  compassion, or idealism, or
altruism, that he makes these hilarious mistakes."

While Miller's book has been praised for its "eloquence"
and "playful use of language," it has enraged Bush
supporters.

Bush's ascent in the eyes of many Americans - his
approval rating hovers at near 80 percent - was the
direct result of tough talk following the Sept.11
terrorist attacks. In those speeches, Bush stumbled not
at all; his language of retribution was clear.

It was a sharp contrast to the pre-9/11 George W. Bush.

Even before the Supreme Court in 2001 had to intervene
and rule on recounts in Florida after a contentious
presidential election, a corps of journalists were
salivating at the prospect: a bafflingly inarticulate man
in a position of power not seen  since vice-president Dan
Quayle rode shotgun on George H.W. Bush's one term
in office.

But equating Bush's malapropisms with Quayle's
inability to spell "potato" is a dangerous assumption,
Miller says.

At a public address in Nashville, Tenn., in September,
Bush provided one of his most memorable stumbles.  Trying
to give strength to his case that  Saddam Hussein had
already deceived the West concerning his store of
weapons,
Bush was scripted to offer an old saying: Fool me once,
shame on you.  Fool me twice, shame on me. What came out
was the following:  "Fool me once, shame ...shame
on ... you."  Long, uncomfortable pause. "Fool
me....can't get fooled again!"

Played for laughs everywhere, Miller saw a darkness
underlying the gaffe. "There's an episode of Happy Days,
where The Fonz has to say, 'I'm  sorry' and can't do it.

Same thing,"  Miller said.

"What's revealing about this is that Bush could not
say, 'Shame on me' to save his life. That's a completely
alien idea to him. This is a guy who is absolutely proud
of his own inflexibility and rectitude."

If what Miller says is true - and it would take more
than just observations to prove it - then Bush has
achieved an astounding goal.

By stumbling blithely along, he has been able to push
his image as "just folks" - a normal guy who screws up
just like the rest of us.

This, in fact, is a central cog in his image-making
machine, Miller  says: Portraying the wealthy scion of
one of America's most powerful families as a regular,
imperfect Joe.

But the depiction, Miller says, is also remarkable for
what it hides - imperfect, yes, but also detached,
wealthy and unable to identify with the  "folks" he's
been designed to appeal to.

An example, Miller says, surfaced early in his
presidential tenure. "I know how hard it is to put food
on your family," Bush was quoted as saying.

"That wasn't because he's so stupid that he doesn't
know how to say, 'Put food on your family's table.' It's
because he doesn't care about people who can't put food
on the table," Miller says.

So, when Bush is envisioning "a foreign-handed foreign
policy," or observes on some point that "it's not the way
that America is all about," Miller contends it's because
he can't keep his focus on things that mean  nothing to
him.

"When he tries to talk about what this country stands
for, or about democracy, he can't do it," he said.

This, then, is why he's so closely watched by his
handlers, Miller says - not because he'll say something
stupid, but because he'll overindulge in  the
language of violence and punishment at which he excels.

"He's a very angry guy, a hostile guy. He's much like
Nixon.  So they're very, very careful to choreograph
every move he makes.  They don't want him anywhere near
protestors, because he would lose his temper."

Miller, without question, is a man with a mission - and
laughter isn't it.

"I call him the feel bad president, because he's all
about punishment and death," he said. "It would be a
grave mistake to just play him for laughs."

Santa's Black Market at SomArts in SF.  CFDC is a group of underground
designers and fabric sculptors who relish in the bliss of the abnormal.

performance that will take you on a journey to distant lands and beyond.

Subject: [sfraves] (m)utterings at the end of a working day. happy mondays all.

--0-1468440893-1039460335=:10712
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit


I am from Jersey, Channel Isles. It is a small little Island by France, which is in Europe. You can see France on a nice day, and some of the old folk have these funny english/french accents. You can walk around the whole island in a day, it's only 45 miles square. The kids however are bang into dance culture, having plenty of nice old castles to set up raves in, and and a seemingly endless supply of cash to party with.  (thanks daddy)
Ross' top 6 list of famous jersey boys in house. 
1. Guru Josh.  Used to be called the Animal and was famous for his "Pervert's Ball's" long before his house days. Fed up of late 80's bored new romantic types, he decides to create the best sax solo on a house record ever, by releasing Infinity, and rereleasing it every year, until there are indeed, infinite copies. 
2. Lee Mullin.  Lucky Lonzo, the quiet kid in my class, once came skiing and broke his arm, upon return from the cruel slopes he was gifted the news his dog died. Bored with being the butt of everyones jokes he decided to become famous for wearing white suits and being the keyboard player for HYBRID. Then toured the world and won best live act 2001 for there performance in IBiza. He now only gets out of bed if the supermodel he shares it with decides that yes, $10,000 is Ok for a days work. 
3. James Reynolds. Forbidden to inherit his father's title "Lord Reynolds" by tony blairs UK government, James decides that London still needs him, so he remixes "a rose is still a rose" for Aretha Franklin and along with Mat Jam Lamont and freinds invents UK 2 step garage. 
4. Andy Chatterley. Always the pale kid, we certainly wondered what was going on with chatters at all times. Keyboard to Mark Laws guitar in local band Hunt the Dark Knight, the teenager discovers original acid house, turns left at greenland, then heads to London to be a part of the free party movement, and was envied by all. Turns up as engineer on Eddie Lock record after keeping himself busy by being missing for over 10 years. 
5. Ilker Ulkan (the turk.) Kept Jersey scene buzzing very nicely. Jealousy forces him to leave Jersey, so he goes to Slinky with Gaz White and get's job flying aroung the bloody world buying new trainers, so he can seriously flout the "No Sportswear" rule at UK clubs.Nice One.  

6. Me. After being gifted by god at being not good at really anything in particular, ross stumbles through life shamelessly self promoting himself and his freinds. This leads to interest from the majors, who set out to cut this rough diamond into a commodity with eventual corporate salary. What voodoo helped this publicist get cushty deskjob and plasma screen to boot? Could it be that his work output is minimal, yet done with a smile. Or is it simply that he is the luckiest lad in la la land.

From sfraves-return-96645-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org Mon Dec 09 19:07:14 2002
Return-Path: <sfraves-return-96645-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org>
Delivered-To: sfraves-archive@hyperreal.org
Received: (qmail 11183 invoked by uid 1103); 9 Dec 2002 19:07:12 -0000
Mailing-List: contact sfraves-help@hyperreal.org; run by ezmlm

list-post: <mailto:sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Delivered-To: mailing list sfraves@hyperreal.org
Received: (qmail 11156 invoked from network); 9 Dec 2002 19:07:12 -0000
X-Originating-IP: [132.241.246.179]
From: "crazy legs" <waltzingvish@hotmail.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Cc: sacraves@hyperreal.org
Bcc: 
Date: Mon, 09 Dec 2002 11:07:16 -0800
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
Message-ID: <F144diAG95OIKaOSbsS00020f0a@hotmail.com>
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 09 Dec 2002 19:07:17.0030 (UTC) FILETIME=[30BC3460:01C29FB6]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] Sac dances at ETD3!

Yeah, so the other people picked me up late as usual. I knew we would not 
get there before 10 haha. I hoped I would not miss out on who I wanted to 
see!
I slept most of the way in the car, because I had slept so little the
previous night, didnt go to bed till 4 or so heh heh.
Satoshi, the Japanese dude & Yong , a chinese guy were both hardcore
ravers. Satoshi had started way back, he has been all over the country
since maybe 6 or 7 years back while the other guy had started a little bit 
before I did.
They were very excited that they had met me , so now they knew someone
else who they could go with. Well, the feeling was mutual. Though I said , I 
did not know if I would be here next semester. But we'll be in touch, they 
insisted that I call them whenever I get back. That I definitely will! The 
car was built pretty rave ish too, it had blinking lights on the outside & 
more stuff. They played thumping trance all the way. Not that I minded, I 
was too busy sleeping:)
We finally got there a little bit before 10. It was soooo cold, as we
hurried to the venue. It turned out to be a huge ballroom, which was very 
nice. There was a good wooden floor to dance & jump on , all night long, 
yay!
The decorations were there and so was the crowd. Oh well, the crowd was
always there at Sac parties. This would be the clincher, I would know
finally whether Sac ravers actually wiggled their asses.
I saw the lineup, & I was pleased that the dj's I wanted to see had not
come on yet.
There was like 5 minutes left before it was time for Valerie Sparks!
I was sooo hyper about seeing her, after how much I loved dancing to Molly 
at Devotion!  Oh yeah baby, I was jumping up & down and moving in time to 
the beats that spun out of her magical fingers.
Every now & then, she would look up at the crowd & wave her hands in the
air and urge us on to dance even harder. She has a very lovely smile.
A couple of times during the hour she looked at me directly & smiled. And I 
melted away into the ground like the liquid mercury man does in
Terminator2. Except  I just flowed all around, dancing a crazy rhythm of
my own.  The intense feeling that raged inside me only served to make me
realise even more how much fun I was having. Hey, I also found that I did 
not have to keep up with the beat as long as I was in sync with it heh heh
Yeah, the other part of that hour, Micro was good too.
I glanced around me now & then, & who do I see. Someone very familiar...I 
keep seeing her at the Sac raves, it was Terri! She looked sooo hot:) I went 
over to give her a big hug. She was there, getting her groove on alright!
Too bad, the hour flew by so fast. But it was good it did too, because I
would have completely worm myself out otherwise.
I think the last one that Valerie spun was "love you down"? I think that
is a really neat song.  She walked off the stage & I went over to say hi.
I hugged her, & said I really enjoyed her set. She says, thank you for
coming out here. And then she was gone.
At this point, they had jungle/turntablism going on, this was my chance to 
catch my breath before Dina rips everything up once again!
I went and sat down on the stage where Terri was in a chair.
I was foolish once again to forget my earplugs in the car! so I wanted to 
not expose myself as much as often to the loud volume.
It was fun hanging out with Terri, she massaged my shoulders a wee bit as I 
sat there on the floor. She said she could feel lots of knots on my
shoulders. I said, yeah it must be, because I also dance so much ballroom, 
where I had to keep a frame. The jungle music was not bad at all.
Terri said she could totally get lost in the hypnotic rhythms it could
induce. I had to agree with that.
This is kind of funny, I always viewed jungle as something off limits to
me, the same thought as hardcore. But I was beginning to change, I could
see her point there. She went off to dance some to it, but I still rested 
for a while. The beats were pretty awesome, I just did not like it that the 
mc was shrieking over that volume. It hurt my ears at times. Maybe they 
ought to take a note of that.
Oooh oooh oooh, it was almost witching hour, I saw Dina come in & I went
up to talk to her a little bit. It was so good to see her again, the last 
time was Alchemy? Ha this time she had hair styled differently, it looked 
cool:)
I think at some point that night, she asked me what I thought of
Sac now, I said hell yeah, they do dance and this was a great party.
Soon, it was time for Dina & Denise. Ooh , this was going to be so
heavenly, I shot off straight to the bathroom so I didnt have to go
anytime in the next hour heh heh.
And then, it was time....Denise started it all off. The crowd adored her
as I did too. Even though it was my first time seeing her spin, I already 
knew I loved it. At different points where the music would fade a wee bit, 
she would raise her hands  and everyone on the floor would do that too. Me 
too!  Oye, & then Dina stepped up. Oh yeah, I yelled and I screamed as much 
as my lungs would allow me too. There she was, her agile fingers all in a 
flurry flying over the decks and her body grooving at the same time. Dead 
cool (& hard) beats pounded out of the speakers(there were a few speakers 
right there in the middle along with the usual left & right box of them) and 
I was dancing even harder.
I did not mention, when I was standing there right before Dina's set, I
had my hands plugging my ears as I stood there waiting for her to start.
I felt a tap on my shoulder, & this girl gave me a couple of ear plugs.
They were the ones that kind of stick when you press it against the ear
canal. I was so glad, I was very grateful to her for that. And I dont even 
know her name, didnt see her later on either.
Back to the music, they were throwing goodies into the crowd sometime into 
the set. So yeah, that made things even livelier. The crowd went crazy 
trying to catch everything out there in the air. They threw glowing rings 
first, I tried to catch some, but I didnt. And then, the guy who was 
throwing them, looked straight at me & aimed & I got one. Later on I knew 
this was dj scepter. I put this glowing ring on my head as in like a wreath 
or laurel and kept dancing. Someone later on that night, took it away from 
me because he said he would give me a buck. I said oh yeah, I'll take that!  
Speaking of that, I saw a recent post about battery charged alternatives, I 
thought that would be neat to get at some point.
Did I say something about the crowd, oh my gosh, the floor was sooooo
packed like sardines in a tin can. And everyone was dancing like crazy!!
They also threw more stuffed animals & other stuff. I was just dancing, I 
did not want any of that heh heh. One negative aspect of this was that, it 
drew some people out there in front who were just there to catch all those 
things. They were really rude & this one guy literally tried shoving me to 
the side so he could stand there & grab something!  No that could not make 
me angry, no way was anyone ruining my day, (rather night)
Well, all these people faded away once they stopped tossing stuff, and
then the floor belonged to the dancing fools:)
Everytime Dina came back or did something, I would be there, waving my
hands madly and shouting & cheering her on. I tried jumping really high at 
times, but found that it wore me out if I did it too often heh heh.
That hour was the best part of the night for me. I totally wore myself out 
dancing madly. Yeah, I could have paced myself for the rest of the night.
But how could I resist when Dina spun like that???
Oh yeah, while I was sittting there with Terri before Dina's set, I was
talking to her about nye, I didnt know what to do. I did not like the idea 
of Coolworld too much because I fear it will be too massive & anyway more 
importantly the vibe...it might be so different. Terri said go to Seattle! 
heh heh. And now I cant get it out of my head, contemplating the wild & 
impossible.
There was a roar that went up around the room when Dina & Denise were
done, & I joined in. After that it was Tom Slik & then Scepter. I danced
for a little while, and then I knew I had to take a break soon.
Dina was throwing rather sprinkling water on the heads that were dancing by 
the stage. Aaah, the cool water must have felt nice!
Which was alright  because Mystre/Dyloot were coming on. I went and sat
down at the very back of the room while they came on. I did not go dance
for any part of their set. It was exactly the same old stuff that I heard 
before at Wish and then some at Popsikle.
To quote Terri, its like pop
radio, they play the same songs over & over and there is this certain
group of people that never seem to get enough of it.  That's not me!
Yes, the first time was awesome @popsikle. That will always have a place
in my heart. here's hoping they will change sometime, even thought the
hope right now will be futile.
Terri teaches and it was so funny when she said, that she never sees any
of her students out there while she always dances. I think its awesome. I 
wish I had that life. That way I could be around school and still get away & 
party.
I saw Britty another raver from earlier raves, she slipped on yet another 
piece of candy onto my wrist:)
I went up in front to dance for the summerhayes, they were pretty decent.
Yes, the crowd was fading, I mean getting smaller. Still I danced, Dina
came up to me sometime during that set, to say she was leaving.
We bid adieu & I wonder if I shall ever see her spin again? Because I am
gone(maybe for a long long time?) after nye...I am really sad about that.
I was soo tired when it was 4 am, I could not stay for the last set.
The people with me felt the same so we took off.
Halfway back home, a tire went flat. they found that someone had slashed
it back there , when it was parked for the night. How weird, I thought
something like that would more likely happen in Oakland or something but
not there. And it was so silly, that the car did not even have a spare.
I didnt know whether to laugh or what haha.  We drove on that flat tire
for , I dont know maybe 5 miles or was it 15? I was sleeping so I dont
remember much except the constant rattling of the car. They managed to get
it fixed somewhere, lucky them that it did not screw up the rim.
So I got home at 10 and then drifted away....

vj

The Benefits of Water
75% of Americans are chronically dehydrated.

In 37% of Americans, the thirst mechanism is so weak that it is often
mistaken for hunger.

Even MILD dehydration will slow down one's metabolism as much as 3%.

One glass of water shuts down midnight hunger pangs for almost 100%of =
the
dieters studied in a U-Washington study.
Lack of water is the #1 trigger of daytime fatigue.

Preliminary research indicates that 8-10 glasses of water a day could
significantly ease back and
joint pain for up to 80% of sufferers.

A mere 2% drop in body water can trigger fuzzy short-term memory, =
trouble
with basic math, and difficulty focusing on the computer screen or on a
printed page.

Drinking 5 glasses of water daily decreases the risk of colon cancer by =
45%,
plus it can slash the risk of breast cancer by 79%, and one is 50%
less likely to develop bladder cancer.

Are you drinking the amount of water you should every day?


Of course, too much water may have strange side effects  =AD

Wow, great article.  I just got over some kidney stones so I've been doing 
alot more research on stuff myself.  From what my doctor said its not really 
how much you drink a day because some people retain more than others.  Its 
all personal.  Some can get by with 6, some need alot more.  Too much of 
course depletes electrolytes.

What he said is more important, at least in keeping your system running 
clean is you should be peeing 2 - 3 quarts of fluid a day.  Drink 4-6 
overall but if you're not getting rid of enough, drink more.

As for me, I've recently been having one of those Odwalla Superfood's every 
morning.  I have a can of Mt. Dew (used to drink a 12er or 2 a day easy) in 
the morning and then a superfood when I get to work.  This stuff is more 
amazing than coffee and red bull combined when you start drinking it 
regularly.  I've had more energy lately than I've had in years.  So now I 
have a soda in morning and at night for taste, then superfood and water 
throughout the day. :)

-Rayn



From: "Happy" <happy@happycandykid.com>
To: "SFRaves" <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Subject: [sfraves] NRR: The Benefits Of Water
Date: Mon, 9 Dec 2002 12:52:28 -0800

The Benefits of Water
75% of Americans are chronically dehydrated.

In 37% of Americans, the thirst mechanism is so weak that it is often
mistaken for hunger.

Even MILD dehydration will slow down one's metabolism as much as 3%.

One glass of water shuts down midnight hunger pangs for almost 100%of the
dieters studied in a U-Washington study.
Lack of water is the #1 trigger of daytime fatigue.

Preliminary research indicates that 8-10 glasses of water a day could
significantly ease back and
joint pain for up to 80% of sufferers.

A mere 2% drop in body water can trigger fuzzy short-term memory, trouble
with basic math, and difficulty focusing on the computer screen or on a
printed page.

Drinking 5 glasses of water daily decreases the risk of colon cancer by 45%,
plus it can slash the risk of breast cancer by 79%, and one is 50%
less likely to develop bladder cancer.

Are you drinking the amount of water you should every day?


Of course, too much water may have strange side effects  ­

From: "Happy" 
To: "SFRaves" 
Subject: [sfraves] NRR: The Benefits Of Water
Date: Mon, 9 Dec 2002 12:52:28 -0800

The Benefits of Water
75% of Americans are chronically dehydrated.

In 37% of Americans, the thirst mechanism is so weak that it is often
mistaken for hunger.

Even MILD dehydration will slow down one's metabolism as much as 3%.

One glass of water shuts down midnight hunger pangs for almost 100%of the
dieters studied in a U-Washington study.
Lack of water is the #1 trigger of daytime fatigue.

Preliminary research indicates that 8-10 glasses of water a day could
significantly ease back and
joint pain for up to 80% of sufferers.

A mere 2% drop in body water can trigger fuzzy short-term memory, trouble
with basic math, and difficulty focusing on the computer screen or on a
printed page.

Drinking 5 glasses of water daily decreases the risk of colon cancer by 45%,
plus it can slash the risk of breast cancer by 79%, and one is 50%
less likely to develop bladder cancer.

Are you drinking the amount of water you should every day?


Of course, too much water may have strange side effects &shy;

>Excerpt from Dave at 1015 and a PRNewswire article on Circus..
> http://www.deciblast.org/forums/viewtopic.php?t=724

"The agent stated that according to the DEA guidelines Ten15 is a rave due
to the late night operations, the presence of glow sticks, loud techno
music, the presence of EMT's and excessive sales of water."

I wish there was some way to figure out what the fuck the DEA is thinking
here, exactly. Get rid of techno music? That's a freedom-of-expression
issue, the government can't pull that kind of shit. Stop selling water?
It's as though no one can do right by these people - you drink too much,
they're on your ass for public drunkeness. Drink too little, you /must/ be
high. The glowstick thing is just absurd. I fail to see how any of this
doesn't fall under the category of "circumstancial evidence." Places like
1015 try to do right by their patrons by providing EMT's and water and
various other services, and they end up getting slapped down anyway.

Seems like the exective branch of the government has a bug up their ass
about people dancing all night and choosing forms of recreation that are
either outside the law, can't be regulated/taxed/risk-assessed for
insurance purposes, or don't represent a desirable target market for
advertisers.

This is, of course, absurd and if I were the operators of 1015 and other 
public venues I would seek the advice of good attorneys as well as support 
from the ACLU.  The oppression has begun once again.  I have no desire to 
see the clubs go away, although my dancing these days is mostly 
underground.  But this is just "level one."  If they knock out all public 
dancing in this country using these guidelines, then they will move to any 
party where there is electronic music available at "unreasonable" hours 
(10:00 PM?).

BTW, I wonder what constitutes "excessive sales of water?"  Would they 
prefer people drink more booze?  Ahhh....it's all fuckin' crazy, and the 
direction of this country is really making me think about getting the hell 
out before the black SUVs arrive at my door.  Heil Bush!!!
