Subject: Re: [sfraves] 1015/Circus visited by ABC... 1015 bans glowsticks

Oh my god that makes me sick.  Not only are they making normal things 
paraphenelia, they're the things I USE SOBER TO STAY UP ALL NIGHT!  This is 
such BS.  I'm not saying 1015 Circus wasn't in the wrong here, I mean hell.  
If you have employees having 10k pills confiscated then they deserve to be 
jailed and I'm surprised they didn't have door security at the club.  It 
sounds like they had it coming but that doesn't change the fact that us 
people who don't partake in illegal substances (often, I'm not saying I 
don't) on a regular basis need to suffer the lock down on the things we use 
to keep us going.

I go out sober from illegal things 95% of the time.  Hell, I only drink 
about 50% of the time. If I do choose to be on something when I go out, I 
take it before I go in or get to the party.  Not only do I not want to get 
in trouble during a search, I don't want the venue owner to get in trouble 
for me being caught doing it inside by someone who doesn't work there and 
have it shut down for them.  As for the smaller intimate clubs that look the 
other way for the bay areas non-drug drug Miss Mary, I still feel paranoid 
doing it in someone elses place of business for their sake.

And as nice a guy as I like to think I am I have no sympathy for dealers at 
events that get caught.  They endanger the party and state of the whole 
scene for us.  I'm hypocritical to a point because I have bought at parties 
before, just usually not for myself and I feel bad about having done it now 
as well because its irresponsible for the scenes sake.

Do not take this for me not liking people who go to parties blasted out of 
their minds, thats how they like to party and I can't judge them for that.. 
but please just be responsible and don't put the party and promoter in 
danger.  I don't hate the dealers either, its just when they have trouble 
with the man, it spills over onto the rest of us as well.

Be a scout.  Be prepared for your party ;)

-Rayn

At 04:53 PM 12/9/2002 -0800, Mike Migurski wrote:

>What I find wierdest about these kinds of misconceptions is that they
>basically ignore all normal standards of human rationality. "Someone can
>dose you" ... "A cooling off area staffed by EMT's" ... "too much water."

If all this could be addressed with reason and logic, Mike, there would be 
no oppression.  The roots of this social control lie far beyond the pale of 
reason.  Real issues in the country -- the economy, unemployment, poverty 
and the like -- are not being addressed efficiently.  Instead we have a 
government waging war on various folks, including us, to divert attention 
from problems they are not prepared to solve.  Corporations own most of the 
public press.  Corporate interests are more and more in line with 
government interests.  Mussolini defined Fascism as the merger of corporate 
and national interests.

Beyond this logic, there is the ongoing and deep fear in this Puritan 
culture of pleasure and any non-productive activity.  This is nothing new, 
and has served as the basis for much oppression and persecution.  We have 
merely substituted science for sin, and use unsubstantiated "scientific" 
beliefs and manipulated statistics and other data to recreate the Puritan 
state which, to my mind, was, and can be again, every bit as oppressive as 
the Taliban.



>I guess it's fairly obvious that none of these people have ever had the
>pleasure of dancing in a hot sweaty club, and the needs that it entails:
>proper hydration, and a bit of rest once in a while. If they think our
>motives are so out of whack, they must really think that we are in some
>fundamental way /different/ from them, and therefore probably undeserving
>of rights, respect, or human dignity.

Fear brings suspicion of any deviation from the norm.  We have agreed as a 
nation to forgo freedom for security.  The results are just beginning to be 
manifest.

Love,

Apollo

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii

Do you LICK your envelopes ????

This is a true story reported on CNN
If you lick your envelopes...You won't anymore!!!! A
woman was working in a post office in California. One day she
licked the envelopes and postage stamps instead of using a sponge. That
very day, the lady cut her tongue on the envelope. A week later, she
noticed an abnormal swelling of her tongue.

She went to the doctor, and they found nothing
wrong. Her tongue was not sore or anything. A couple of days later,
her tongue started to swell more, and it began to get really sore, so
sore, that she could not eat. She went back to the hospital, and
demanded
something be done. The doctor took an x-ray of her tongue,and noticed a
lump.

He prepared her for minor surgery.
When the doctor cut her tongue open, a live roach
crawled out. There were roach eggs on the seal of the envelope.
The egg was able to hatch inside of her tongue,
because of her saliva. It was warm and moist.

Andy Hume wrote:
Hey, I used to work in an envelope factory. You
wouldn't believe the.....things that float around in
those gum applicator trays. I haven't licked an envelope for
years.

To All:
I used to work for a print shop 32 years ago and we
were told NEVER to lick the envelopes. I never understood why
until I had to go into storage and pull out 2500 envelopes that were
already printed for a customer who was doing a mailing and saw several
squads of
roaches roaming around inside a couple of boxes with eggs everywhere.
They
eat the glue on the envelopes. I think print shops have a harder time
controlling
roaches than a restaurant. I always buy the self sealing type. Or
if need be I use a glue stick to seal one that has the type of glue
that
needs to be wet to stick.


PLEASE PASS THIS ON!!!! STOP DOING IT




God Bless!    Love, your sister in Christ, Tami

I once got roaches in my ears from hearing too much commercial trance at a
party.  The cheese in the beats attract roaches, who then lay their eggs
in the grooves (scientists have proven that the grooves trigger the part
of the abdomen that triggers egg laying behavior in female and type II
hermaphroditic roaches) and then those eggs are amplified over the sound
system, causing anybody within reach to risk infection.

This also happened (well something similar) in Pittsburgh at a party
called "The Journey Continues pt. IV".  Said Samuel Rollins, the promoter
"Mars was playing closing his set with that Pachabel track and everybody
started feeling antennae tickling around in their ears... we didn't
realize till later... that track is so cheesy that the roaches were
hatching at unheard of rates."  He continues, eyes growing wide from the
intensity of the memory "It was late in the party, some people had trouble
figuring out if it was really happening".  Similar complaints stemmed from
a playing of "A fifth of Beethoven", a popular classical dance music
remake from disco's dying days at an underground disco event in lower
Manhattan almost 25 years before.

In other parts of the world, changes in music and local flora and fauna
often result in strange distortions of this disturbing scientific
anamoly... like an outbreak last year of "kutiz", an indigenous Yemenese
insect with four sphincters around each of it's three eyes after a local
DJ played a Mushroom Jazz through Microsoft's secure IIS server after
eating Taco Bell followed by some herbal viagra at a local American hotel
complex that employs date rape drugged slave labor.

If you add your name to the top (do not cheat, break the chain and we all
lose!  Margaret Hemmins of Muscogee, Oklahoma did this and got hit by a
boat on a trailer in front of a bar just 32 days later!) and send five
dollars and this mail to the LAST five people on the list.

Lots of people have already won!  All you have to do is send your money to
the names at the top, put their names and your name at the bottom, and
wait for your millions to come in!  Practically the only thing you can do
to screw this up is send a crosspost message to several hundred people
warning of a silly urban legend!

(Tami, I think you meant well, but that story is a tad far fetched...
good ways to check up on a story like this before sending include
checking CNN's website, or looking up "roaches eggs envelope glue" at
Google.com)

Find out more at:
http://www.cnet.com/techtrends/0-7311128-8-7141601-1.html

> demanded

> lump.
>

1015 always had the best glowsticks. this is true: i
must have mentioned this before: i once had a 1015
glowstick that glowed bright for at least a
week....bright like the night sky before the
rain...one of my favorite colors....i can't and refuse
to believe that people who spend any time whatsoever
in san francisco don't notice anything besides what is
in the brain up there....it makes me think that people
go to the wearhouse and no where else, and that is
probably the case....the computer, the wearhouse, and
don't even look around and notice anyone or anything
but where the car is parked...maybe watch out for some
isolated bugs or something like that, and then head
directly for the nearest greasyspoon and wolf down
some sort of fair in routine mindless fashion. your
completely missing out, if this is the case...it is
also common knowledge amongst police forces
nationwide, the going rate for an ecstacy pill or an
eighth of maryjane, street value, that is.....i
understand and see quite clearly that many youngsters
(of course, i use that word in total nerdom.....give
me a frigg'in break...when does anyone get to the
point where they can use a word like youngsters and
not also simultaneously be wearing some sort of, oh,
mid-leg length shorts made out of polyester and maybe
some knee-hi athletic socks...it's the weekend attire
for the middle-aged, i suppose, and it goes with
youngsters...that and a baseball cap of some sort that
has a predominating color that directly clashes with
the shorts....young'ins)....anyway though, something
that you might consider is that your money goes a lot
farther than you might think, as i continually try to
put forth, and that you might consider some other ways
to gain satisfaction in your life that your current
group of friends might not....you don't have to paint
your face...how about canvas instead? have you ever
once stepped inside of an art supply shop? why not go
totally techie while your at it? do you see my
point?...if you can actually read and follow this,
besides the fact that i have a way with words, it has
a lot to do with the good fortune that your brain
chemistry is in good working order...shouldn't you
keep it that way? :)

Hey guys, i know this is completely off the wall... BUT.... I'm hoping there is a super-nerd lurking on this list...  I know there are sum heavy duty unix gurus on this list... maybe there are some other folks that deal with the crap that they call windows...

I'm developing some software for a chemistry lab.  At this lab is a windows 2000 server that runs the lan in the office as well as some more important shit.

Twice the active directory in this server has taken a dump, both times leaving no users with "logon from the network" rights.  A friend of mine found me a fix for this problem, but after applying the fix this time, the server was left in a strange state.

It thinks its just fine, however the only machines that can log into it are other active directory machines.  The server is running in mixed mode and up until yesterday, all of the win98 and NT4 boxes had no problem logging into the server.  After fixing the active directory, they can't.  They can see the domain, but when trying to access it, they say there is either no domain controller or the uber cryptic "the domain controller is not setup for transactions".

Has anybody on this experienced this problem?  If not, does anybody on here have any familiarity with the legacy networking in win2k? Could this be a problem in the repaired group policy template or is it completely unrelated?

[and please no cracks from the peanut gallery about how windows sux... I KNOW DIS]

If anybody knows anything about this problem or where i could go look for answers...please help me :)  

I know its a simple solution and we just need a temporary work around (for a month or so).  If this would involve setting up a temporary backup domain controller for the win2k domain (that doesn't have a hosed active directory) or anything cheesy like that.. I just need something that works :)

keep it wet & hard...

p a t

	charset="iso-8859-1"

X-Priority: 3
X-MSMail-Priority: Normal
X-Mailer: Microsoft Outlook Express 6.00.2800.1106
X-MimeOLE: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE V6.00.2800.1106
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Windows 2000 Problems

Can you please give more info? It sounds like you only have 1 domain
controller. That in itself is bad news as you have found out. How many
clients (NT, 98 and/or 2K) are on this domain? You only need to run in mixed
mode if you have NT BDC's, otherwise you can run in native mode. Your
downlevel clients (ie NT and 98) need WINS in order to properly participate
in the domain, which can be run from the domain controllers. Can you remove
the NT clients from the domain and re-add them? You mentioned Group Policy.
What modifications have been made to the Default Group Policy or other GPs?

Happy  :-)

PS Feel free to respond to me off the list.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: NRR: Windows 2000 Problems

Actually, you can use NT BDC's with AD, as long as it's still in mixed mode.
One of the AD domain controllers holds the role of PDC emulator. As far as
the BDCs are concerned, they are domain controllers on a NT4 network. This
is an easy way to do an NT to AD migration. Upgrade your PDC to Win2K and
make it the first AD DC. If there is a problem, you can shut down the AD DC
and promote the BDC and be right back where you started.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: NRR: Windows 2000 Problems

Let's say you have a legacy application that uses SQL 7 on NT4, and cannot
use SQL 2000. You can run AD in mixed mode with NT BDCs for the SQL server
to communicate with. To use AD to it's fullest, the clients have to be
running 2K or XP, and these should be using DNS to find the closest copy of
the Global Catalog. Whoof!

As an out-of-work NT super-nerd, I have way too much free time on my hands,
as shown by the amount of energy I've put into this thread! Lol!

>
> > Actually, you can use NT BDC's with AD, as long as it's still in mixed
> mode.
> > One of the AD domain controllers holds the role of PDC emulator. As far
as
> > the BDCs are concerned, they are domain controllers on a NT4 network.
This
> > is an easy way to do an NT to AD migration. Upgrade your PDC to Win2K
and
> > make it the first AD DC. If there is a problem, you can shut down the AD
> DC
> > and promote the BDC and be right back where you started.
> >

Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
Message-ID: <F94HFE8Pvs51YoDK7n00001e7b0@hotmail.com>
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 10 Dec 2002 23:53:26.0979 (UTC) FILETIME=[553C4130:01C2A0A7]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: NRR: Windows 2000 Problems

IMHO Happy is technically sound on that advice, although if you were that 
close to having a BDC in place that is an NT4.0 box that could log in, you 
probably would not be in the position you are (maybe not??).  To say the 
least, getting a box into that state will take some time, and validating it 
into the domain which currently does not appear to be authenticating in 
mixed mode will most likely complicate the issue (by not authenticating  
which is your current condition).

I would look to what caused the problem to begin with.  Start with the date 
and time at which your problem developed.  Do some old fashioned sleuthing 
in the event logs and look to the NTDS log files for service layer 
interruptions.  You have listed a key word Transaction in your error 
message that would point to DTC as nothing else really uses the transaction 
method of session negotiation. You might be correct in your group pol 
assumptions but it seems like the symptom you describe where your logons no 
longer authenticate is at fault, not the AD implementation itself.  There 
are AD command line tools available from the MS KB that may help to identify 
the authentication problem but you would have to run them on the NT box and 
that may not generate the appropriate error.  This is probably an 
authentication issue, probably linked to directory service permissions.  
Since all user account, groups, network shares and objects are treated as AD 
server objects, you need to look deeper as to why authentication is not 
taking place.  Start by tracing the Event IDs from event logger and then 
address each one from the time of conflict.

Lastly, Service Pack 3 makes many corrections to the Active Directory 
manager that may be at fault currently.  At least bring your service packs 
up to date and then start to sleuth.  Just my $2.50.

IT Ranger

Error msg: The domain controller is not setup for transactions


Possible Microsoft KB Articles that can help:
Microsoft Knowledge Base Article  247715
Microsoft Knowledge Base Article  128489
Microsoft Knowledge Base Article  278299

 > > > Actually, you can use NT BDC's with AD, as long as it's still in 
mixed
 > > mode.
 > > > One of the AD domain controllers holds the role of PDC emulator. As
far
 > as
 > > > the BDCs are concerned, they are domain controllers on a NT4 network.
 > This
 > > > is an easy way to do an NT to AD migration. Upgrade your PDC to Win2K
 > and
 > > > make it the first AD DC. If there is a problem, you can shut down the
AD
 > > DC
 > > > and promote the BDC and be right back where you started.

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Just too many words from Geri Duhl

I thought SF Raves was much more of a community where people could come
and share ideas.  I see other people posting poems.  Lots of people post
political stuff.  I think there needs to be a little more art coming
through as well.  When I'm in a bad mood or have the time I love reading
Geri's posts because they don't make much sense sometimes.  Reminds me
that things don't have to all the time.  Then I smile, close the email
and get back to work.

If this is just a list where we're supposed to talk about raves, clubs
and music... Then almost everyone is guilty of breaking the "rules."
Relax... Its just a party ;)

-Rayn

I'd love to be able to genuinely share your opinion, Rayn.

While it is nice to see that someone is getting something positive out of
this chickie(?)... for the rest of us, really, it's just one long, endless
string of drivel, interspersed with her newfound bile about people who are
awful, dirty hippies because they don't share her taste in long-winded
babblefests about the best place to pick up glitter.

I mean, what the fuck.

I knew a girl a lot like Geri once, actually.

She was the one who informed me that Eminem fought in Oakland gang wars,
that she helped manage the Cannabis Club, and half the bay area owed her
millions of dollars for underground raves she had thrown.

She was also, in case you didn't pick up on it, bugfuck wazoo.

Come to think about it...

I hope that isn't you, Geri. ^_^

The Rational Hatter

Subject: [sfraves] waffle therapy nrr

Every now and then a pretty bird comes down from the sky and taps me on 
the shoulder "oh-so" eloquently. Whatever I did to attract it's 
attention is unknown (other than the fact that my bright orange 
sweatshirt might have something to do with that, or that I was 
particularly shining the day that such events occur). I believe that 
granola could have possibly been put on this Earth just for me 
sometimes, especially when mixed with raspberries and a nice 
coconut-white cup of plain yogurt. : ) MMMmm. It reminds me of the time 
that I was reading a book and these clouds rolled by and covered up 
everything that I had been putting so much of my energy into that day. 
Even the clouds were against me! Without asking, they swooped down and 
rained on my parade that I had been trying so hard to keep afloat. But 
of course -- when someone offers me a drink, whether it be lemonade or 
green tea -- I am normally never one to turn such a unique opportunity 
down, especially when I am in a position that I find myself in quite 
often, especially nowadays when things seem so glum and 
uncircumstantial and there is but a tiny glimmer of belation to be 
found on a sunday when there is the smell of fresh biscuit permeating 
from the kitchen. Or even the bedrooom for that matter! :D Happiness is 
rarely found when going by the book so often-time evidence leads you to 
believe that without finding yourself there is no such thing, but who 
needs myself, i can find it just find by twittering myself into the 
tanning salon and mounting the uv-bar like how lassie saved the boy who 
fell off his bike in that one episode of nick-at-night.

i'm sorry if you don't like what your reading, perhaps what i wrote was 
not meant for your eyes, but happened to find itself there. I plan on 
posting one of these non-sequiter poo letters every day until the day 
that my fingers fall off or I can no longer find the means of using the 
internet. I am quite confident that I will build up a following of 
rejects that enjoy my posts because somehow in my ramblings it makes 
their lives not seem so lonely in a Heaven's Gate'ish fashion.

down with censorship!
Neo Duhl

 arrests

US CA: Rave Crackdown Results In Hollywood Nightclub Raid, Drug
URL: http://www.mapinc.org/drugnews/v02/n2233/a04.html
Newshawk: Please Help Keep MAP On Line http://www.drugsense.org/donate.htm
Pubdate: Mon, 9 Dec 2002
Source: Nevada Appeal (Carson City, NV)
Copyright: 2002 Nevada Appeal
Contact: editor@nevadaappeal.com
Website: http://www.nevadaappeal.com/
Details: http://www.mapinc.org/media/896
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/mdma.htm (Ecstasy)
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/raves.htm (Raves)
Bookmark: http://www.mapinc.org/find?158 (Club Drugs)

RAVE CRACKDOWN RESULTS IN HOLLYWOOD NIGHTCLUB RAID, DRUG ARRESTS

LOS ANGELES -( AP )- A seven-month probe that led to the seizure of more
than 10,000 Ecstasy pills culminated in a raid early Sunday at a popular
Hollywood nightclub where authorities allege designer drugs were openly
sold at rave parties.

Five people were arrested on drug charges during the raid of Circus Disco,
capping an undercover investigation by the U.S.  Drug Enforcement Agency
and the California Department of Alcoholic Beverage Control.

During that time, alcohol control investigators bought Ecstasy, cocaine,
marijuana and ketamine from 25 people.  In six cases, the drug sales were
either made or facilitated by nightclub employees, the state's alcohol
control department said in a statement.

The pills that were seized over the course of the investigation had an
estimated street value of more than $200,000, officials said.

No one at the club was available for comment Sunday night.

Investigators targeted Circus Disco following the September 2001 death of
a 27-year-old man who collapsed on the dance floor and began having
convulsions after taking Ecstasy he allegedly obtained at the nightclub.

The man's parents have filed a wrongful death lawsuit against the club's
owner, Eugene LaPietra, who spearheaded an unsuccessful ballot measure to
have Hollywood secede from the city of Los Angeles.

State officials said they had consulted one of the nation's leading
experts on Ecstasy and raves.  After visiting Circus Disco, the expert,
Trinka D.  Porrrata, said the club was clearly hosting raves based on
factors ranging from the sale of caffeinated "power" drinks that
supposedly enhance Ecstasy's hallucination-inducing effects to the loud
music and the presence of a "cooling off" area staffed by emergency
medical technicians.

Although the club remained open Sunday night, the state Department of
Alcoholic Beverage Control plans to accuse Circus Disco with violating the
terms of its liquor license for allowing "the conspicuous and blatant use
of drugs," the agency said in a statement.  The action could result in the
club having its license to sell liquor suspended.

Phreaky aka Karina
----------------------
http://www.sfraves.org
----------------------
karina@hyperreal.org
phreaky@dreamscape.org

Subject: [sfraves] Words for Mormon boy & too many words from Geri Duhl (heres a good thread)


In a message dated 12/10/02 7:55:21 PM, josephwhunt@hotmail.com writes:

<< Wow, the "Elite Ravers" are passing judgements on the impartial.  What a 
surprise;  I thought that I would never see the day...
Lots of love, even for Geri,
-Trendy Mormon Boy >>

 Hey Trendy Mormon Boy,

 There is a difference between "passing judgment" and "critical analysis." 
Passing judgment sounds like a religious term that someone from....never 
mind. Long live Utah and polygamy. 
 Elite ravers passing judgment are 20 years olds who think they are the shit 
because they've been to every Imagine party and helped make decorations. They 
have a custom Imagine outfit or hat or fleece and wear it almost every time 
you see them out. Did that custom fleece come from Imagine charity proceeds 
or did the crew spring for those out of their own pocket???
 Please note that loving Geri doesn't need to include supporting the 5 posts 
a day about the cute boy, and tea, and what is on TV, and quoting Bush 
straight off of CNN and whatever else sticks in her head long enough for her 
to type it.
 The only thing worse on this list last couple weeks was Mr. Sholin (DJ 
Septer) posting about the "incredible 2x4 with VETERAN Paul the Fan Man" in 
Sac's most unique line up ever.
 Real love is about telling someone the truth, hypefree. Not some candy 
coated fluffy version of what you wanted to say but were afraid to lay on the 
table. Real love is taking the risk, even if it means risking defender 
flames, to say it like it is "Hey lady could you chill on posting everything 
that you think we all need to read". Real love is saying "Shut the fuck up" 
with compassion. That is not elite. Nor harsh.
 It is just that those post are unique and witty and bizarre and slightly 
developmentally disabled when read a few times. But as the frequency 
increases so the cuteness fades and it is just plain obnoxious.
 We love you Geri! For all that you are. I personally would love you more if 
you read more and typed less. Here, here to that. Can I get an amen?


  HYPEFREE007

So here's what I don't get...

You start out complaining about "geri dahl", suggesting that she/he/it/whatever
be restircted to a tiny number of posts per week.

Then you go on to say the (s)he is deep and insightful.  (S)he is neither.  You
obviously share the opinion, otherwist you wouldn't be calling for the
restriction.

Finally, you make it to the obvious solution: a filter.  So why didn't you just
go straight to filtering in the first place?  It's not as if the "geri dahl"
posts are commercial spam, by any streach of the imagination.  So, if they
bother you, why *NOT* just filter?

Myself, I read in digest mode, and see the thread topics at the top of each. 
So I usually just page down through any threads started by him/her/it/whatever.
 But really... just HOW often does a "will 'geri dahl' please shut up" thread
come up?


cya,
john

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Words for Mormon boy & too many words from Geri Duhl
 (heres a good thread)

On Wed, 11 Dec 2002 HYPEFREE007@aol.com wrote:

>  Hey Trendy Mormon Boy,
>
>  There is a difference between "passing judgment" and "critical analysis."
> Passing judgment sounds like a religious term that someone from....never
> mind. Long live Utah and polygamy.

That was just the "passing judgment" that TMB was prolly talking about.
So far as I've seen, he hasn't advocated either of the two.

>  Real love is about telling someone the truth, hypefree. Not some candy
> coated fluffy version of what you wanted to say but were afraid to lay on the
> table. Real love is taking the risk, even if it means risking defender
> flames, to say it like it is "Hey lady could you chill on posting everything
> that you think we all need to read". Real love is saying "Shut the fuck up"
> with compassion. That is not elite. Nor harsh.

The thing that strikes me about the rave community is that the word "love"
flows so freely nobody knows what it means anymore.  Granted, it's all
subjective, but can anybody "Really Love" Geri Dahl from her posts alone?
Real Love often involves more than just posts to a list.

>  It is just that those post are unique and witty and bizarre and slightly
> developmentally disabled when read a few times. But as the frequency
> increases so the cuteness fades and it is just plain obnoxious.
>  We love you Geri! For all that you are. I personally would love you more if
> you read more and typed less. Here, here to that. Can I get an amen?

No, you can't.  This is a public list, and Geri Dahl can post as much or
as little as she wants until she's moderated by someone that controls the
subscriptions to the list.

That's the one thing that seems to escape minds like yours - you can bitch
as much as you like, but whomever it is that you're bitching at can choose
to ignore you and go about their merry business - amazing as it may seem,
your views are not absolute.

I've seen the AOL mail client - it has a delete button, and it also has a
field for "From:" using them in combination might be a good idea in the
future when you see posts from people that you don't like to read.

-lev

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] [NRR] "Club Drugs"

Well fuck it, if others can ramble, so can I.  :P

So I amble into the elevator at work this morning, and there are a couple of
8.5x11 sheets taped onto the walls that simply say "CLUB DRUGS" with the
location of whatever this is (in the lobby, to the right, blah blah blah).
I joked around with the folks around me, "Club drugs? What, are they for
sale? Are they giving them away? Ecstacy? Ketamine? GHB? Hook a brotha up."
Mind you, I work in one of those highrise office buildings, so this is the
oddest place to see a flyer like this... And probably an odd place to rattle
off the names of various psychotropics in the presence of people in suits &
ties.

Then I remember that a month or two ago, a similar flyer had been posted in
our elevators about "marijuana addiction."  Looks like our building has its
very own Mr. Garrison. Drugs are bad, mmmmm'kay? I keep looking down the
hallway for a balding closet case with a hand puppet, but to no avail.

I snicker about this until I'm mentally halted by the thought that this is
probably a small part of that bigger picture of the recent (or rather,
ongoing) Fear and Loathing that's been spread about to distract us from the
real issues. Instead of worrying about how we're financially in shambles and
that we're trying to remedy it by blowing up or exploiting any brown-skinned
folks we can find, we're being reminded that our biggest fear is that one of
our own might be dancing to the blipping and beeping of electronic music
while getting intoxicated in some legally sanctioned space that probably
gives a good back to the economy by means of liquor licenses, permits, and
taxes.

Anyway, thinking about this makes my head hurt, and I've got to coordinate
an international release of some really shitty, buggy software so I can keep
my job so I can make this pittance so I can keep paying for the steep cover
charges and drinks at these scandalous clubs where all these drugs are being
abused.  In the meantime, I think I'll track down Mr. Garrison on my break
and give him a piece of my half-rotten-from-clubbing mind.

 - omid


---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

the decks.  Come on, dance with me...er, US!

A Chicago-based Dj with eminence since 1996, Justin Corbett 
made the move to the Bay Area in 2002 to join  the crew at 
Primal Records in Berkeley, where he continues to be the 
buyer for progressive house and breaks, as well as techno.

An up-and-coming producer in his own right, Justin has 
recently founded his own label, Slow Motion Sequence and 
endeavors to spread the word of forward-thinking dancefloor 
music the world over.
_________________________________________________________

                 Wednesdays @ Il Pirata
             2007 16th Street @ Potrero Ave
                10pm - 2am, age 21+, FREE,
         Full bar, Great people, Comfy atmosphere
      
          Bringing you the rare combination of
     harmony and sophistication in electronic music
      [ house | tribal | tech-house | progressive ]

             With residents Joseph Lee, Kem,
            Zeel, Telene, plus weekly guests.

_________________________________________________________

  For info or bookings please email telene@elastiq-sf.com

                   We have a web site:
               http://www.elastiq-sf.com/

     Please visit the site for any upcoming schedules.

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Just too many words from Geri Duhl

correct me if i'm wrong, but isn't one of the functions of a "moderator," at 
least in theory, to "moderate" when, e.g., a list member engages in hate 
speech?  i quote from Ms. Dahl's latest controversial missive:

"scummy, stinky, sweaty, oily dank smoking acid trippy ugly hippy girls only 
party. someone get on it quick, because i can tell you for sure that there 
are enough followers of that life plan to keep you in business for life if 
your into it...hey, i hear some of these kinds of people even get laid and 
occasionally remember it."

substitute the name of an ethnic or religious group--or, perhaps, the name 
of YOUR favorite sub-set of the dance-music scene!--for "hippy" in the 
preceding quote, post it under a name other than that of She Who Must Be 
Indulged, and just watch the fucking fur fly, no?

i decided to grow my hair longer than the typical American male when i was 
14 years old.  i've been taking shit from ignorant, closed-minded little 
people ever since.  i will be forty-six years old on Monday, and i am sick 
and fucking tired of this shit.  i don't give a damn what Geri Dahl's 
personal foibles or problems are, and i really don't care about her more 
typical illiterate, self-absorbed drivel; in fact, if other people hadn't 
copied her verbiage into her replies, i'd never even have seen it, since i 
filtered that daft bitch MONTHS ago. but when her bullshit gets incorporated 
into a thread, i can't avoid it, since i at least scan posts that i don't 
filter.  and she has NO right WHATSOVER to post this kind of hateful, 
ignorant drivel.  perhaps our "moderator" should stand down in favor of 
someone who actually takes the responsibilities of the position seriously, 
rather than saying in essence "it's not a problem unless you give a shit."  
or just answer the simple question: is it acceptable for ANYONE to engage in 
hate speech against WHOEVER they're stupidly prejudiced against?  or is that 
right accreted only to Ms. Dahl, and is hatred allowed only against 
"hippies"?  i'll take my answer on the air...

--hb


>Geri is in a unique position that while she doesn't really break any
>rules, she still manages to bother some of you folks.
>
>I'll admit her posts come from some other planet, but if you don't want to 
>read them, then...don't read them! Problem solved.
>
>-terry

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Just too many words from Geri Duhl

They don't? ;)  Totally agree with you though.  I'm so sick of
political-correctness and hurt feelings.  Sure there are some major
underlying issues behind socital problems but at the same time we're
using scare tactics, court cases and new laws to go about it instead of
the cost-inefficient process of edumacation.

Bob,

I'm white and in a lot of countries I would be ridiculed, spit on,
robbed etc. because of it.  Hell, I'm even of Irish descent.  Yet all
irishman jokes are typically accepted as funny and I don't know many
people who get too butt-hurt over it... (Note:  We are not all cops
named Murphy and live in boston) And if I were to be angry at someone of
another nationality making fun of my heritage I would most likely be
branded the racist as well since I'm white and jokes about us don't
matter since we've never been opressed.  That's why Belfast is still a
warzone, Spanish people are no longer white, and most of the original
settlers of the US were slaughtered by native tribes until
reinforcements arrived. (Not that I condone what we did to them after
that in the slightest.)  I've very proud to be of Irish descent but I'm
not overly serious about it... Hell, we created Guinness ;)

To keep going on I was born mormon, but its by general consensus its ok
to say things like 'Oh, its ok to make fun of mormons about polygamy,
their undergarments etc. because its funny and they don't seem to mind.'
I'll tell you that most mormon's are very jovial people and able to
laugh at their own weird ways.  It doesn't mean it doesn't hurt though
as a kid to be picked on about how weird you are for the LDS religions
past of multiple wives.  The constant hasseling of, whats wrong with
you, you guys don't drink, don't smoke, don't (shouldn't) drink caffeine
or even tea, you dress weird, you don't swear, etc.  Instead of calling
that person an insult or claiming they need to be moderated they'll lead
by example and still be a good person to you and try to educate you
about why they are the way they are, typically and mostly outside of
Utah.  Up until the late 1980's or 90's it was still legal to slay a
mormon in Missouri due to the opression they got in the 1800s.  

I had long hair for 5 years in the heart of mormon country.  The only
time I got picked on about it was when jobs wanted me to look
professional.  I got called hippy, I still do get called hippy even
though I have short hair and don't really fit the dress.  Did I ever
care?  Not really.  They got a lot of political movements going that
didn't exist before, but their lifestyle was far too radical for people
to understand, and they didn't do a good job of explaining and educating
people of why they do what they do.  Soon they were seen as people who
protested for any reason and they got old quick and people stopped
listening to the commonly dirty, drugged up, free love person because
they started grating on peoples nerves.  People like to be able to
express opinions without being ripped into, sometimes its derogatory
because they are uneducated on your way of life.  And if they are
educated about it then they probably have an opposing viewpoint and you
either work through it or don't associate with that person.  If someone
makes a comment about your lifestyle that you don't agree with, explain
to them your point of view.  If they refuse to listen, refuse to
associate with them.  It doesn't mean that other people don't like them
though.

There is a huge difference between racism and lifestyle though.  A
lifestyle is something you most likely choose or are raised in but you
always have the option to change if you don't like it, or you should be
proud of it and realize that there will be people out there who don't
agree with you.  (I'm not going into family guilt factors for sake of
length) You can either get over it or be bitter.  You can't choose the
color of your skin though.. Well, Michael Jackson prooved us wrong there
but I don't think people will be following his lead since his
expieriment seemed to fail and his nose eventually fell off...  But when
you're persecuted for something you can't change, its these things that
should be looked at and dealt with because your skin color doesn't
determine whats in your head.  And the man will try to make you believe
that because you are different, you are not as good as them.  Its
because they're scared.  Frightened.  And also uneducated or raised to
believe a certain way.  If you can for one second not snap back at them
and try to get them to listen and change their view point a little, it's
the road to their recovery.  Or you might find out that they were
traumatised by something and the only thing they remember is a skin
color, or a drugged out look in the eyes, or the persons sex and they
reject anything relating to it from then on out until they seek help.
If you don't want to deal with them, don't.  Geri obviously didn't piss
off everyone on the list with her hippy comment.  You should respond to
her in private and ask her why she thinks as such or shrug it off.  If
we were to ban everyone who made a comment without thinking first of
anothers feelings, we'd have no leaders of our country, no military, no
philsophers, and definitely no artists or musicians.

We are all different, we are all unique and we all have the most complex
computer and operating system known to man built into our head.
Unfortunately, its easier to use it to hurt and defend than it is to
accept new data or explain yourself without striking back and fueling
the fire.  If you don't take the brief effort to see where someone else
is coming from, you don't have a starting point yourself and come off
sounding as ignorant as they.

Of course I'm also forgiving and accepting to a fault.  Fool me once,
whatever.  Fool me twice, whatever.  Fool me again, avoidance.
Apologize, welcome back.  My problem is I typically consider everyones
point of view and usually never talk because I'm always analzying
incoming data and can't translate my opinions to speech fast enough.

-Rayn

> correct me if i'm wrong, but isn't one of the functions of a "moderator," at

>
<snip>
> perhaps our "moderator" should stand down in favor of

> rather than saying in essence "it's not a problem unless you give a shit."
> or just answer the simple question: is it acceptable for ANYONE to engage in
> hate speech against WHOEVER they're stupidly prejudiced against?  or is that
> right accreted only to Ms. Dahl, and is hatred allowed only against
> "hippies"?  i'll take my answer on the air...

Howlin' Bob,

Of course hate speech is discouraged on this list. However, I fail to see
Geri's posts as hate speech. You take a single excerpt with an off-color
remark and ask me to step down because I don't adopt a harsh stance? I
think it would be a diservice to the list to walk on egg shells
and be reactive to anything that someone on the list might find offensive.
This isn't an AOL list. This isn't a public high school where they ban a
novel because it has the word nigger in it.

One of the reasons SFR has been allowed to prosper is because
of its hands-off moderation policy. Freedom of speech is key to this list.
Personally, I draw the line at those who blatantly abuse the list or attack
others on it. Currently, I don't believe Geri falls into either category.

Anyone and everyone here has always been welcome too send me their
complaints and suggestions, and many have. Contrary to your belief, Bob, I
do take my role here very seriously, and spend a lot of my day keeping up
with traffic and performing list admin duties. However, as your public
servant, if enough of you believe SFR needs to crack out the whip, I will
oblidge or find someone who can.

take care,

terry

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: FS - 2 21" computer monitors

Hey all,

I want to get rid of my 2 21" CRT computer monitors (replacing with
flat-panels).  Anyone need a nice display?

#1 is Optiquest (Viewsonic OEM) Q115 : .26 pitch, 1600x1200x76Hz.  This is a
great monitor and has been on my desk for about a year.  It's a gorgeous
display.  These sell new for about $550 + shipping.

#2 is a Sun 21" display.  It is not the trinitron, but the next model down.
It is vertically flat and gorgeous.  I'm pretty sure it is a .26, and I know
it can do 1600x1200x80Hz.  The trinitron is selling for $1000, so I'd guess
this is somewhere around $600 new.

I'll best offer on these, but let's not get silly - I'm not letting them go
for $100. :)

Tim

I'm not mad about one extremely stupid post from Julie.

There's nothing about SFR thgat mandates reason, and to be honest people
have been making occasional fun of hippies, tranceheads, e-tards,a dn
sarcastic techno djs and other inherent demographics.

That's not the problem.

The problem is someone who consistently tests the rules of this while at a
complete 180 to the spirit of what it's about (discussing raves and rave
culture in and around SF).

How many more almost exclusively off topic mails until it's a problem?

I recommend she be asked by the moderator (with list support) to police
herself (at least 50% on topic posts or something), and should that fail
we boot her.

We're talking several messages a week, to hundreds of recipients, for
years now... with only an extremely small fraction even pretending to be
along the lines of what most of us signed up for.

If Julie doesn't know where this type of writing belongs... do we have to
shoulder the brunt of it?  Usenet, personal web page, livejournal, etc.
SFRaves is NOT the place for the personal ramblings that have nothing to
do with the scene.  Of course we all do this from time to time, but she's
made a habit out of it that wastes everybody else's time.

andyw

On Wed, 11 Dec 2002, blindspot wrote:
-&e->Why shouldn't we tolerate a community's harmless wackos? Especially
-&e->when they really aren't doing any harm? Is an online community that
-&e->different than a real one?

It's a topic centric discussion list.

The "community aspect" of SFR is not just this list (but the only part
Julie participates in).  It's also going out to events, being there,
meeting others from the list, offline communications, etc... not talking
about yourself incessantly on a mailing list that has nothing to do.

If I showed up on a linux newsgroup talking about nothing but bee pollen,
you better believe they're gonna kick me the fuck off.  I don't understand
why rules of courtesy in regards to topic and respect shouldn't apply
here.

andyw

Content-type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"
Content-transfer-encoding: 7bit
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] How a community treats its wackos

I'll throw my long, rambling, semi-coherent hat in the ring. :P

Don't recall who originally said this, but:

>> If I showed up on a linux newsgroup talking about nothing but bee pollen,
>> you better believe they're gonna kick me the fuck off.  I don't understand
>> why rules of courtesy in regards to topic and respect shouldn't apply
>> here.

I'm in the "if you don't like it, just delete it" camp, as that's generally
what I do. I treat it like the 100+ pieces of spam I receive at work each
day and send the GDB (look, I'm already using the acronym!) on its merry
way.

However, I'm also inclined to agree with the Linux/bee pollen analogy. The
difference comes from one single, solitary letter.  You see, the list is
called SFRaves. Meaning the main topic at hand is raves (or anything related
to them, which so often turns out to be music, DJ/raver culture, and
society/law).  At least, that's what I take it to be, so I think everyone's
complaints are valid.

Had one letter been added to the domain name - say it was "sfraveRs.org,"
then no one would have much to complain about. Because then, well, GD as a
purported raver could post her inane ramblings all she wanted, because it
would be about an SF-area raver - namely, herself.

So if we want to get this nit-picky about it (which I'm assuming people are,
otherwise they wouldn't be posting constantly) and want to whine about
everything to a moderator, there first need to be defined lines. At what
point is something NRR *too* NRR for SFRaves? Who's to decide that? Who's to
judge what's too NRR too often?  Geri's self-absorbed analyses of hair
products? Sameer's right-wing rants against war protesters? Osby's
oh-my-gosh declarations about the cookies he just baked? Screw it! Let's
make all NRR posts illegal, or at best, limited to once a week.  *grin*

Wait, wait, wait... Hold it!! We couldn't have the same SFR without these
little entertainments that arrive in our inboxes everyday, could we? Sure,
there'd be plenty of rave-related info, and the list would be a dynamic
version of the calendar. Are we sure that's what we want? Because if we
condemn one individual's off-topic ramblings, why should anyone else be
entitled to do so, even if it was less often?

The bottom line is, a good number of us clog some of the bandwidth here with
utterly Non-Rave-Related crap, myself included. Some more often than others.
Although those things are way off topic and often waste our time, and sure
as shit a number of them bug me, I think we're better for having them. Even
though we all love our community and want to maintain it, we also have to
keep the blemishes, whether they be purveyors of political vitriol or
useless banter. I hate to agree with the overly PLURry people on the list
(you know who you are, you candy-colored dorkoids), but it just wouldn't be
the same community without these, erm, warts. Or however you see them.

What am I saying?  Either put together a movement to establish some strict
rules and have them mercilessly enforced, or kick back, relax, and enjoy
this ever-growing, fucked up, wonderful, dysfunctional virtual family that
we are. Personally, I prefer the latter - less rules and a few annoyances -
rather than the Ashcroft-inspired less-freedom-for-more-peace-of-mind trap
;)

Well, that's my two-and-a-half cents. (Inflation, ya know.)

 - omid

www.radio1328.com
www.tavallai.com

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Unfortunately, our constitutional rights do apply to this list.  Geri, as
whack as she may be, does have the right to say what's on her twisted little
mind.  Although I am not personally fond of Geri because of a lil flame war
she and I got into a few months ago, I do support her in her unique views.
She has the right to share, she has the right to babble.  If you don't want
to read it you are a ctrl+a ~> del away from ALL and any posts pertaining to
her.  Her posts have been described as adding a "hai ku" *sp?* quality to
the list.  I personally call it insane blathering, but I'm not lazy enough,
or grumpy enough, to let her 3 posts a week get to me or make ME START
emphasizing every OTHER word IN CAPS cuz I'm SO mad about GERI filling MY
inbox with shiat. (!)  If you let the idiot get to you, the idiot will one
day rule the town.  Chill out ya'll.  Do what I do and make ample use of
your delete key...It works wonders =)

~Emily

Subject: Re: [sfraves] How a community treats its wackos

Constitution has nothing to do with this list. It's a privately owned list
which is operated on a privately owned server. Constitution doesn't apply.
Any private forum such as SFR is subject to the rules of the forum. The
consitution provides for the right to have a server hosting a list like SFR,
but doesn't guarantee the subscribers the right to say whatever they want.
The list is setup as a forum, a very open forum, and has a moderator which
can step in and censor at any time. Be glad that this list is as such. I may
not like hearing all the random thoughts from Julie but it's nice to know
that I can dump like that should I choose to. It's a privilege, not a
right...

ryan.bailey
sninesix.design
www.sninesix.com
www.innocentchild.com

Unfortunately, our constitutional rights do apply to this list.  Geri, as
whack as she may be, does have the right to say what's on her twisted little
mind.  Although I am not personally fond of Geri because of a lil flame war
she and I got into a few months ago, I do support her in her unique views.
She has the right to share, she has the right to babble.  If you don't want
to read it you are a ctrl+a ~> del away from ALL and any posts pertaining to
her.  Her posts have been described as adding a "hai ku" *sp?* quality to
the list.  I personally call it insane blathering, but I'm not lazy enough,
or grumpy enough, to let her 3 posts a week get to me or make ME START
emphasizing every OTHER word IN CAPS cuz I'm SO mad about GERI filling MY
inbox with shiat. (!)  If you let the idiot get to you, the idiot will one
day rule the town.  Chill out ya'll.  Do what I do and make ample use of
your delete key...It works wonders =)

~Emily

culture in and around SF).

How many more almost exclusively off topic mails until it's a problem?

I recommend she be asked by the moderator (with list support) to police
herself (at least 50% on topic posts or something), and should that fail
we boot her.

We're talking several messages a week, to hundreds of recipients, for
years now... with only an extremely small fraction even pretending to be
along the lines of what most of us signed up for.

If Julie doesn't know where this type of writing belongs... do we have to
shoulder the brunt of it?  Usenet, personal web page, livejournal, etc.
SFRaves is NOT the place for the personal ramblings that have nothing to
do with the scene.  Of course we all do this from time to time, but she's
made a habit out of it that wastes everybody else's time.

andyw
 >>

 WELL SAID ANDY!!!!! GERI TONE IT DOWN

Subject: [sfraves] DPFVA: CALI: Santa Cruz deputizes WAMM

http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2002/December/11/local/stories/02lo
cal.htm

December 11, 2002

Council deputizes pot club founders
By DAN WHITE
Santa Cruz Sentinel (CA) staff writer

SANTA CRUZ - The City Council voted unanimously Tuesday to deputize
the co-founders of a medical-marijuana club, symbolically making them
officers of the city government.

That doesn't mean Wo/Men's Alliance for Medical Marijuana's Mike and
Valerie Corral are actual deputies, have any special powers or will
"need to show any stinkin' badges," said City Councilman Tim
Fitzmaurice. Instead, their status means the council officially
sanctions WAMM's activities.

Council members said they hope the formal link between the city and
the group will increase legal protections for the Corrals, who have
not been charged with a crime in connection with a September raid by
federal agents on their pot farm, but are wary of future prosecution.

The Corrals are still trying to get the seized marijuana plants and
some equipment back from the federal government.

At the very least, the deputization shows solidarity with WAMM,
council members said.

Armed federal agents arrested the Corrals on Sept. 5 and tore out 167
plants at their Davenport-area marijuana garden. The Corrals, who
were released hours after their arrest, said they were told they
could be arrested again at any time.

WAMM's founders say most of the group's 200-plus members are
seriously or terminally ill.

Council members received national media attention later in September
for showing up to a rally on the steps of City Hall, where WAMM
members came to get their weekly allotment of medical pot. For their
stand, council members were alternately praised as heroes standing up
against federal bullies, and ridiculed as flakes who were
perpetuating the city's wacky, drugged-out image.

If the WAMM founders end up before the Supreme Court, "we're showing
faith in what they are doing," Councilman Tim Fitzmaurice said. He
said WAMM could turn to the court and say, "Look, this is the faith
the community has in us."

Andrea Tischler of the local Compassion Flower Inn, a
bed-and-breakfast devoted to medical marijuana, urged the city to
take it a step further and "consider deputizing others to run clubs
because over 2,000 patients are in need of their medicine" in Santa
Cruz County. She said there's no way WAMM alone can serve the need.

Councilman Mike Rotkin said he's concerned that the national press is
making the city's stand on medical marijuana into an
everybody-must-get-stoned story.

He said city leaders did not take the deputization status lightly,
and that it was extending this status because of WAMM's continued
commitment to protecting terminally ill patients. He said that for
anyone else to get this deputy status, they'd have to prove they had
as much commitment and responsibility as WAMM.

Councilman Mark Primack supported the motion but said he wanted to do
something that had more "teeth" to provide guaranteed legal
protections for the Corrals. He said he was dismayed by a recent
statement by the federal Drug Enforcement Administration that
deputization would not change the Corrals' status in the eyes of the
government.

"What is a tangible action to create real protection?" he said.

Rotkin replied that he thought DEA spokesman Richard Meyer was being
"very disingenuous" in his statements to the Sentinel earlier this
week, and that deputization could offer real protections.

"This could be a way to defend them because they are following the
spirit of the local (medical marijuana) ordinance and should not be
prosecuted," Rotkin said. "In the end, it's not up to the DEA but the
courts to settle this."

Meyer on Tuesday reiterated his statement that "federal law
supersedes state or local law, so nobody in the U.S. has
authorization to distribute illegal drugs at will. We are a country
of laws. Deputization really does nothing as far as federal law is
concerned."

The federal government considers medical marijuana contraband and has
asserted that its authority overrides state and local laws that make
provisions for medical marijuana - touching off an emotional debate
about alternative medicine, drug use and local authority.

The Corrals said Tuesday they hoped their new status would give them
protection under the same federal law that lets police officers
legally carry and sell drugs while engaging in narcotics stings.
According to this reading of the law, the Corrals would be
"enforcing" state and local laws allowing for medical marijuana use.

"It's opposite ends of the same continuum," Mike Corral said.
"They're out to bust people and we're out to help."

Meyer said he couldn't imagine WAMM meeting the criteria to fall
under the provisions of that federal law.

"That makes no sense," he said. "Local deputies handle drugs, process
them and lock them up. They don't distribute them to people on the
street. If they did that, they would be breaking the law."

Santa Cruz, however, is not the first city to try to use deputization
of medical marijuana club members to increase their protection from
federal prosecution. A similar approach was used in Oakland and San
Francisco. The strategy has yet to be tested in federal court.

WAMM members say they are still getting marijuana for members. They
declined to state the source.

WAMM board member Suzanne Pfeil said the government "tries to
characterize a sick and tiny community as drug trafficking, and that
it has to protect the (community) from us. We ask you to protect us
from them."

Contact Dan White at dwhite@santa-cruz.com.
--
----
Dale Gieringer (415) 563-5858  // canorml@igc.org
2215-R Market St. #278, San Francisco CA 94114

MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] How a community treats its wackos

it has been my understanding for quite some time now
that the letters NRR in the subject line are
designated to allow listees to filter out
non-rave-related posts.

if you don't know how to use your email filters, drop
me a line and i'll help you figure it out if i can. 
besides filtering your email lists you can also reduce
spam.

because of off-topic posts, i've gotten furniture from
fellow sfravers, picked up links to cool websites,
gotten some interesting perspectives with raver flavor
on current events and other hot topics... these are a
few benefits of NRR that i can think of just off the
top of my head.  are we talking about doing away with
NRR?

to suppress something is to give it strength; this has
been the testimony of censorship time and time again. 
there is enough fascism elsewhere, don't you think? 
lest we forget, this whole community is populated with
whackos. just ask the DEA.

;)sooz

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Calling All DJs

If you are booked for a party then how come your friend hasn't taken care of
the sound system? That's not a dj's responsibility. In the world of throwing
parties we as promoters take care of all the details including sound, venue,
tickets, water, logistics, and lineup. The dj is paid talent and only needs
to show up with a record case.

It seems that your friend doesn't know what they're doing if you're having
to make this request to SFR. Those that don't know what they're doing have
no place in the current state of this scene.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] time for a bit of sense.

Our corporate council has an interesting stance on morailty-

It is simply "how would things be if everyone did it?"

Like- is it wrong to rip a page out of a book in the library?
You might say yes, you might say no- but what if *everyone* ripped a
page out?
Obviously then there would be no books left.

I'm not one for censorship, and Terry made his moderation duties
clear-
But at the same time-
She's got the right to post nonsenical drivel (IMO)-
Just like I've got the right to tell her to shut it and stop wasting my
time.
...

Getting back to the original point- I think we should *ALL* begin
posting like she does.
I think that would sort out whether it was right or wrong pretty
quick...

-- 
AIM: IMFDUP
"and what is temptation, if not embraced..."

their own..That way you learn a good portion of what goes on. Hell when I

did know the basics and I got threw it..Just my opinion

Nick
http://www.core-nrg.net
http://www.hardcoreforthepeople.com

  Chris Dumas <christherebel@earthlink.net>, <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
In-Reply-To: <00b101c2a220$b528fa50$0a0a0a0a@asgard>
Message-ID: <Pine.GSO.4.44.0212121319090.20317-100000@atari>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Calling All DJs


On Thu, 12 Dec 2002, Happy wrote:
-&e->So, only people who are experienced should throw parties? The door has
-&e->closed, and there is no room for people to learn and, most likely, make
-&e->mistakes? I've never tried to throw a party, but I figured I could give it a
-&e->shot some day if I wanted to. Thanks for letting me know that I should defer
-&e->to the "established promoters."

It's a really good idea to crew a few parties first (helping bigger, more
established groups as a humble little servant), before throwing your own.
Ryan is not saying that you have to be an experienced promoter to
"deserve" throwing parties... but if you're charging people for something,
shouldn't you have your shit together?  It takes experience, and the best
way to do that is help crews that are doing it right.

It's also a good diea to take on a couple friends who have done the same,
with similar intentions.  That is the root of most successful collectives.

Learn what goes into security considerations at an underground, how
visuals and lights and sound work together to plan a room, how to work out
decorations, deal with a collective work force, space owners, etc.

It might be easy to throw a party... but you should have the experience
to deal with adversity should it arise.  Way too many posts about
promoters' first parties being a dangerous waste of money... don't be one.
Putting all the risk of an event on fate and the pocket books of your
guests is arrogant and dangerous...

I did sound for a lot of people's first parties back when I had a sound
system, and trust me... there's a BIG difference betweeen a first party
thrown by people who have no clue, and a first party thrown by people who
have learned from others' events by crewing different aspects of the
parties (building up to real resonsibility, not just staffed a water bar
or something like that) and communicating with the people who throw them.

Knowledge is power, research and experience are your friends.
andyw

What Nick said is what I meant by the post. Hearing someone say they're
booked and have to bring sound for their friend who booked them raises a
flag for me. If you haven't thrown a party, don't really know what you're
doing you risk a lot not just for yourself but for others who are out there
throwing parties. Venues are rare now and to have inexperienced people
risking the longevity of a venue bothers me.

Although I delete all of her posts (unless it has an intriguing subject line) 
it's a sort of comfort to see her name in my inbox. Ever since I joined SFR 
in early '99 she's been adding her uniqueness to the list by way of a few 
eccentric e-mails every week. She's a staple of SFR, joining others such as 
Pol*E*wog,   Andy Tiedye, Andy W, Deepfog, Leslie, Terry, Vlad, TeknoDiva, 
BBoiBreks, MoonChyld, InnocentChild, Jennifer Love Hewitt.... even Osby. : )  
 These are just a few of the names that come to mind when I think of those 
who make up the personality and history of SFR. They add a bit of color to an 
otherwise monochromatic list. And Geri sort of plays the role of the strange 
aunt or uncle everyone has in their family. She may not be your favorite aunt 
but she certainly serves as an endless source of giggles! So resort to the 
tactic that always works with your strange Uncle Filbert- just smile and nod. 
After all, what would a family be if it weren't dysfunctional? : D

heart,
Alida

I have noticed that there are bum lookers, bum riders and bum sitters.  I 
often use a nice lotion on my bum to keep it from chafing.  It's those 
hippies with their salmon smelling incense that aggravate my bum.  As I was 
sitting here meditating on the lack of good bottom parties I noticed that 
the shaman of events in the land of the green eyed salmons was providing 
some wonderful body care products at the latest bum event next week.  I 
worry about this.  I protect my bum, and I don't want invasive action 
here.  Bum people can be so cruel sometimes.  I can handle that, but it's 
the body protective synthetics I lack.

Alas,

Apollo

At 01:56 PM 12/12/2002 -0800, Omid Tavallai wrote:
>I have an allergy to pollen. Particularly bad are my allergies to flowering
>trees, like walnut blossoms. Those damn near killed me as a child. Would I
>be able to take bee pollen as a food supplement without fear of severe
>allergic reaction? Or will the stuff simply kill me?

I have a severe reaction to bee stings.  Once, incredibly enough, I was 
bitten by a bee in Bloomingdale's mens' department in the middle of winter 
and there was great drama trying to find the bee to prove that I wasn't 
some crack head:)

I do use bee pollen supplements now, however.  You might try a small dose 
of royal jelly or pollen to test.  The reaction, if it occurs, shouldn't be 
severe.

Apollo

Subject: [sfraves] I'd rather be dancing =)

I remember like on Tahnksgiving Weekend when I went outta town w/ the fam & 
we had Thanksgiving in like by Santa Barbera kinda... grrrrr... I was achin' 
4 some Groovy beats & somewhere 2 dance my ass off!!  Rather, I had 2 settle 
for a mini golf/arcade place to let off those vibes & spend money on video 
games that probably equaled out to a cover to like 1015 or 550... LoL

BUt I dunno man... I could do the family thing, hang out w/ relatives I see 
4-5 times a year, but man... when the clock hits 10pm... I wanna Groove!  
Hello 2Day =P

Dancing always gives me all these undescribable feeling of I dunno, Bliss, I 
dunno... a totally higher state (hey... sober anyway)  I mean, hear those 
yummy beats, yummy melodies, yummy sounds makes me jus' move & fly away!

I was remembering something that Alida posted once about closing her eyes 
when she dances & letting the music take her away!!  Then again, there was 
an Ascension moment when Alida & I were on the floor & this song came on!!  
But man, music does so much 2 like a person's mentality, ya know!!  Feelings 
of greatness come in, sometimes a sad song on the radio makes some1 have 2 
like do this mondo pull over & cry on the side of the freeway... la la la 
la... wait, I'm talkin' about dancing!!!

Ya know, the best 4 me is when there's like some Juicy Jungle playing on a 
kinda empty dance floor 'cause I get 2 like be this Mondo Space Hog & Jam!!  
LoL... Alota DJs Thanks me 4 danciong during their sets & stuff, but man... 
the Music is jus' so much Groovy stuff, ya know!

There was this 1 time @ Butterfly House when we were dancin' in the Garage & 
stuff!!  It wasw when "One More Time" like kinda jus' came out & it was 
playing!!  LoL... Jason DK coined the phrase "Candy House" when he heard 
that song... BUt man, we we're all dancing on the floor to this Groovy song 
& bein' total Goofs 'cause we were celebrating each others company, the 
Music, ya know... it was a Dope night man!!!

There was another time I remember @ Mad Hatter when Aryck, Miki, Ryan, & I 
like all met up there & Andy W was spinning that night!1  LoL... we had the 
best time jus' dancing w/ each other, hangin' out, drinking beers, & jus' 
totally havin' this Groovy time!!  LoL... even when Andy did this HUGE Train 
wreck, but it's OK, he recovered fine!!  Well, wait it wasn't 2 long after 
that when he shaved off all his long hair...hmmmmm

Point being to all this, I'd rather be in the company of Groove Family, 
Groovin' the night away on the floor, & makin' Memories w/ people I Love!!  
It's been hard doin' that on a 7 nihgts a week basis like I did 4 like 2 
years in a row w/o a car...LoL... but I go out & Dance as much as I can when 
possible =)

Then again, stayin' home & catchin' up on 2 Seasons of Charmed sin't so bad 
either!!  I have 2 convince my parents to like let me put the VCR i n my 
room so I won't miss my Thursday night lline up anymore since I"m never home 
on Thurs nights anymore & I keep missing FRIENDS...

OK... jus' some Food 4 Thught that's been building in my head lately =)  I 
mean, it's like wonter Holidays & man, there's alota family stuff comin' up 
& I dunno....LoL.... I'd rather be dancing after all the family festivities 
w/ family on the floor! =)



Take Care,

Subject: Re: [sfraves] How a community treats its wackos

well, being as I was just laid-off today, now I can read everyone's posts!!

Anyone looking for an enterprise-level senior sysadmin? :P

Omid Tavallai wrote:
> I'll throw my long, rambling, semi-coherent hat in the ring. :P
> 
> Don't recall who originally said this, but:
> 
> 
>>>If I showed up on a linux newsgroup talking about nothing but bee pollen,
>>>you better believe they're gonna kick me the fuck off.  I don't understand
>>>why rules of courtesy in regards to topic and respect shouldn't apply
>>>here.
>>
> 
> I'm in the "if you don't like it, just delete it" camp, as that's generally
> what I do. I treat it like the 100+ pieces of spam I receive at work each
> day and send the GDB (look, I'm already using the acronym!) on its merry
> way.
> 
> However, I'm also inclined to agree with the Linux/bee pollen analogy. The
> difference comes from one single, solitary letter.  You see, the list is
> called SFRaves. Meaning the main topic at hand is raves (or anything related
> to them, which so often turns out to be music, DJ/raver culture, and
> society/law).  At least, that's what I take it to be, so I think everyone's
> complaints are valid.
> 
> Had one letter been added to the domain name - say it was "sfraveRs.org,"
> then no one would have much to complain about. Because then, well, GD as a
> purported raver could post her inane ramblings all she wanted, because it
> would be about an SF-area raver - namely, herself.
> 
> So if we want to get this nit-picky about it (which I'm assuming people are,
> otherwise they wouldn't be posting constantly) and want to whine about
> everything to a moderator, there first need to be defined lines. At what
> point is something NRR *too* NRR for SFRaves? Who's to decide that? Who's to
> judge what's too NRR too often?  Geri's self-absorbed analyses of hair
> products? Sameer's right-wing rants against war protesters? Osby's
> oh-my-gosh declarations about the cookies he just baked? Screw it! Let's
> make all NRR posts illegal, or at best, limited to once a week.  *grin*
> 
> Wait, wait, wait... Hold it!! We couldn't have the same SFR without these
> little entertainments that arrive in our inboxes everyday, could we? Sure,
> there'd be plenty of rave-related info, and the list would be a dynamic
> version of the calendar. Are we sure that's what we want? Because if we
> condemn one individual's off-topic ramblings, why should anyone else be
> entitled to do so, even if it was less often?
> 
> The bottom line is, a good number of us clog some of the bandwidth here with
> utterly Non-Rave-Related crap, myself included. Some more often than others.
> Although those things are way off topic and often waste our time, and sure
> as shit a number of them bug me, I think we're better for having them. Even
> though we all love our community and want to maintain it, we also have to
> keep the blemishes, whether they be purveyors of political vitriol or
> useless banter. I hate to agree with the overly PLURry people on the list
> (you know who you are, you candy-colored dorkoids), but it just wouldn't be
> the same community without these, erm, warts. Or however you see them.
> 
> What am I saying?  Either put together a movement to establish some strict
> rules and have them mercilessly enforced, or kick back, relax, and enjoy
> this ever-growing, fucked up, wonderful, dysfunctional virtual family that
> we are. Personally, I prefer the latter - less rules and a few annoyances -
> rather than the Ashcroft-inspired less-freedom-for-more-peace-of-mind trap
> ;)
> 
> Well, that's my two-and-a-half cents. (Inflation, ya know.)
> 
>  - omid
> 
> www.radio1328.com
> www.tavallai.com
> 
> 
>

Subject: [sfraves] RE: Linux

Bee Pollen is actually really nifty stuff.

Really, I don't know that for a fact, I'm just taking the word of some random
srtanger on that.  Really I'm not sure what bee bollen really is.  I know that
plants and flowers have pollen.  I definately know that pine cones have pollen.
 There's aome kind of plant that lives on the same hill as me in the city that
has helluva pollen.  I know that, because during pollen season it is totally
pointless to wash my car.  Sure, I can wash it.  But in less than a day, it'll
have a thick coating of pollen on it again.  Oddly enough, this usually happens
when I let it sit overnight when I'm sleeping.  I like to sleep.  I really
don't think I sleep enough.  Maybe I should smoke pot and quit showering like
some dirty hippy so I could sleep more.

But I didn't think bees had pollen?  Plants make pollen.  And bees are
animeals.  Oops, I mean animals.  Obviously no one should make a meal out of
bees; or of any other animal.  But the point is that animals don't make pollen.
 Actually, I don't think I really have a point.  But I like bee pollen, even
though it doesn't really come from bees.  But I like honey.  That comes from
bees.  Or at least that's what teacher told me.  I don't think I believe
teacher.  Because I once caught a bee and tried to make honey come out.  Honey
didn't come out.  The bee just bit me instead.  It hurt a lot.  I don't think I
like bees.

I don't really think I like pollen either.  My doctor says it's what makes me
sneeze a lot.  He also says it's what makes my eyes water and hurt a lot.  I
take these funny little pink pills so that I don't sneeze.  They also make my
eyes not water and hurt.  They also make me really sleepy.  Maybe I should eat
a bunch so that I can sleep without smoking that pot stuff.  It says on the
bottle not to drive when I take the pills.  But if I don't take the pills I
sneeze a lot and my eyes water and hurt.  Besides, it's fun to drive after I
take the pills.  Everything moves in slow motion.  It's like that movie with
keyanu reeves in it.

I don't like that movie though.  That one chick looks like a slutty whore in
all that black leather.  I bet she is a pot smoking hippy.  Well, no she's not,
she's too skinny.  Everybody knows that dirty hippies can't stop eating and are
all fat and ugly.  I bet she was a slutty hippy but is a tweaker now.  In fact,
I don't think I did see her eat at all in that movie.  What a whore.  She must
do lots of drugs.  Especially the way everything gets all blurry and green and
stuff in that movie.  And the way that mirror oozes around.  That movie was
made for dirty druggies.  I should rent it and write down all the credits and
send the names in to the dea.

I don't know what bee pollen or my car or my allergies or that movie has to do
with linux.  Or with raving.  Or even with san francisco.  But someone said
that everyone is doing it.  I think I'll go to the library now and tear a page
out of a book.  On second thought, I can't get to the library before it closes
today.  So I'll go tomorrow and tear two pages out, so I can make up for the
page I can't tear out today.


cya,
john

I have noticed that there are bum lookers, bum riders and bum sitters. I 
often use a nice lotion on my bum to keep it from chafing. It's those 
hippies with their salmon smelling incense that aggravate my bum. As I was 
sitting here meditating on the lack of good bottom parties I noticed that 
the shaman of events in the land of the green eyed salmons was providing 
some wonderful body care products at the latest bum event next week. I 
worry about this. I protect my bum, and I don't want invasive action 
here. Bum people can be so cruel sometimes. I can handle that, but it's 
the body protective synthetics I lack.

Alas,

Apollo

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Has anybody ever seen Geri Dahl?

Course you could do what I do and be a part of many scenes at once. Punk
for your aggression (anti-flag/ bouncing souls a couple days ago was
dope!). Metal for your self loathing (hi neurosis!). Goth and Industrial
for your cynicism, house music for your hoochie tendencies. Drum and
bass for your beer swilling, I'm cooler than you attitude, and I ain't
frontin! Psytrance for your worldly "mind expansiveness". Hardcore for
when you want to feel like you have ADD.

Or you could go raving for the all the love you receive, except when
people gang up on you behind your back and decide that you don't deserve
to be loved, and in fact deserve to be evicted from the group.

Of course you could just be yourself, for times when you want to be
simple and just feel like you.

Hope I didn't miss anyone in my labels... 

-tim   


PS-- for an added bonus can you guess what kind of music I am listening
to right now?
