Subject: [sfraves] Re: mind games nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr nrr

>
>
>Pick a number BETWEEN 1 and 11
>
>Multiply that number by 9
>
>You should now have a 2 digit number... Take the 2 digits and add them together...
>

The result of the first three instructions will be the same regardless 
of the number one originally chooses, with the exception of 11.

10 * 9 = 90
9 + 0 = 9

9 * 9 = 81
8 + 1 = 9

8 * 9 = 72
7 + 2 = 9

...

2 * 9 = 18
1 + 8 = 9

1 * 9 = 9
0 + 9 = 9

>Take that number and subtract 5 from it..
>
Now everyone has 4.

>Now each number corresponds to a letter (1 = a, 2 = b, 3 = c).... Take the number you have, figure out which letter it corresponds to and then think of a Country that begins with that letter...
>
Now everyone has "D".

How many countries are there that start with D? As far as I know there 
are four. Denmark, Djibouti, Dominica, and Dominican Republic. Of those 
four, Denmark is the clearly the first that would come to the minds of most.

>Now take the name of that Country, look at the second letter in the name, and think of an animal that begins with that letter...
>
Now everyone has an E.

What animal that starts with an "E" is most likely to come to mind 
first? Eel? Elk? Eurasian goshawk? Not likely. It will be elephant.

>Now, think of what color that Animal is...
>
This is not any leap. Everyone has elephant, so everyone now has grey.

>Now let me remind you that there are no GREY ELEPHANTS in DENMARK..
>
Of course. How could any native English speaker have arrived at anything 
else?

21266

BOSTON - Techno artist Moby was attacked by two men while signing =
autographs outside a nightclub following a radio station-sponsored =
holiday concert, police said.=20


            AP Photo=20


                  AP Photo =20
                 Slideshow: Moby=20

          =20


                  The Year in Movies
                       View the top 25 most popular movies of 2002 =20

                  Yahoo! Year in Review 2002=20
          =20

     =20

According to police and witnesses, Moby, whose real name is Richard M. =
Melville, was approached by the men about 1 a.m. Thursday outside the =
Paradise Rock Club. One of the men punched Moby in the back of the head =
and on the right side of his face, breaking the singer's glasses and =
cutting and bruising his face.=20


When two club security guards tried to stop the attack, the assailants =
sprayed a macelike substance at Moby, Moby's manager and the guards, and =
then fled, police said.=20


Moby, 37, declined medical attention.=20


The assailants said nothing during the attack, and the motive is =
unknown, said Paradise manager Jeff Marshall.=20


During the concert, Moby, a self-described pacifist, had spoken out =
against aggression and violence.=20


He wrote on his Web site that he is not angry about the attack, just =
mystified about the motive. He has asked the attackers to post an =
explanation.=20


"And if anyone sees me in the next couple of weeks and I have some big =
bruises or stitches on my face, well at least you know why," Moby wrote. =



Moby is electronic music's first bona fide superstar. His 1999 album, =
"Play," sold 10 million copies. For the past two years, the Connecticut =
native has headlined a touring festival that has featured guests such as =
David Bowie (news).=20


___=20

<P>According to police and witnesses, Moby, whose real name is Richard =
M.=20
Melville, was approached by the men about 1 a.m. Thursday outside the =
Paradise=20
Rock Club. One of the men punched Moby in the back of the head and on =
the right=20
side of his face, breaking the singer's glasses and cutting and bruising =
his=20
face.=20
<P>
<P>When two club security guards tried to stop the attack, the =
assailants=20
sprayed a macelike substance at Moby, Moby's manager and the guards, and =
then=20
fled, police said.=20
<P>
<P>Moby, 37, declined medical attention.=20
<P>
<P>The assailants said nothing during the attack, and the motive is =
unknown,=20
said Paradise manager Jeff Marshall.=20
<P>
<P>During the concert, Moby, a self-described pacifist, had spoken out =
against=20
aggression and violence.=20
<P>
<P>He wrote on his Web site that he is not angry about the attack, just=20
mystified about the motive. He has asked the attackers to post an =
explanation.=20
<P>
<P>"And if anyone sees me in the next couple of weeks and I have some =
big=20
bruises or stitches on my face, well at least you know why," Moby wrote. =

<P>
<P>Moby is electronic music's first bona fide superstar. His 1999 album, =
"Play,"=20
sold 10 million copies. For the past two years, the Connecticut native =
has=20
headlined a touring festival that has featured guests such as David =
Bowie (<A=20
href=3D"http://rd.yahoo.com/dailynews/ap/ap_en_mu/inlinks/*http://rd.yaho=
o.com/DailyNews/celeb/*http://search.news.yahoo.com/search/news?p=3D%22Da=
vid%20Bowie%22&amp;c=3D&amp;n=3D20&amp;yn=3Dc&amp;c=3Dnews&amp;cs=3Dnw">n=
ews</A>).=20

<P>
<P>___ </P></FONT></DIV></BODY></HTML>

>From: "paul gordon" To: the_emperor99@hotmail.com

>>>From: "amber daniel">
>To: lmid.cdaniel

The following short quiz consists of 4 question and will
tell you whether you are qualified to be a professional.

Scroll down for each answer.
The questions are NOT that difficult.

1. How do you put a giraffe into a refrigerator?
> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > 
> > > > > > > > > > > The correct answer is: > > Open the refrigerator, put 
>in the giraffe and close the > > door. This question tests whether you tend 
>to do simple > > things in an overly complicated way. > > > > > > > > 2. 
>How do you put an elephant into the refrigerator? > > > > > > > > > > > > > 
> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Open the 
>refrigerator, put in the elephant and close > > the refrigerator...... 
>Wrong Answer. > > > > Correct Answer: > > Open the refrigerator, take out 
>the giraffe, > > put in the elephant and close the door. > > This tests 
>your ability to think through the > > repercussions of your previous 
>actions. > > > > > > > > > > 3. The Lion King is hosting an animal 
>conference. > > All the animals attend except one. > > Which animal does 
>not attend? > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > 
> > > > > > > > > > > > > Correct Answer: > > The Elephant. The elephant is 
>in the refrigerator. > > This tests your memory. > > > > OK, even if you 
>did not answer the first three questions > > correctly, you still have one 
>more chance to show your > > true abilities. > > > > 4. There is a river 
>you must cross. > > But it is inhabited by crocodiles. > > How do you 
>manage it? > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > 
> > > > > > > > > > > > > Correct Answer: > > You swim across. > > > > All 
>the crocodiles are attending the Animal Meeting. > > This tests whether you 
>learn quickly from your mistakes. > > > > > > > > According to Anderson 
>Consulting Worldwide, > > around 90% of the professionals they tested > > 
>got all questions wrong. But many preschoolers > > got several correct 
>answers. Anderson Consulting > > says this conclusively disproves the 
>theory that > > most professionals have the brains of a four > > year old. 
> > > > > Send this out to frustrate all your smart friends. > > > > >

anything BETWEEN 1 and 11 would be 2 through 10, right?

*************************
2 x 9 =18 :: 1 + 8 = 9

4 x 9 = 36 :: 3 + 6 = 9
5 x 9 = 45 :: 4 + 5 = 9
6 x 9 = 54 :: 5 + 4 = 9
7 x 9 = 63 :: 6 + 3 = 9
8 x 9 = 72 :: 7 + 2 = 9
9 x 9 = 81 :: 8 + 1 = 9
10 x 9 = 90 :: 9 + 0 = 9
***************************

conclusion...

> > > > that begins with that letter...
> > > > >
> > > > Now everyone has an E.
> > > >
> > > > What animal that starts with an "E" is most likely
> > > > to come to mind
> > > > first? Eel? Elk? Eurasian goshawk? Not likely. It
> > > > will be elephant.
> > > >
> > > > >Now, think of what color that Animal is...
> > > > >
> > > > This is not any leap. Everyone has elephant, so
> > > > everyone now has grey.
> > > >
> > > > >Now let me remind you that there are no GREY
> > > > ELEPHANTS in DENMARK..
> > > > >
> > > > Of course. How could any native English speaker have
> > > > arrived at anything
> > > > else?

Quotes for the Week: Inspired by Random SFR List Topics...

"He was so narrow minded he could see through a keyhole with both
eyes ..."


You may easily play a joke on a man who likes to argue -- agree with
him.
                -- Ed Howe


"It was pleasant to me to get a letter from you the other day.  Perhaps I
should have found it pleasanter if I had been able to decipher it.  I
don't think that I mastered anything beyond the date (which I knew) and
the signature (which I guessed at).  There's a singular and a perpetual
charm in a letter of yours; it never grows old, it never loses its novelty
=2E... Other letters are read and thrown away and forgotten, but yours are
kept forever -- unread.  One of them will last a reasonable man a
lifetime."
                -- Thomas Aldrich

Regards,

Karina

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** :::::::: Commotion **

Beat Collective presents COMMOTION - Commotion's opening night featuring
eight DJ's spinning funky house, breaks, and other huge choons ::
Location: Rawhide, 280 7th St at Folsom :: Two dance floors and roof deck
with marquee tent:: Entertainment: Visuals and Digital Art by 47, fire
performances and dancers Time: Dance all night from 9PM - 4AM ::Main room
:: DJ Seven (Blue, Lo-RiseDJ Recordings) Monty Luke (loopwreckas, future
shock) Geno (UK) Maurice (Release) Tyler Reed (Unified Beat Theory, Qool)
Upstairs :: DJ Manks (Sonic Suffusion) Bishnu (Revolution Records) DJ Iggy
Adam Ohana (Fuel Records, Eyephunk, Marine Parade) Door: $10, dress to
impress :: Cocktails only $3 before 11 :: Don't miss this event. Hope to
see you all there ::

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D174

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Phantasm **

Count Alaric spins spooky sounds for Friday the 13th. Be afraid. No cover.
Located @ 2202 Oxygen Bar - 795 Valencia St., (Valencia & 19th), SF

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D210 San
Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Weekly: Mayonnaise **

Mayonnaise - Come and savor the creamiest house beats. Featuring resident
DJs Chonky-T, Melyss, and DJ Tonic. No cover, 21+ @ Skylark, 3089 16th
Street, (16th @ Valencia), Hours: Monday - Friday (4 pm - 2 am)

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D144 San
Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Weekly: Pop presented by Dream Chimney **

Minimal house and techno-pop to heat up the dance floor. Featuring
Resident DJs The Beat Broker & The CoWorker, resident VJ Matt Biederman
(Del Ray Arts), and international DJs & live acts. 21+. Located @ An-Sibin
DJ Bar 1176 Sutter Street, (Sutter @ Polk).

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D152 San
Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Weekly: 5 Fridays **

Truestar presents... 5 Fridays - Come shake what your momma gave you. 5
Fridays hit you with the aural gems that you've been dying to hear. Come
in and give everyone a high 5! Featuring resident DJs Namane and DJ Henry
plus rotating DJs weekly. Cover TBA, 21+, information: truestar.net
Located @ 330 Ritch Street (between 3rd and 4th off of Townsend), SF

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D216 San
Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Weekly: Sonic Fridays **

Sonic Fridays - Ten15 & Spundae bring you World-Class talent every Friday
along with rotating DJs from around the Bay Area & the globe.

DECEMBER 13 - DJ Dave Ralph plus Jonathan Ojeda, Frisky, Little Mike, Marz
Faram, and Rafael

DECEMBER 20 - The UK's James Zabiela and Boston's Steve Porter plus DJs
Madame Mercury, Spinner, Ghost, Frank Nitty, Kevin Kind, Kwashi, Scott
Carrelli, Mark Musselman, and Rafael

$20 cover, $10 before midnight w/ coupon, free before 10:30 pm, 21+.
Located @ Ten15 Folsom, 1015 Folsom Street, (between 6th and 7th)

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D221 San
Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Monthly: Nectar **

 (Second Friday of the Month) - Rowena of Risque and Yana of Walking Art
 Liquid Latex present Nectar.

Deep within a beautiful, exotic flower is a small, sweet, ambrosial
center. Rowena of Risque and Yana of Walking Art would like to introduce
Nectar; a select, fashionable and attractive crowd, in an exquisite,
sensual atmosphere, surrounded by deep, seductive house beats. You are
invited to revel in an atmosphere steeped in sensuality. You are invited
to lose yourself to engaging house music or just sit back and watch. You
are invited to be hypnotized by sultry and seductive models displaying
unique liquid latex designs.We have been meeting a lot of wonderful new
people and would like to introduce our old friends to our new friends, and
make Nectar the night for people to mingle, dance and enjoy themselves.

A note to our new guests: This is a woman-centric event being hosted by
two women. It is a place where women and couples can go and dance the
night away, chill with friends, or explore an inner sensual side. To keep
this atmosphere relaxed, fun and well-balanced we ask that each gentleman
attending Nectar come escorted by a lady. This is not a swingers club.

Cover $40 couples, $10 women, 21+

Located @ Decibel, 699 Market St. (Market @ 3rd), San Francisco, Downtown

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D275 San
Francisco, CA California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Monthly: Joyride **

Every second friday of the month. An evening of blazing hip-hop, heavy
funk, and other dance floor gems. DJs Vinnie Esparza and O-Dub bring you
"Joyride", an evening of raw funk, hip hop, vintage reggae, dancehall, and
Latin. 21+. Located @ 26 MIX 3024 Mission St., (Mission @ 26th), SF

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D195 San
Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 13, 2002 ** Weekly: Square **

Square With resident DJs Behrouz, Franky and Special Guests.

This luxurious hot spot offers a gorgeous main room with overlooking
balcony, smoking room complete with a large selection of cigars and pool
tables, full kitchen with an excellent chef, three bars and incredible
architecture dated to 1899. Firedancers and cirque style performances will
keep the scenery alive. @ Ruby Skye, 420 Mason St. (between Geary & Post)

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D115 San

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Popscene **

Mod Lang Records present...Popscene! Featuring Britpop, mod, 60s soul, new
wave, indie and electronica grooves With DJs Aaron & Jeremy. Every
Thursday Evening.

Jeremy P. Goldstein, popscene co-founder and DJ, is "excited to see the
club's popularity remain so vibrant for 5 years now. I cherish the
opportunity to share the music that is so important to me with an equally
passionate fanbase. Our crowd is really knowledgeable and we love to hear
their suggestions." Aaron Axelsen, fellow popscene co- founder and DJ
agrees. "It's been so rewarding to present this club for 5 years in a city
like San Francisco, with its rich and varied musical history, a city that
embraces diversity; a city that allows us to throw a night where our
supporters dance to a eclectic mix of music from Pulp to The Rolling
Stones to the Chemical Brothers to The Jackson 5."

Presented by the SF Weekly, popscene hosts the hottest and most unique
weekly nightclub every Thursday 10 pm - 3 am at 330 Ritch Street, where
ages 18 and over groove to the tunes of Britpop, indie, mod, new wave,
electronic and '60s soul. Popscene features dancing, cocktails, live bands
and record release parties.

Tuesday, December 31, 2002 ** Construction NYE 2003 **

Equal Opportunity Housing Project presents...  Construction NYE 2003

Construction NYE is the premier house music event for New Years Eve.

Construction NYE will take place at the beautiful Club Bas in San
Francisco's North Beach District located at 383 Bay street @ Mason. We
have three unique atmospheres of music and d=E9cor planned for this special
event. Each room features 2 bars EAW sound and the worlds top DJ talent.

In the main room DEEP CHAMBER we are proud to present the exclusive prime
time midnight set by SF most beloved DJ, Miguel Migs. This room will also
feature memorable performances by Ellen Ferrato and Moulton Studios guru
Jay J.

In the FUNK LAB, Construction is proud to present the exclusive NYE
performance of the speaker phreaker himself, Terry Mullen. With supporting
sets by Spettro, San Antonio's house prodigy, Ben Davis of 12monkeys and
Tweekin records, and David Savior.

 We will be serving up free cosmopolitan martinis all night to get that
 buzz started, and feature a complementary champagne toast at midnight
 while Miguel Migs rings in the New Year. This event will start at 9 pm
 sharp and go through after-hours for the first time in Club Bas's
 history. Get there early as every DJ set will be well worth witnessing.
 There is plenty of covered parking available directly across the street
 in the Safeway parking garage to provide a hassle free night. Tickets are
 available at www.GrooveTickets.com starting at just $45. Be sure to get
 your tickets well in advance, as this show is likely to sell out presale.
 We look forward to spending New Years Eve with everyone in a musical
 atmosphere with some of the most talented and uplifting DJs the world has
 to offer!

      In the Deep Chamber: Miguel Migs (11 pm - 1 am) Naked Music,
      Transport Ellen Ferrato (9 pm - 11 pm) Sugar, 2nd Sunday Jay J (1 am
      - 3 am) Moulton Studios Torque (3 am-close)

      In the Funk Lab: Terry Mullen (1 am - 3 am) Catalyst Recordings

      pm) 12 Monkeys, Tweekin Records David Savior (9 pm - 10 pm) Surreal
      SF

Tuesday, December 31, 2002 ** Soulive **

Mystery Machine Productions presents...Soulive Plus DJ Logic and Lettuce

Soulive is a band whose time has come. This groovy combo are trailblazers
in defining a new branch of the Hip-Hop tree. Their flawless sound fluidly
combines the soul and jazz of the past with the inventive sound of today's
hip-hop, dub, funk, and dance music. As a result, this New York City trio
is a melting pot of jazzy harmonies, soul drenched ballads, hip-hop
rhythms, and no-nonsense funk. But it is Soulive's raucous live
performances that have earned them a devoted legion of fans few of their
contemporaries can brag about. They have sold out clubs across the nation
and show no signs of letting up soon.

 Be sure to check out Soulive a.k.a. "the Greatest Band In The World" as
 they kick off 2003 at the DNA Lounge in San Francisco with DJ Logic and
 Lettuce. DJ Logic will join Soulive after sitting in with Government Mule
 the night before at the Beacon Theater in New York!

$100 includes open bar, 21+. Located @DNA Lounge, 375 11th Street (11th @
Harrison), San Francisco, Soma

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D277 San
Francisco California, USA

-------------------------------------------------------
Administrative Notes
-------------------------------------------------------

SFRaves serves the greater SF Bay Area, but reaches
beyond the local scene to all corners of the Terra
Firma - thanks to everyone whose support of and
contribution to the SFRAVES.org community - locally
--> to both poles ---> to all points along the
equator ---> as well as each longitude and latitude
perspective that makes this beautiful place we know
as Earth our home.

Please notify me regarding new events, event
changes, deprecated event information, or any other
information pertaining to events in the greater SF
Bay Area and beyond.

I look forward to hearing from you @
karina@hyperreal.org

THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every
week.

To subscribe to the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a message
to:  sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this
list:  sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or
sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

Faithfully yours, -- Karina Powers
karina@hyperreal.org

Copyright: All trademarks, product or service names,
brand names and/or logos appearing on
http://www.sfraves.org site, calendar and archives
are the property of their respective owners.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Nonsense post #1

Dude, you would have loved alaska. The salmon run was absolutely awesome 
to watch during the summer time. My brother, dad, and I would go fishing 
down at the mouth of the nome river, and would catch dozens of salmon. 
It was really cool. We're talking fresh salmon. No impurities or 
anything. Hundreds of thousands
Come to think of it, that's one of the only things I miss about alaska, 
short of snowboarding the powder on newton mountain about 30 miles 
outside of nome. Just the purity of the place was awesome. Nobody for 
miles and miles around. You would drive your snowmobile on top of the 
mountain, drop whoever's snowboarding off, go to the bottom of the 
mountain, and watch as you carved fresh untouched snow. Oh, and no trees 
either. :)
It was great.

Subject: [sfraves] The Man Who Taught His Ass to Talk nrr

Did I ever tell you about the man who taught his ass to talk? His whole
abdomen would move up and down you dig farting out the words. It was
unlike anything I had ever heard.

"This ass talk had sort of a gut frequency. It hit you right down there
like you gotta go. You know when the old colon gives you the elbow and it
feels sorta cold inside, and you know all you have to do is turn loose?
Well this talking hit you right down there, a bubbly, thick stagnant
sound, a sound you could smell.

"This man worked for a carnival you dig, and to start with it was like a
novelty ventriliquist act. Real funny, too, at first. He had a number he
called "The Better 'Ole' that was a scream, I tell you. I forget most of
it but it was clever. Like, "Oh I say, are you still down there, old
thing?'

"'Nah! I had to go relieve myself.'

"After a while the ass start talking on its own. He would go in without
anything prepared and his ass would ad-lib and toss the gags back at him
every time.

"Then it developed sort of teeth-like little raspy in- curving hooks and
start eating. He thought this was cute at first and built and act around
it, but the asshole would eat its way through his pants and start talking
on the street, shouting out it wanted equal rights. It would get drunk,
too, and have crying jags nobody loved it and it wanted to be kissed same
as any other mouth. Finally it talked all the time day and night, you
could hear him for blocks screaming at it to shut up, and beating it with
his fist, and sticking candles up it, but nothing did any good and the
asshole said to him: 'It's you who will shut up in the end. Not me.
Because we don't need you around here any more. I can talk and eat AND
shit.'

"After that he began waking up in the morning with a transparent jelly
like a tadpole's tail all over his mouth. This jelly was what the
scientists call un-D.T., Undifferentiated Tissue, which can grow into any
kind of flesh on the human body. He would tear it off his mouth and the
pieces would stick to his hands like burning gasoline jelly and grow
there, grow anywhere on him a glob of it fell. So finally his mouth sealed
over, and the whole head would have have amputated spontaneous- except for
the EYES you dig. That's one thing the asshole COULDN'T do was see. It
needed the eyes. But nerve connections were blocked and infiltrated and
atrophied so the brain couldn't give orders any more. It was trapped in
the skull, sealed off. For a while you could see the silent, helpless
suffering of the brain behind the eyes, then finally the brain must have
died, because the eyes WENT OUT, and there was no more feeling in them
than a crab's eyes on the end of a stalk.

-William Burroughs, Naked Lunch

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Happy Happy

Wow! This was a fun experience! As I said last night, I got the call last
minute, so I jumped in the shower, grabbed my records  and headed to the
party. I walked into this big old house in West Oakland, kinda near the
Noodle Factory and started looking for my friend. I saw several girls
dressed as guys, and guys dressed as girls, but I didn't see my friend. I
called him, and when I said, "where are you?" this really ugly chick in a
short dress with bright pink hair and stripped stockings said "I'm right
here!" LOL! He apologized for forgetting to tell me that this was a drag
party. I do wish I had known, cause I love theme parties, but oh well. His
tables are setup in a room where there is a band playing. They are kinda
sloppy and I figured that they were drunk, but they were having fun and lots
of folks are rocking out to them. The bass player blows his amp, so he sits
out while the rest of them play for about 1/2 hour longer. The set ends when
the lead guitarist starts bumping against the drum kit, then body checking
the rhythm guitarist and culminates with him flopping into the drums. I
loved it! They didn't break their instruments, which I've never seen in
person, but they did erupt into a cacophony of sound!
    My friend started spinning techno, then went into some trance. People
were grooving on it, and I said to him "Hey, they're loving this foofy
stuff! I tagged in and spun in a trance track. When I was just about to mix
in the second trance track, everyone left the floor! I was like SHIT! Now
what do I do? It was too late to match something different, so I had to
bring in the trace track, but no one danced to it. I told my friend "Damn, I
lost them!" I suggested that we go into some breaks to change the vibe. We
tagged back and forth, and people were digging it, but the problem was, the
wooden floor was really bouncy, and when people were dancing
enthusiastically (and drunkenly) it made the tables skip. The worst came
when this one reeeeeallly drunk long haired guy with a long beard pulled his
dress over his head, pulled off his panty hose and started jumping around
the room butt naked! I looked down at the table, since I really didn't want
to see a naked guy in front of me, but the problem was that he was jumping
so much and the needles were jumping so much that there was no way to mix. A
lot of the time, all we could do was cut from one track to the other without
mixing. Some people were so wasted that they didn't even notice, but the
ones who did were sympathetic to our challenges!
    After a while, the booze ran out and people started leaving, so I
decided that it was time to bring up the tempo. I started to drop some d&b,
and people were loving it! I tried to tag with my friend, but his stuff was
too slow to play with mine, so I spun until he had the fever again and I let
him bring the tempo back down. It was still really hard, because although
the few people who were dancing were trying to stay back from the tables,
but they were still skipping. All in all, I think that this was a great
experience for me. It was totally spur of the moment. It was a challenging
environment to play in, and above all, it was fun!

Happy  :-)

"A happy person is not a person in a certain set of circumstances,
but rather a person with a certain set of attitudes." -Hugh Downs

This seems apropo for a Dahl post, thanks Karina.

"It was pleasant to me to get a letter from you the other day.

Perhaps I should have found it pleasanter if I had been able to decipher it.

I don't think that I mastered anything beyond the date (which I knew) and
the signature (which I guessed at).

There's a singular and a perpetual charm in a letter of yours; it never
grows old,
it never loses its novelty....

Other letters are read and thrown away and forgotten, but yours are
kept forever -- unread.

One of them will last a reasonable man a lifetime."
                -- Thomas Aldrich

Subject: [sfraves] Thank you to Moksha Tribe crew for the wonderful rave party in San Francisco

Words cannot even begin to express the high that I feel this morning after
dancing to my heart's delight at the Moksha Tribe underground held in San
Francisco, called "Ouroboros." OK, I know that it is only a party, but each
person makes his or her own moments within the scene, and these moments were
special to me.

Many native Californians are jaded to their own state's special character,
but every time that I drive over the Bay Bridge into the big city I get a
thrill, even with traffic (especially at night when the city is bright).

I found the map point and my good friend, Carl (NomadicDJ to those "in the
know"; http://www.nomadicdj.com/frameset.htm) and he expressed concern over
the venue's plumbing problems when I asked him about his upcoming set.
Apparently, a pipe burst in the secondary room so all music was to be
concentrated in one area, thus taking away his DJ spot. Nevertheless, he
assured me that everything would be all right and I got my directions to the
secondary map point.

Without giving away proprietary details, I just have to say that it was
funny to be walking around in the heart of San Francisco, Market Street,
trying to find the dudes with the "green patches" at the second map point,
who had directions. I met some fellow ravers and we had a good laugh (and
some frustration) trying to find these people. We ended up at Carl's Jr, the
hamburger joint, and by happenstance found a "green patch dude" who told us
to split up into smaller groups to get to the venue nearby.

I do not know the ravers, whom I was hanging out with, but I walked up the
street with one of the guys after we got final directions, and then I
spotted the Bijou Hotel on the street corner. I insisted that we go inside
to check it out, because I know someone who works there, and it is a
happening hotel for the international crowd. My fellow raver thanked me for
letting him know about this aspect of the hospitality industry. If you are
interested, check out this link:
http://www.jdvhospitality.com/hotels/sf_bijou.html
It seems like a cool place to stay, especially if you have guests from out
of town.

Anyway, we immediately found our way over to the venue, went inside, and it
was a friendly crowd with good music and a wonderful vibe. I found one of my
friends, Mike, whom I met at The Stud last month, and we were both glad to
see each other. We danced for many beats, hung out in the smoking area, and
lounged in the chill room.

I found a comfortable chair near a fan, beside Ravin Rizz's massage table,
and spent a few moments with Mike just cooling down (The venue was hot, as
is typical with San Francisco underground rave locations). At least they had
fans!

I met many people whom I know from the scene, including Jessica, Happy,
Nick, Mikah, Osby, Tom M. (DenverhouseDJ), Michael the Red Stickman, Joey,
and of course, Apollo, and I received warm greetings and hugs from all
concerned. I am so happy right now, just basking in the warmth of human
friendship.

In addition, I am feeling glad to have someone else in my life, Mike, my new
friend who I danced beside almost all of the night. You have to understand,
usually I travel "solo" to such events, and it was a pleasure to meet up
with someone special to me. He is a native to the area, but we have similar
interests.

I do not have much else to say, other than it was a great party because it
was small and intimate (limited to 200 people). But in closing, I remember
that last week my swim instructor at the gym said that dancing is good for
your abdominal muscles, and I believe her now, because I really got into the
groove and now I feel the pain!

Good night (I mean, good morning) to all,
Greg




---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Ok to start with I want to second everything Greg VP just said... =
Ouroboros was really a wonderful party, with that small intimate vibe =
that is sometimes lost these days. I want to thank the whole crew who =
made the party possible, it seemed that there were soo many people =
working the party, handing out water, picking up trash, cleaning the =
bathrooms or just moping the water up from the floor. You guys really =
made my night.=20

We got there around 1:30 (My girl Nicole, friend Julian and I) and =
started to get our groove on to the tasty beats right away. The music =
was really great all night but I had to shake my head when I thought I =
heard the beastie boys in there..... I was right but it worked really =
well... :-) The decorations were great also, it created the perfect =
atmosphere !

Hours of Dancing, Nicole got a massage from Riz (Mondo Thanks) and we =
hung out on the sheepskin rug in the chill room meeting, got to meet and =
talk to many great new people.

When the music stopped and the lights came on, the three of us headed =
down the waterfront, we got there just in time to watch the sun come up =
and illuminate the Golden Gate Bridge.... a perfect ending to the =
perfect night. After a short stop at Mels for some nourishment we made =
the trip back out to the east bay.

Now its time to rug up in front of the warm fireplace and watch video's =
and snooze the rest of the day away.

Thanks to everyone who put this party on, for all those people we talked =
to over the course of the night.. We hope to see you all again soon.....

Love
Aussie, Nicole & Julian

 I want to add my thanks to the Moksha Tribe crew as well! Outside of the
loss of the second room due to flooding, it was great! I heard that
the water in the second room was due to rain, not a burst water pipe,
but maybe it was a broken rain gutter?

 The party was a benefit for the Larkin Street Youth Services
organization:

 http://www.larkinstreetyouth.org/index.html

 ... which I didn't know anything about before the party, but it seems
to be a valuable and needed source of aid to San Francisco's homeless
youth.

 I got layed off on Fiday, so I really needed this party to help lift my
spirits. Which it did ! I didn't pull an all nighter, but I compresed
enough dancing into the time I was there to feel some aches this
morning ( but they're good aches! ). I was the guy in the white t-shirt
with little smiley faces and a little label stuck on the collar with
"LARRY" written on it.

 Also thanks to Mike Migurski and the rest (?) of the lighting F/X crew
for not having a fog machine. And thanks to the 99% of you who actually
did not smoke tobacco on the dance floor, per the requests on the No
Smoking signs.

 Looking forward o the next Moksha Tribe event ( hopefully in drier
weather ) -

 - Larry Ching

Subject: [sfraves] Moksha Tribe review from chewy

I had fun at Moksha Tribe last night. It was my first
party, and my first time in San Francisco. It is a
really noisy place and there are lots of people. But I
had fun saying hi to all of them while we were walking
to the party.

The place was really coloful, and there were lots of
pretty lights and friendly people there. I just ran all
over the place as soon as I got there and said hi to
everyone. I found a tennis ball and then people threw
it across the dance floor and I got to chase it. I
liked chasing the ball all over =) I got a  bracelet
from joey, but it was too big for my arm and too small
for my neck, so I wore it on my back.

I took a little nap with Jessica in the chill room,
then played some more. Thankfully, no one stepped on
me, because I'm kinda short. Keri's chili was really
good, but I only ate one bean because I didn't want to
get diarrhea.

Sorry to Andy Tie Dye for barking at you, your cape was
just so colorful and I wanted to play with it. Maybe we
can play next time.

I had to leave early because it was getting too loud
and I had to go poo. But thanks Apollo, Delia, Uncle
Osby, and everyone else that played with me.  I had fun
at my first party =)

-chewy

Subject: [sfraves] Moksha Tribe Thanks You...

--=====================_26932504==_.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

On behalf of the Moksha Tribe collective I send our heartfelt thanks to all 
the dancers who attended Ouroboros last night.  I don't review our parties, 
but even with all the work involved in throwing a party I had a really 
great time myself and was able to dance a bit to every set.

The collective often talks about the excellent people who come to our 
parties, and this was no exception:  many, many good, passionate dancers, 
who bring a respectful, loving vibe -- folks we really have come to view as 
family.  All of you really rock!!!!  We were fortunate to spend an evening 
celebrating dance, music and life with the likes of you.

As you may know, there is much drama and stress preceding a party and one 
must be prepared to deal with any contingencies that arise.

Moksha had originally intended to do a relatively small, one-room party at 
the venue in SF.  After doing a thorough inspection tour of the facility we 
discovered that there was a very large storage room off the main dance 
area:  a sort of no-mans' land shared with a hotel next door but "owned" by 
neither the venue lessor or the hotel.  It was full of junk, however.  So 
seeing an opportunity for another room of music I negotiated with the venue 
owner to obtain access to half of that room.  The crew went in two weeks 
ago and hauled out what seemed like tons of garbage and then cleaned and 
prepared the space for dancing.

Along comes the typhoon from Guam or whatever.  Those of you who attended 
know that Ouroboros was in a basement, so there was a general concern that 
the whole space might be flooded in the storm.  The SF sewage system is an 
archaic deal that was never designed to deal with heavy rains.  As we were 
driving to the venue Saturday afternoon in a van loaded with equipment and 
decorations, detouring around fallen trees and flooded streets, a massive 
wind-rain event overwhelmed us right near City Hall and we were almost 
forced to pull over.  Then I get a call from the venue saying that a pipe 
had burst in the storage room and it was flooded.   When we arrived shortly 
thereafter I expected to see the whole space under water.  Fortunately, 
only the second room was affected.  We pumped it out and repaired the pipe, 
but the floors were damp and smelly and there was no guarantee that if the 
storm persisted the pipe would hold.  We decided that there really could be 
a risk of electrocution back there with all the sound and other lighting 
and went back to the one-room party.  There are times when one must make 
the best of what one is given.

But the party went off with no other problems.  We ran all night long.  No 
police. No other drama.  Just lots of good fun with a great group of ravers.

We truly hope that all of you who came had a memorable evening.  The only 
reason we do these events is to bring some light and happiness to our 
family in these often dark, and certainly damp, times.

Again, Moksha Tribe sends much love and appreciation to our extended 
family!!!!!

Apollo for Moksha Tribe.

Moksha Tribe

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Many persons have a wrong idea of what constitutes true happiness.  It is 
not attained through self-gratification, but through fidelity to a purpose."
-Helen Keller

"As long as you haven't experienced this:  to die and so to grow, you are 
only a troubled guest on the dark earth."
-Johann Wolfgang Von Goethe

"Chaos often breeds life, where order breeds habit."
-Henry Adams
--=====================_26932504==_.ALT--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ATP: Am I the only one left

I hear you. I guess I could write a small review about the b-family party
this weekend. Great crowd, cool space, beautiful people. By beautiful people
I mean that was a damn good looking crowd with such a fashionable artsy
sense of dress. If you had to explain what the younger side of the artsy
soma crowd looks like this party would be a shining example. Yum! Music I'm
sure was great, but due to some mishaps in the planning the sound was
horrible. Jay made it better but it still hurt.The energy level was really
high and people were dancing. For me it was more of a social event. It was
great to go and know less than 10 people for once. I miss those days of
anonymity. Bison Brewing provided the drinks for the night and I must say,
hard iced tea is pretty good! GFunk is a lush. Ghetto lushous indeed.

Oh and I have to add how much I love sfpd. They just don't care. I flipped a
bitch in the middle of 17th and the cop pulled me over for no front lisence
plate. I haven't even registered the car yet and when asked where the plate
was I told him the seller was looking for it. Didn't care that I didn't have
registration, proof of insurance, didn't even mention the u-turn. Just gave
me a $10 ticket and that was that. Now if only small town cops like Danville
were like that...

Now I'm at work waiting on people to get their shit done so I can get my
work done. In the meantime it's all about redesigning my gauge faces for my
car from scratch.

http://forums.vwvortex.com/zerothread?id=620957 - this is the tach for the
car. I'm hand making these using backlight (not BLACKlight) film and custom
led/fiber optic illumination. None of that ghetto green EL stuff that all
the honda kiddies use. If you have a 90 - 91.5 G60 Corrado or 90 - 93 Passat
I have gauges for you. All hand re-designed in Illustrator for clarity and
seperations.

ryan.bailey
sninesix.design
design :: www.sninesix.com
photography :: www.innocentchild.com

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ATP: Am I the only one left

i'll add my $.02 on sfpd caring/not caring.
it was halloween '00, i was up in sf to catch BT at the warfield, leaving
the show my friends decided they wanted to drive (my car, go figure). we
start heading up 5th and decide to make an illegal left onto market (well,
again, they made the decision). as they were making the left, i noticed a
cop was at the light, so about 1/2 a block down where fulton comes out, he
pulled us over.

nevermind the masses of drunkards on the street, or down at castro, or all
the people making illegal u-turns on market, he pulled us over for making
and illegal turn, didn't mind that the drive had corrective lense
requirement and wasn't wearing them, or that it was an out of state expired
license, just the illegal turn sir.

long story short, when our whole ordeal was over, he told us we could leave,
and we asked if we could make another (illegal) left back onto market from
where he had pulled us over, he said 'sure' and stopped traffic to allow us
back onto market.

i love sfpd.

-xs

Subject: [sfraves] Plur Dead?  (REPOST--Sorry Email probs)

PLUR, I suppose, sounds a little outdated and clich=E9.  However, it's a =
cornerstone of this community, just as much as "Freedom, Liberty, and =
Justice for all" is a cornerstone of our society--though both seem to be =
getting outdated.  So, I will throw out this PLUR term a bit in this =
email, just as an acronym we all hopefully agree on deserves some place =
in our dance culture.
=20
I went to an underground this last weekend.  Thrown by my favorite SF =
group.  The music was awesome, the mood of the people working the =
underground were awesome.  Everything was perfect, just as I have come =
to expect from this group, and really, SF Raves in general.
=20
Back to this PLUR thing.  The last letter is R.  Respect.  Respect that =
we are all adults, and we are all adult and capable of respecting each =
other's beliefs in this community.  If we're gay, like pot, like E, like =
K, like rum, like to dance on our hands swinging poi with our feet--it's =
all good.  We all RESPECT each other, because if we don't want to =
respect, we just walk out those front doors back into the world.
=20
So here is MY issue.  I am late 20's.  My boyfriend is late teens.  Big =
deal, love happens.  We're both very happy with each other, and both of =
us compliment the other in the most perfect of ways.  Always, we have =
been accepted for being ourselves, however, this last party, some girl =
actually berated and scorned us for our relationship.  I totally, for a =
moment, felt like I was at Polyesters.  So my question is, is PLUR =
fading, or it is just fading for me.  Any insight? =20
=20
And my advice for this chick, if you want to make people feel like they =
are in a mainstream hate club, why don't you and your prejudices just go =
to one yourself.
=20
Peace.
=20
Raf

on 12/16/02 4:04 PM, Rafeki at rafeki@procyon.us wrote:

> So my question is, is PLUR fading, or it is just
> fading for me.  Any insight?

I don't think PLUR is fading... It's just that no matter where you go, no
matter how great the community as a whole is, there will *always* be
assholes. It's human nature. However, I do think there's a lot more
hostility and negativity in the world now than there was 5 or 6 years ago,
but that's just my experience. I think it's more a reflection of the world
and the state of everyone in it, as opposed to 'the scene' - think of it as
a microcosm.

> And my advice for this chick, if you want to make people feel like they are in
> a mainstream hate club, why don't you and your prejudices just go to one
> yourself.

Because then she wouldn't be blazing new trails and spreading venom, which
would undermine her agenda.. right?  (Sorry, just playing devil's advocate
there..)

 - omid

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Plur Dead?  (REPOST--Sorry Email probs)

Well, PLUR aside, you're going to run into some rude people no matter where
you go, so just don't let it get to you. It's life in the big city. There is
a certain lack of respect in large metropolitan areas because there's just
too many people concentrated in one area.

But I know what you mean, and sometimes when people say things, we just wear
this BIG chip on our shoulders, especially me. I don't take criticism well.
I'm surprised that I haven't kicked someone's ass yet. Maybe that day will
come; hopefully not (spanking is better).

One time, at a weekly party in Oakland, this dude said, "Why are you dancing
that way, it's boring--you're just moving back and forth." As if it really
matters, but I just got really pissed off and let it ruin my evening. I
stormed off to the main bar and got drunker than a skunk. Didn't dance
anymore. That's not like me at all.

Learned my lesson from that one: as I said, blow them off (rude people). You
will never see this chick again. Just be happy with your BF--sounds like a
good relationship to me. I think she was just jealous. And envy breeds
contempt.

Greg VP



-----Original Message-----
From: Rafeki [mailto:rafeki@procyon.us]
Sent: Monday, December 16, 2002 4:04 PM
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: [sfraves] Plur Dead? (REPOST--Sorry Email probs)


PLUR, I suppose, sounds a little outdated and cliché.  However, it's a
cornerstone of this community, just as much as "Freedom, Liberty, and
Justice for all" is a cornerstone of our society--though both seem to be
getting outdated.  So, I will throw out this PLUR term a bit in this email,
just as an acronym we all hopefully agree on deserves some place in our
dance culture.

I went to an underground this last weekend.  Thrown by my favorite SF group.
The music was awesome, the mood of the people working the underground were
awesome.  Everything was perfect, just as I have come to expect from this
group, and really, SF Raves in general.

Back to this PLUR thing.  The last letter is R.  Respect.  Respect that we
are all adults, and we are all adult and capable of respecting each other's
beliefs in this community.  If we're gay, like pot, like E, like K, like
rum, like to dance on our hands swinging poi with our feet--it's all good.
We all RESPECT each other, because if we don't want to respect, we just walk
out those front doors back into the world.

So here is MY issue.  I am late 20's.  My boyfriend is late teens.  Big
deal, love happens.  We're both very happy with each other, and both of us
compliment the other in the most perfect of ways.  Always, we have been
accepted for being ourselves, however, this last party, some girl actually
berated and scorned us for our relationship.  I totally, for a moment, felt
like I was at Polyesters.  So my question is, is PLUR fading, or it is just
fading for me.  Any insight?

And my advice for this chick, if you want to make people feel like they are
in a mainstream hate club, why don't you and your prejudices just go to one
yourself.

Peace.

Raf

Hey Vishal ,its me Dustin. I recently saw you at Devotion and I still 
remember your first race at Neo Tokyo : ) The guy with the funny cap and the 
drive to dance without specific need for Dj hype. I dont know if you remember 
but at that Neo Tokyo party I was wearing hospital scrubs, that wasnt just a 
costume. I work in UCSF medical center. UCSF is both a college and a hospital 
and they have job postings on their web site, being a hospital this is the 
busy season. I know they are always hiring for several positions, some 
without prior experience. Theres some jobs that work with patients, some that 
dont, and some jobs that are in the school facilities that have nothing to do 
with hospital work. I've worked there three years now while I've been going 
to school part time. Theres lots of different cultures, age ranges, variety 
of travelling workers. An added bonus is that I have two family members who 
also work in the same facility, so if recommendations are needed just ask : ) 
 Basically I would suggest applying online for as many jobs as possible and 
posting a resume, but also I think you should pick up a real application at 
the Human resources offices. This is a little confusing because the HR office 
is at a sepearte campus, Mount Zion on Divisadero.  I'm pretty sure you could 
get directions and numbers online. Another way to go might be a temp service. 
I was first hired through a temp agency before I was an official employee of 
the hospital. In fact the temp agency, Kelly Services, is in the same Human 
Resources building on Divisadero. I hope all this info helped, my advice is 
to apply for every opportunity you see.

The best of luck Vish, 
Hope you can stay in Cali

--part1_181.13bfda25.2b3195e4_boundary--

More ravers than not expected plead not guilty




By TOM KERTSCHER
<mailto:tkertscher@journalsentinel.com>tkertscher@journalsentinel.com


Last Updated: Dec. 7, 2002

Racine - Unless things begin to turn around on Monday, the city's plan to 
settle 441 rave citation cases by cutting the fine is in trouble.
18a3c2.jpgRave
<http://graphics.jsonline.com/graphics/news/img/dec02/ravebig120702.jpg>18a3fc.jpg
Photo/<mailto:egebhard@journalsentinel.com>Erwin Gebhard
The first wave of the 441 people ticketed at a Nov. 2 rave made their 
initial appearance in Racine Municipal Court last week. Most of the people 
standing in line were waiting to plead not guilty and get another court date.
<http://graphics.jsonline.com/graphics/news/img/dec02/raveabig120702.jpg>18a41c.jpg
Photo/<mailto:egebhard@journalsentinel.com>Erwin Gebhard
Micabil Diaz (left), legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union 
of Wisconsin, talks to people waiting to enter a plea in municipal court. 
So far, 19 people have accepted a deal to plead no contest and pay a lower 
fine.
By the Numbers
Most of the people who received city citations for attending a rave party 
and had their initial appearance in Racine Municipal Court last week 
decided to fight the citation rather than accept a reduction in fines to 
$100 from $968.

The rest of those cited will have their initial court appearances on Monday 
or on Dec. 16.
18a43b.jpg441: People issued citations for being an "inmate of a disorderly 
house"
18a45d.jpg206: People scheduled last week for initial Municipal Court 
appearance
18a477.jpg147: Pleaded not guilty
18a48b.jpg40: Did not appear in court; will be convicted
18a4a0.jpg19: Pleaded no contest and agreed to pay $100 fine.

A storm of denunciation descended upon city officials after it was revealed 
that police had issued $968 municipal tickets to young adults attending a 
Nov. 2 rave, a party known for distinctive dance music and, oftentimes, 
illegal drug use.

Even city officials who supported the crackdown said the fine was too high.

In response, the city attorney's office offered to reduce the fine to $100 
for anyone who pleaded no contest to being an "inmate of a disorderly 
house." But when the first wave of those ticketed made their initial 
appearance in Municipal Court last week, only 19 of 206 took the deal.

If that trend continues on Monday and on Dec. 16, when the rest of those 
cited will make their initial court appearances, the city could be facing 
the costly prospect of hundreds of trials - or dismissing the citations en 
masse.

Assistant City Attorney Scott Lewis said he won't know what will happen 
until after the second round of court hearings that begin Dec. 18, when 
people who pleaded not guilty appear for pretrial conferences.

At that time, Lewis said, he will be able to assess how strong the evidence 
is and decide how to proceed.

With the sheer numbers involved, "I admit I'm placed in a very difficult 
position here," Lewis said.

The plea bargain obviously offered a substantial fine reduction, but many 
of those cited said last week that they refused the deal because they had 
done nothing wrong. They pointed out that only three men were arrested on 
drug charges, but everyone at the party received the municipal citation, 
regardless of how long they had been at the party or other factors.

"Basically you're guilty by association and the Constitution says you can't 
do that," said Racine attorney Erik Guenther, who is representing some of 
those who were cited.

Even those who might have considered paying the $100 to be done with the 
case decided against the plea bargain because the citation includes a 
reference to controlled substances. Although a municipal citation is far 
less serious than a criminal charge, no one wanted to have a drug-related 
offense on their record, and many were girding for a fight.

"I think we'll win. Everybody I talked to is on our side," said Laura 
Maurer, 21, of Waukesha, who plans to enter her not-guilty plea Monday.

"I feel if everybody pleads not guilty, it will get thrown out," added Kurt 
Bohman, 27, who performed as "DJ Simple" at the rave and drove six hours 
from his Minneapolis home to plead not guilty last week. "It will clog up 
the court system. It already has."

Court officials had expected no more than 100 people would plead not guilty 
last week and were unable to immediately schedule a pretrial conference for 
about half of them. The hallway outside the court clerk's office was filled 
with those pleading not guilty, many sporting multiple body piercings and a 
few who brought their toddlers.

Ald. John Engel, chairman of the Common Council's Public Safety and 
Buildings Committee, said he agreed with offering to reduce the fines, but 
said it was important that police took a hard line at the rave party in 
order to discourage future raves. He said such parties are known for 
illegal drug use and illegal drugs were found at the Racine party, which 
was held at the Tradewinds tavern.

"Are we turning into a rigid, hard-nosed community? I don't think so," 
Engel said.

Engel and other city officials acknowledged that one of the aims of the 
crackdown was to discourage anyone from ever holding another rave in 
Racine. It might have worked.

"I would never come down here again," said Joseph Johnson, 25, of Milwaukee.

Daniel Kushner, 23, of Chicago, who like Johnson pleaded not guilty last 
week, said the popularity of raves had been on the decline, partly because 
of the law enforcement crackdowns, which usually result in raves being shut 
down and party-goers being sent home.

"The golden era of the scene has passed," he said. "They've worn us down 
pretty well. There's no 'us' anymore."




Moksha Tribe

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Many persons have a wrong idea of what constitutes true happiness.  It is 
not attained through self-gratification, but through fidelity to a purpose."
-Helen Keller

"As long as you haven't experienced this:  to die and so to grow, you are 
only a troubled guest on the dark earth."
-Johann Wolfgang Von Goethe

"Chaos often breeds life, where order breeds habit."
-Henry Adams

I posted this elsewhere and it turned out better than
I thought it would when I started, so I thought I'd
share it here.

nic

--- "David A. wrote:
>   Could someone please translate this headline:
>=20
> "More ravers than not expected plead not guilty"
>=20
>   I have been having a lot of trouble figuring out
> what they were trying to
> say.  Is there an extra "not" in there??  Is the
> "expected" an accident?  Or
> do I just no longer understand english?
>=20
> 			-David

I'll try.

The way the legal game works in this country, is that
if you're 'in the dock' there's a lot of verbiage
around your rights as a citizen, but the reality is is
that the average defendant is so pressed by the weight
of the proceedings that most are *expected* to plead
out.

In other words, cave in, roll over, assume the
position....=20

It's called 'being bullied.'

because to REALLY stick up for yourself, once things
have gotten this far, is a life upside down turning
hassle, and despite the lip service given to the
'presumption of innocence' everyone around you that's
important to you will assume the worst.

that's just hella stressful, and most people in this
position just say fuck it, it's not worth it, what's
the fine so i can get the fuck out of here, so it's
*expected* that most will just give up and avoid all
that *petty* static and just quit and go back and get
on with their lives.

this is why this case is so extraordinary, it's not
just one or two people doing this, but by now,
HUNDREDS who have found the inner strength to say
BASTA, enough, this is BULLSHIT and I'm going to
follow it through to the end, no matter what the
personal cost.

Nothing like strength in numbers, eh?

Shove shit down my throat?

Here's some back, I hope you choke.

Which, btw, the DA's office in Racine is doing on this
one, god bless 'em, they signed up for this, now let
them do their jobs, hope they all get the stress boils
they're used to giving instead of getting.

Nothing I like more than the sound of a bully's
petard being hoisted, and hoisted high.

Eminem knows all about this, his whole last album has
this as its theme, which explains why he's moved so
many units, because he's not the only one that's had
enough of this time wasting crap that accomplishes
nothing except to steal value and productivity from
good people that want nothing more to just enjoy their
lives.

He's singing about it, and god bless, these people are
actually *doing* something about it, it's about time.

btw, anyone born after 1990 will have no clue what
'presumption of innocence' means, since, thanks to
Poindexter and his TIA program, everything is going to
monitored from this time forward.=20

it's the ultimate bullying tactic and whine all you
want, it will not go away, get used to it and figure
out where to go from there.

nic


The real objective is human brotherhood.=20

This is widely felt to be the case, though it is not
usually said, or not said loudly enough.=20

Men use up their lives in heart-breaking political
struggles, or get themselves killed in civil wars, or
tortured in the secret prisons, not in order to
establish some central-heated, air-conditioned,
strip-lighted Paradise, but because they want a world
in which human beings love one another instead of
swindling and murdering one another.=20

And they want that world as a first step.=20

Where they go from there is not so certain, and the
attempt to foresee it in detail merely confuses the
issue.=20

Eric Blair, London, England, 1943

it's been 60 yrs, y hasn't this happened yet?=20

We have the technology.

to settle 441 rave citation cases by cutting the fine is in trouble.

Milwaukee.

Daniel Kushner, 23, of Chicago, who like Johnson pleaded not guilty last =
week, said the popularity of raves had been on the decline, partly =
because of the law enforcement crackdowns, which usually result in raves =
being shut down and party-goers being sent home.

"The golden era of the scene has passed," he said. "They've worn us down =
pretty well. There's no 'us' anymore."

My company's holiday party was held at Cirque Du Soleil - Varekai last =
night. I've never been to one of these performances before and only =
caught glimpses of one on TV. Last night blew my mind. That was the most =
unbelievable performance I've *EVER* been to. Phantom, Les Miz and other =
such acts all pale in comparison to Cirque Du Soleil. The amount of time =
and effort placed into the production was beyond anything I could =
fathom. The costumes, the makeup, the music, the amazing gymnastic =
feats... All of it left me in complete awe. I'm really at a loss for =
words. If you haven't gone you should. From all the people I know that =
have seen the Vegas performance they said the one in SF right now blows =
it away. By far one of my favorite things I saw was the mini hot air =
balloon with the digital video projector inside. They managed to rig a =
projector inside this floating balloon and have it project on the inside =
walls. The net result was a 360 degree projection on a sphere like =
surface. That was too damn cool. That and the opening sequence with the =
guy and the net. I'll stop now. GO. GO GO GO.

ryan.bailey
sninesix.design
design :: www.sninesix.com
photography :: www.innocentchild.com=20

------=_NextPart_000_05B8_01C2A744.89CACFE0--

Subject: [sfraves] KLP: Incognita 4 the past 2 weeks (kinda long)

KLP = Kinna Late Post fyi =)

OK... so like 3 weeks ago when I went 2 Incognita... I was kinda late 'cause 
I did 1 of those group survey things in Walnut Creek & la la la... but when 
I got there 2 Sitio... Mal was on the decks upstairs & oh My goodness man... 
it was such a Dope Jungle set!!  Good Shit man!!!  He was amazing!!  I mean, 
it's like totally fun watchin' Mal spin 'cause  he's totally gets in2 it & 
totally dances behind the decks!!  LoL... he also told me that he got alota 
new vinyl that night & man... such an Awesome set!!!  I swear... if any of U 
ever see this guy around... talk 2 him about music... any kinda music... & 
there's so much knowledge this dude has that u'll walk away from that 
conversation in Awe!!!

Downstairs, Queen Agnes Bee was spinning her breakbeats & oh Wow... that set 
was so Awesome!!  She totally went from like Tribal Break Beats, to Old 
Skool Break Beats, to like New Skool Break Beats & it was jus' Awesome!!!  
But again... I did have the problem of deciding which room 2 spin in 'cause 
2 rooms of yummy beats 2 Groove 2 is jus' so confussing... but fun =)

Oh Gosh... & the people who came out during that nightwas Groovy 'cause I 
mean... the Vibe is so Dope when U come out 2 Incognita that you're jus' 
surrounded by Groovy people, ya know =)

OK... now last week was Awesome!!!  It was really Neato 2 have like alota 
musical EDM genre's presented that night...

I do have 2 say that the Killa subz crew came & fuck shit up when they 
spun!!  I 4got 2 ask Hak if he spun anything original oh oh oh oh.. & it was 
so Awesome hangin' out w/ him again!!  & Das!!  I swear man... I never get 2 
C those 2 enugh... oh oh oh.. & Proxy!!!  It was so Awesome seein' Proxy 
again!!!  Oh Gosh... & they all spun like crazy & totally Awesome sets!!

Then Rob BLiss went on upstairs after the KS Hoimes were done!!  OK... this 
was an Awesome set!!  I mean... he totally spun fuckin' hard ass Jungle 
toons then mid way in2 his set... he busted out w/ Fuckin' 2Step.... That 
was Sick!!! =)  Yum! =)  OH Gosh man... if it wasn't enough when I was 
danicin' my ass off to the Jungle.. then 2 Step came on 76 I was 
oooooooooooooh yeah!

OK... the last DJ who spun upstairs was Aphelion!!!  OK... Dope Dope Dope 
fuckin' set!!  I mean... he spun alota Diva Vocal Jungle which I totally 
Loved & oh gosh... there was this 1 song that totally blew me away, but I 
4got the name of it!!  But man... he was totally Fuckin; it up on the TAbles 
& totally jus' ooooh man... I Love it when this Dude spins!!  I mean... oh 
gosh.. we were all up there dancing 2gether: Gfunk, Veanne, Tina, hmmmm... 
alota people!!  But man...  So Dope!!! The best part was when Aphelion was 
done spinning & we were all kickin' it... he gave me a CD & ooooh man... 
Dope CD!!!  The song he spun that I Love is on there!!!  Hey... I heard he 
often spins @ gideons or whatever that venues called in the South Bay & 
hey... y'all should go check him out!!!

OK... downstair was pretty sick also!!!  The start of the night was 
Groovy!!!  Misio & some1 I 4got her name did this totaly tag set & it was 
Sick!!!  They mixed Break beats & Tribal HOuse 2gether... yum!!

OK... DJF & BabyDaddy both spun these Awesome Breakbeat sets & maybe it's 
kinda 2 far from when it happen 2 remember if they did anything special... 
but I remember they were fun sets!

BUt man... when JohnSchatz hit the decks... oooooooh wah.... Mondo 
Yum...LoL!!!  He spun Ghetto Tek & it was sick!  The Dope part of his set 
was when he mixed in this 1 song by 2 Live Crew... I 4got the name of it... 
& sped it up 2 make it beatmatch the Ghetto Tek Tunes he waws spinning & 
fuck man... so Sick!!

Another thing about last week wasx it was a nice way 2 Say Bye 2 a Really 
Groovy chic & wish her the best in Boston!!!  Oh Yeah... it was Also Dope 
seein' Ryan come out & Andrew Phelan!!  Love those guys & don't get 2 C them 
enough =(  So that was a mondo Treat 2 hang out w/ them!


Oh yeah.. early in the night.. I got 2 give Amber her Birthday present... & 
she liked it =)  Yay!!



Take Care,

Just so you know, I just got off chat with Jessica.  I esplained to her that I didn't misconstrue her words.  Once when I was stationed in Texas, I walked into a bar with some buddies of mine.  All of them were Caucasian but me.  And there were a bunch of guys with cowboy hats wearing big buckles hanging out in the bar.  One of them walked past me and sang the line from that Sesame Street song, "One of these things is not like the others..."  That made me feel VERY uncomfortable and mad!!!  Just because other people act like sheep and dress alike and follow each other around doesn't mean that other people are wrong because they don't act like sheep.I just wanted to know if she felt uncomfortable, that's all.By the way, I did make her day a little bit better :)  YAY!!Frank--- Jessica McMahan  wrote:> Boy... ** ***** DECEMBER 19TH 2002 ***** ** =
INCOGNITA.bass.INFUSED.beats.THURSDAYS=20

*TrashAmerica / Incognita Xmas Bash* $ $$ $ $$$$$ only $4.99!! $$$$$ $ =
$$ $=20

downstairs- trashamerica $2 keg beerz!=20

Kevin Parish - LIVE PA Kevin makes music that gives to almost all types =
of electronic music. Past live shows have been any combination of live =
pop karaoke to his own pop songs, weird noise played on Nord, and =
electronic music with beats. His singing voice invokes a hodgepodge of =
emotions. There is usually an element of sarcastic humor in the music, =
and in the lyrics for the pop songs... "Your tax dollars pay to keep =
people in jail for growing weeds, while you cruise around in your big =
pink hot rod burning gas, just like me inside your furnace heart"... =
<http://www.kevinparish.com>=20

Spooky ruben - LIVE PA Wakey Wakey, Guten Morgen, Buenos Dias..."Bed" =
and "Breakfast" have arrived! Spookey Ruben's latest dual release =
embodies a comprehensive 24 track compilation of his works 1998-2001, =
where each song depicts an hour in a day (BED: 1am -12pm, BREAKFAST: =
1pm-12am) according to Spookey's own warped imagination. Certain tracks =
feature the distinctive touches of luminaries such as John McEntire and =
Doug McCombs of Tortoise, Eric Matthews, Andy Chase as well as Jim =
Gilmour of Canadian prog rock legend SAGA. In both "Bed" and "Breakfast" =
Spookey's musical explorations wander even further into the past and =
further into the future offering the listener what Spookey calls: "a new =
kind of music." <http://www.hi-hat.ca/promo/spookeybio.html>=20

TEMP - LIVE PA In addition to working on solo projects and hosting their =
***TrashAmerica events, Kevin Parish and Skip Found Teli make music =
together. Kevin's pop sensibility and Skip Found Teli's aptitude for =
musical obscurity combine the staccato rhythms of electro with =
simplistic melody and harmonic tension in a tribute to =
musical/mechanical innvovators of the 20th century. Look for T.E.M.P. =
'+1 [4:01] edit on the Mute 'Pre-set' comp in January =
<http://www.mute.com/pre-set>=20

Paedofile - DJ SET Originally released on the NoFuture offshoot SKINT =
funded label TRASH, 'The Kids Are Alright' saw aural pervert and =
cut'n'paste chaos theorist DJ Paedofile showcasing his dodgy sense of =
humour and disturbed sound (de)constructions. Aesthetically affiliated =
with the atrocity electronica of V/VM, his freeform electronic =
skullduggery provides an entertainingly disturbed array of manhandled =
samples fidgeting voices manipulated to sound like disturbed insects, =
distortion stretched to breaking point, dislocated voices that blows =
away conventional musical wisdom in a sound storm of 'fuck you' =
fortitude. [Jon B.]=20

Havoc - DJ SET One of the major players in the SF music scene, Havoc =
promotes major events and DJs. For more info, check out Compression. =
<http://www.clubcompression.com>=20

Upstairs - incognita breakbeats & electro Cybrid - LIVE PA Cybrid is a =
live-performance collaboration between SF Bay Area artists =
Audioelectronic <http://www.protolab.com/audioelectronic> and Skoop =
<http://yojimg.net/Music.> Cybrid is dedicated to exploring the =
interface between man/machine improvised live electronic performance, =
noise manipulation, feedback loops, melodic content, and funky electro =
beats. <http://www.wearecybrid.com>=20

and last but definitely not least, dj sets from ....=20

Sheztek - moksha tribe=20

Razz - moksha tribe=20

Donna Matrix - halflife, freebeats=20

Hi Amber and all of you that joined us for another SCORCHING performance by
the S.U.N. Project!

It's Thursday and we're just now recovered from an amazing last saturday
night with Sun Project, dutch, maxx, uphonic, masonic, michael anthony,
b.smiley, irina, and toires.  wow.

thank you to everyone that contributed their energy and positive vibrations
to one hell of a night!  the dancefloor on both levels was packed with happy
people going for it.  nice to have you all along for the journey!

Sun Project are truly unique among any techno or trance artists.  If you had
seen them before, or if it was your first time, it was another
mind-blowing-full-on performance.  we thank Sun Project profusely for flying
all this way just for our (((THUMP))) party - their only US appearance in
2002.

we've finally fired up the FORUMS again on our site so if you want to join
in the discussion about the sun project party, or any thing else about our
radio shows, parties, gear, whatever, check em out on our site:
http://www.thumpradio.com/forums.cfm

finally, get ready for another great (((THUMP))) on 1.1.03 with Olli Wisdom
of Spacetribe fame - one of the best full-on producers and 5th dimension of
trance navigators on the planet!  olli rips!
http://www.thumpradio.com/thumpparty.cfm


peace for a great holiday season to all!

-brian

    mmmmm. . .=20

        i know what you're thinking. . . but anyway. . . : )


    So i've been workin on my car a ton lately (weather permitting). ..  =
i have a reg old civic sohc vtec, 2 dr, 99, etc etc. . . and I seized =
the motor a couple weeks or so ago. i'm just not easy on stuff usually. =
. . so I figure, if it broke, then i gotta make it so it won't, not like =
i need to be more gentle. . . that's not really me. . . no fun either. . =
.=20
    So I've really been looking for a Skunk2 cam, gear (not really =
needed now but if I found one I'd buy it), I want skunk  valve springs n =
Ti retainers, and skunk valves. Since I've pretty much torn my entire =
lil car apart, I've already ported my heads, I should have some mugen =
headers sometime soon, I'm about to clean up my intake manifold (damn =
stock casting work). . .
I "may" need new pistons, I saw some type-r ones I can prolly get for =
not too much. My guess is I cracked one also, rings should be replaced =
regardless, but I'll see if some piston sets kinda fall into my lap =
anytime soon.
    exhaust is easy. . . simple race cat, n bomb exit, or something =
similar (maybe APEXi or Skunk). . . I neeeeeeeeeeed a new ecu, skunk or =
apexi most likely, but I've found some vtec controllers I might pick up. =

    I am looking for skunk parts tho, stage 2. . . it's such a bitch =
getting sohc parts in most places, and in others they just charge =
waaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaay too much. seriously, like 550 for a single cam. . =
. i bet I can get it for less than half that. . . I'd like to have a =
better relation with my local shop y'know. . . but if I do everything =
myself and get everything for less than they could give it to me. . . =
well, they're good for comparison I suppose.
  =20
    I'm still working on some adj. coilovers so I could make up the sag =
from my stereo, possibly a fatter rotor kit, some carbon pieces (front =
lip, rear lip, hood, this and that). . . I know I'll fry my clutch =
within a month or so after I get everything together. Cars are so simple =
to work on. . . I'm about to have my other truck fixed (chevy of =
course), and i'm thinking about a cage n racing my lil honda. . . not =
drag tho, like course, track, autocross, whatever. . . i'm not exactly =
prepared for it yet, but I still have my race itch from motocross, but I =
kinda need use of parts I tend to break. . .=20

    but yeah. . .  if anyone has any info on skunk2 stage 2 engine =
components for a sohc vtec civic. . . then get back to me. . .=20

    i never left this list either. . . my laptop just died, and I didn't =
have any choice but to get another (which should have been here today). =
. . and most of my off time's been spent setting my finances up for some =
things I knew were coming up. . . damn I'm happy I did that. . .=20

    hope all is well. . . stuffs all mutherfuckin wonderful here. . .=20

: )

hehe

arycK

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Rising **

Deep house featuring Brian Hamilton, Paolo, Sonda, Yedi, John Conrad, and
Burn 1. 21+. Located @ An-Sibin DJ Bar 1176 Sutter Street, (Sutter @
Polk).

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D151
San Francisco California, USA

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Altruity Happy Hour **

Thursdays (Early Evening Happy Hour) - Altruity Happy Hour Happy Hour
featuring resident DJs Rocket Morton & DJ Hawthorne plus guest DJs, live
jazz & special performances. Art Gallery Reception showcasing local
artists every week. Live cooking show and exotic appetizers served by
chefs from San Francisco's best restaurants. $5 cover, 21+ Located @ Cloud
9, 34 7th Street, (7th @ Market), San Francisco, Soma

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D271 San
Francisco California, USA

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Collective **

Herve, Mariam & Benito present...Collective

Film: Spoken Word: Lounge: Dance Featuring your hosts Kallie Castro,
Candice Bao, Adrienne Marie LaBonte (7x7 Mag), Susie Im, Abdul Qudus
(Newvibe.com), Elie & Michael (Sophie's MetroSoul). Lyell Perry, Pearl
Verzosa, Kadidja Yansane, Sarah Lee Peterson, Ahmed Kamara, Brian Gadsden,
David Roach (Oakland Film Society), Karen Lapinski. Film screenings start
at 8PM. Spoken Word in the back room after screenings. Party starts at
9PM. Screenings are free. Featuring DJs Jerry Ross (Sophie's), Daymitreeus
(L'Originale), and Daniela (Soul Cafe) spinning soul, nusoul, neosoul,
souljazz, R&B, and hip-hop.  $10 after 10 pm, 21+ The Cellar, 685 Sutter
Street. (Sutter @ Taylor), San Francisco. Lower Nob Hill

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D264 San
Francisco California, USA

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Passenger **

Every Thursday, join us for excursions to the deeper sounds of jazz, house
and soul with resident DJs Paul Craven (On The One) and Capital A.
DECEMBER 5 - The Passenger Five Year Anniversary Party featuring DJ MFR
(Transport Recordings) along with residents Capital A, Paul Craven,
Takeshi, Kazu, Dice, and special guests. Take off on a musical journey
where the drum is your guide and the destination is your soul. Nu Jazz,
Soul, Deep House, Brazilian, latin and uptempo madness on the dancefloor!

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D145 San
Francisco California, USA

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Faith **

Every Thursday Night. Faith - With Resident DJs Blackstone, Ruben Mancias,
Jay-R & Larry, plus special guests in the main room. Free before 10:30
with flyer, $10 after, or without flyer, 18+. Located @ 715 Harrison
Street, (Harrison @ 3rd), SF

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D219 San
Francisco California, USA

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Monthly: Lucky **

(Third Thursday of the Month) - Forward Thought presents...lucky - A
multifarious mid-tempo monthly. With residents John Paul, Enzyme, and Dom
Some droppin' the breaks, broken beats, 2-step and everything in between.

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** GZA **

Mystery Machine Productions presents GZA, Plus J-Live and Casual.
Lyrical swordsman GZA/Genius wields the microphone with a killer kung fu
grip and spits out lyrics faster than light speed turbo overdrive. This
Staten Island native comes with the goods that true hip-hop heads love to
hear - raw, dirty beats and airtight lyrics. A hardcore artist who deals
with subjects of guns, drugs, and the ghetto, GZA presents his
well-disciplined flow with double-edged rhymes and lyrical precision.
GZA started bustin' rhymes as a kid with his younger cousins Prince Rakeem
the RZA and Ol' Dirty Bastard to eventually form what would become known
as the Wu-Tang Clan. With GZA leading this loose collective of MCs,
including Ol' Dirty Bastard, RZA, Method Man, Raekwon, Ghostface Killah,
U-God, Inspecta Deck and Masta Killa, the Clan soon became hip-hop's
reigning monks of doom. But the grandfather of the Clan set himself apart
from the pack with his original style, flow and lyrical content. He's not
only a very mysterious Wu member but also a sharp one standing alone in
hip-hop's lyrical population as a unique voice. 21+.

 Located @ Justice League, 628 Divisadero Street, (Divisadero @ Hayes
 Street), San Francisco, Western Addition

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D328 San
Francisco California, USA
