Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Popscene **

Mod Lang Records present...Popscene! Featuring Britpop, mod, 60s soul, new
wave, indie and electronica grooves With DJs Aaron & Jeremy. Every
Thursday Evening.

Jeremy P. Goldstein, popscene co-founder and DJ, is "excited to see the
club's popularity remain so vibrant for 5 years now. I cherish the
opportunity to share the music that is so important to me with an equally
passionate fanbase. Our crowd is really knowledgeable and we love to hear
their suggestions." Aaron Axelsen, fellow popscene co- founder and DJ
agrees. "It's been so rewarding to present this club for 5 years in a city
like San Francisco, with its rich and varied musical history, a city that
embraces diversity; a city that allows us to throw a night where our
supporters dance to a eclectic mix of music from Pulp to The Rolling
Stones to the Chemical Brothers to The Jackson 5."

Presented by the SF Weekly, popscene hosts the hottest and most unique
weekly nightclub every Thursday 10 pm - 3 am at 330 Ritch Street, where
ages 18 and over groove to the tunes of Britpop, indie, mod, new wave,
electronic and '60s soul. Popscene features dancing, cocktails, live bands
and record release parties.

Thursday, December 19, 2002 ** Weekly: Kit Kat **

(Every Thursday Night) - Kit Kat introduced the weekly party concept to
San Francisco in March 1989 and against all odds established itself as the
only Thursday night party worthy of a monster sweat. Today Kit Kat sits on
a Richter proof funk foundation which is shaken to the core by local
fanatics determined to dance their ass off. This party has inexplicably
managed to elude the weekend warrior virus and has a balls to the wall
energy behind it. By default The End Up provides a comfortable who cares
what you are wearing atmosphere, so all attitude inevitably gets checked
at the door. The party gets started right away and peaks when the local
after hour posse swings on to the dance floor and pushes the elevator
above cloud line in the nick of closing time.

The knobs are manhandled by resident DJ Marc Jellybear whom in turn passes
the closing baton to rotating guests Simon, Garth, Miguel Migs, Jonene,
Wyatt Earp & John Howard. In addition the club hosts monthly special
events with the next level of over hyped DJs that have been, however,
thoroughly Kit Kat tested and do in the end justify having to pass the hat
around for business class airfare.

Overall a guaranteed must call in sick in the next few hours experience.
To join the guest list & receive passes via e-mail:
kitkatVIP@sbcglobal.net

time: 10:30 pm - 4:30 am Free before 11 pm, $12 cover after, 21+ Located @
The End Up, 401 Sixth St., Corner of 6th and Harrison Streets, San
Francisco - SOMA

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D289 San
Francisco California, USA

Tuesday, December 31, 2002 ** Spundae presents...Spundae: Birth of a New
Year **

      Spundae presents... Spundae: Birth of a New Year Birth of a New Year
      After one year of absence, we are excited to be back at our original
      new years venue 1015 to celebrate Spundae style. In his first SF
      appearance, we welcome Armin Van Buuren who was voted #5 DJ in the
      world by DJ magazine, to help us ring in the new year with a 3 hour
      DJ set. Along side with Armin are no other than Cristopher Lawerence
      and Donald Glaude.

      Sign up for a chance to WIN tickets to this event!

There will be a total of 5 rooms with some of the best sound, lights,
visuals and lasers in San Francisco along with a midnight balloon drop,
confetti cannons, and much more. We'll see you on the dance floor!
Mainroom: SPUNDAE STARSHIP Armin Van Buuren voted "#5 DJ in the world" by
DJ Magazine (Netherlands) Christopher Lawrence voted "best American DJ" by
Dance Star USA (moonshine, LA) Donald Glaude (moonshine, Seattle) Jonathan
Ojeda (spundae reckords)

Upstairs: Ellen Ferrato voted #3 "favorite san francisco DJ" by Nitevibe
(2nd Sunday) Jeno voted #4 "favorite san francisco DJ" by Nitevibe
(wicked) Garth voted #8 "favorite san francisco DJ" by Nitevibe (wicked,
grayhound) Markie (wicked) Norman Stradley (2nd sunday) Bassment: QOOL
AFTERHOURS Spesh, Jondi, Scott Carelli, Mark Musselman, and Jonathan
Beech. Frontroom: 70's, 80's and club classics Rafael spins a 6 hour set
Blueroom: VIP ROOM Sound provided by Mainroom DJs

$40 - PRE-SALE TICKETS till december 16th inlude express line entrance,
access to four rooms, and a champagne toast at midnight $99 - VIP TICKETS
include express line entrance, access to five rooms, a champagne toast at
midnight, an open bar from 10 pm till 1:45 am courtesy of SF Station, hors
d'oeuvres courtesy of Shadow Lounge, and access to a private lounge
overlooking the mainroom. For more info and pre-sale tickets please go to
spundae.com or 1015.com. time: 9 pm - 6 am admission: $40 presale, $99
VIP, 21+ tickets & information: spundae.com or www.1015.com

Located @ Ten15 Folsom, 1015 Folsom Street, (between 6th and 7th)

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D220 San
Francisco California, USA

Tuesday, December 31, 2002 ** Construction NYE 2003 **

Equal Opportunity Housing Project presents...  Construction NYE 2003

Construction NYE is the premier house music event for New Years Eve.

Construction NYE will take place at the beautiful Club Bas in San
Francisco's North Beach District located at 383 Bay street @ Mason. We
have three unique atmospheres of music and d=E9cor planned for this special
event. Each room features 2 bars EAW sound and the worlds top DJ talent.

In the main room DEEP CHAMBER we are proud to present the exclusive prime
time midnight set by SF most beloved DJ, Miguel Migs. This room will also
feature memorable performances by Ellen Ferrato and Moulton Studios guru
Jay J.

In the FUNK LAB, Construction is proud to present the exclusive NYE
performance of the speaker phreaker himself, Terry Mullen. With supporting
sets by Spettro, San Antonio's house prodigy, Ben Davis of 12monkeys and
Tweekin records, and David Savior.

 We will be serving up free cosmopolitan martinis all night to get that
 buzz started, and feature a complementary champagne toast at midnight
 while Miguel Migs rings in the New Year. This event will start at 9 pm
 sharp and go through after-hours for the first time in Club Bas's
 history. Get there early as every DJ set will be well worth witnessing.
 There is plenty of covered parking available directly across the street
 in the Safeway parking garage to provide a hassle free night. Tickets are
 available at www.GrooveTickets.com starting at just $45. Be sure to get
 your tickets well in advance, as this show is likely to sell out presale.
 We look forward to spending New Years Eve with everyone in a musical
 atmosphere with some of the most talented and uplifting DJs the world has
 to offer!

In the Deep Chamber: Miguel Migs (11 pm - 1 am) Naked Music, Transport
Ellen Ferrato (9 pm - 11 pm) Sugar, 2nd Sunday Jay J (1 am - 3 am) Moulton
Studios Torque (3 am-close)

In the Funk Lab: Terry Mullen (1 am - 3 am) Catalyst Recordings Spettro
(11:30 pm - 1 am) San Antonio TX Ben Davis (10 pm - 11:30 pm) 12 Monkeys,
Tweekin Records David Savior (9 pm - 10 pm) Surreal SF

City Streets: Hip Hop Hosted By Nemesis Entertainment's Jay B and DLUX

time: 9 pm - afterhours admission: presale tickets start at $45, 21+
tickets & information: www.GrooveTickets.com

Located @ B=E2s, 383 Bay Street, (between Powell and Mason)

http://www.bas-space.com, North Beach
http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D245 CA
California, USA

Tuesday, December 31, 2002 ** Soulive **

Mystery Machine Productions presents...Soulive Plus DJ Logic and Lettuce

Soulive is a band whose time has come. This groovy combo are trailblazers
in defining a new branch of the Hip-Hop tree. Their flawless sound fluidly
combines the soul and jazz of the past with the inventive sound of today's
hip-hop, dub, funk, and dance music. As a result, this New York City trio
is a melting pot of jazzy harmonies, soul drenched ballads, hip-hop
rhythms, and no-nonsense funk. But it is Soulive's raucous live
performances that have earned them a devoted legion of fans few of their
contemporaries can brag about. They have sold out clubs across the nation
and show no signs of letting up soon.

Be sure to check out Soulive a.k.a. "the Greatest Band In The World" as
they kick off 2003 at the DNA Lounge in San Francisco with DJ Logic and
Lettuce. DJ Logic will join Soulive after sitting in with Government Mule
the night before at the Beacon Theater in New York!

$100 includes open bar, 21+. Located @DNA Lounge, 375 11th Street (11th @
Harrison), San Francisco, Soma

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D277 San
Francisco California, USA

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii


WENT TO A PARTY, MOM

(please read all the way to the bottom and sign your name)

I went to a party, And remembered what you said. 

You told me not to drink, 

Mom So I had a Sprite instead.

I felt proud of myself, The way you said I would, That I didn't drink and drive, 

Though some friends said I should.

I made a healthy choice, And your advice to me was right, 

The party finally ended, And the kids drove out of sight.

I got into my car, Sure to get home in one piece, 

I never knew what was coming, 

Mom Something I expected least.

Now I'm lying on the pavement, 

And I hear the police-man say, 

The kid that caused this wreck was drunk, 

Mom, his voice seems far away. 

My own blood's all around me, As I try hard not to cry. 

I can hear the paramedic say, This girl is going to die. 

I'm sure the guy had no idea, While he was flying high, 

Because he chose to drink and drive, Now I would have to die.

So why do people do it, Mom? Knowing that it ruins lives? 

And now the pain is cutting me, Like a hundred stabbing knives. 

Tell sister not to be afraid, Mom.  Tell daddy to be brave, 

And when I go to heaven, Put Daddy's Girl on my grave.

Someone should have taught him, 

That its wrong to drink and drive. 

Maybe if his parents had, I'd still be alive. 

My breath is getting shorter, Mom I'm getting really scared. 

These are my final moments, And I'm so unprepared. 

I wish that you could hold me Mom,

As I lie here and die. I wish that I could say, 

" I love you, Mom!" So I love you and good-bye.

 

MADD IS HOPING TO GET 5,000 SIGNATURES ON THIS, THEN

PASS IT ON TO PRESIDENT BUSH. ! PLEASE SIGN.

When this petition has reached 5,000, please return it to: 

MADD P.O. Box 541688 Dallas, TX 75354-1688 

mailto:info@madd.org 1-800-GET-MADD (1-800-438-6233)

If you receive this petition and do nothing but delete it, 

your selfishness knows no bounds. Signing is such

a small effort to make. After you have read the poem,

please add your name at the bottom.

And never forget, DON'T EVER DRINK AND DRIVE, not even once, 

thinking that it won't matter. 

IT DEFINITELY WILL MATTER!!!

1. Copy the entire e-mail. 

2. Paste it into a new e-mail. 

3. SIGN YOUR NAME AT THE BOTTOM.

4. Then send it to everyone you know.

From sfraves-return-97036-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org Fri Dec 20 12:20:21 2002
Return-Path: <sfraves-return-97036-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org>
Delivered-To: sfraves-archive@hyperreal.org

Mailing-List: contact sfraves-help@hyperreal.org; run by ezmlm
Precedence: bulk
X-No-Archive: yes
list-help: <mailto:sfraves-help@hyperreal.org>

Received: (qmail 34904 invoked from network); 20 Dec 2002 12:20:20 -0000
Message-ID: <3E030B81.3050102@antitux.net>
Date: Fri, 20 Dec 2002 04:22:25 -0800
From: John Dee <antitux@antitux.net>
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.0.2) Gecko/20021120 Netscape/7.01
X-Accept-Language: en-us, en
MIME-Version: 1.0
To:  sfraves@hyperreal.org
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] High rants of the AntiTuX, Part 1

Hrm, well, I'm leaving the bay area soon. I got laid-off from netscape 
last wednesday. It was a great job. I loved it, and I learned alot. 
Anyhow, I'm gonna be moving to phoenix, and do the college thing. It's 
actually going to be an experience for me, being as I didn't even 
graduate high school, or get my GED.

I moved out here when I was 18. I was newly married, and had just taken 
a job at netscape as the head sysadmin of iPlanet learning solutions. 
That job sent me all over the world, filled my passport with stamps, and 
taught me more about how things *REALLY* work in a business than any 
schooling could. I was forced to mature quickly, and adapt to all that 
which life threw at me.

All these great things, have happened to me since I moved out here. My 
daughter was born, I was able to finally pay off all my debts, and I met 
a great group of friends in the rave community. I learned that the only 
person who can really help someone is themselves, and no matter what you 
care, you can't change, or help anyone. The only person that can help 
someone is themselves, and all you can do is give them the tools to 
solve their own problems.

I've also had terrible things happen to me since I moved here. I lost my 
wife to a divorce, and have been fighting for custody of my little girl 
for the last few months. I've been hosed by roommates on rent, 5 days 
before it was due, dealt with depression, and even tried to commit 
suicide once, because of these.

All these lessons taught me something I never really realized until I 
lost everything that I held dear. I realized that the tech industry 
isn't for me, and that I'm much better at helping people than I am at 
fixing, coding on, or just doing generic work with computers. I realized 
that the reason I got into the tech industry wasn't because it was a 
labor of love, but because it was something that boosted my ego, and 
made me feel good. Kinda funny for a kid who dropped out of high school 
when he was in 11th grade, and never got his GED.

In the last few months, through all the turmoil I've gone through, I've 
found some sort of inner-peace, which helped me grow as a person. I 
think I've matured and grown as a person to such a point I'm ready to 
take that next step. Meditation, dancing, and working on the abilities 
that the gods gave me have really helped me move beyond the depressions, 
fears, and doubts in my life.

I'm going to go back to live with my parents, go to college, and do a 
double-major in philosophy and phsychology. With the tools I get with 
those, I'll be able to better understand myself, and be able to help 
those who are struggling with their own personal demons. I'm already the 
emotional rock which a lot of people come to, but through hard work and 
my own personal growth, I'll be able to handle it much better.

I don't know what type of rave community is out in the phoenix, arizona 
area, but I'm looking forward to joining it, and maybe bringing some of 
the joy and peace that I was given out here, there.

I don't have a concrete date for when I'm going to leave, but it'll 
definitely be by the end of january. I want to go there, get a car 
(which I haven't had), get a nice job, and get everything in order so I 
can enroll in college and begin training to fulfill my life's dream of 
helping others figure out how to help themselves.

Everyone I've spoken to about leaving has been so supportive, and I've 
picked up some great advice on how to begin this journey. Emotionally, 
spirtually, and mentally, I know I'm ready. I've already hit 
rock-bottom, so the only place I can go from here is up. :)

Anyhow, drop me a line if you want to hang out, or just chat sometime 
about random stuff. Also, if you have any insight into the community out 
there in that area, please let me know. I would love to hook up with 
some great crews out there, and continue sharing the love I recieved 
from you all.

It's definitely been a an adventure, and I look forward to seeing where 
this ride is going to take me next..



---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

when I chased the last Corona down with gin and rumplemintz.

another round of Stoli and some water from the sink.

I got beaten up by lesbians, then threw up on the bar.

So the bouncers threw me out, and I spent the night in jail,
but at least I didn't go home buzzed, or forward this email.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Winter Solstice Marathon on KZSU

Today (all day Fri) and tomorrow (Sat) till 6am KZSU is hosting the
Winter Solstice Dance Music Marathon, celebrating the longest night
of the year.  Tune in for the remainder of 30 hours of continuously
mixed dance music from 20 DJs from the Bay Area and beyond!  You know
the drill, 90.1 fm or stream thru http://realaudio.stanford.edu.
Follow the action via our webcam, http://studio.stanford.edu (or
http://kzsu.org/~dougm/testcam)

Lots of info (including complete line-up) here:


2002 WINTER SOLSTICE MUSIC MARATHON ON KZSU 90.1FM

Time:		Friday 12AM - Saturday 6AM
Dates:		12/20/02-12/21/02, Winter Solstice
Place:		KZSU Stanford, 90.1FM
Internet:	http://www.kzsu.org
Listen:		http://kzsulive.stanford.edu

This is the 10th Anniversary of the Winter Solstice Music Marathon on
KZSU.  We've invited over 20 underground Bay Area DJs to continuously
mix dance music to celebrate the first day of Winter.

THIS YEAR'S MARATHON:

Friday
0000-0130	ALONZO (Audio Abuse, Phuture Now)
0130-0300	DONOVAN (Mixed Elements)
0300-0430	LU-ROB (Santa Barbara)
0430-0600	DJ CANTOS (s:one, selekta.com)
0600-0730	DEAN (Mixed Elements)
0730-0900	CK (Sister SF, Phuture Now)
0900-1030	MOODY EVA (GoodBeats, Phuture Now)
1030-1200	CAMERON (GoodBeats)
1200-1330	CHRIS LOBSINGER (Proton Radio)
1330-1500	DAVID FOLEY (Kings of Tomorrow/Deep Vision)
1500-1630	MATT MAU (Kings of Tomorrow/Deep Vision)
1630-1800	BERNARD CABIGNON (Kings of Tomorrow/Deep Vision)
1800-2100	SANDY RIVERA (Kings of Tomorrow/Deep Vision - NYC special guest)
2100-2230	JESSE MARTINEZ (Hi-Fi Lounge, Phuture Now)
2230-0000	MUSTAFA (Onda Unda, Phuture Now)

Saturday
0000-0130	ARTURO GARCES (Funky Tekno Tribe, Phuture Now)
0130-0300	DHYAN MOELLER (Drone Muzic, Phuture Now)
0300-0430	DEREK SCOTT - live PA (Trax Cafe) and E.B.E. (Phuture Now)
0430-0600	DYNO (San Jose's Deep, Funky Techno Tribe, Phuture Now)

ABOUT THE HOSTS:

Current KZSU DJs J.C. (An Epiphany of Sound), Eric (Poptronica), Jacki-O
(Big Love Show), Mehrshad (Super Happy Fun Music Show), and friends, will
be the hosts on your 30-hour journey.

ABOUT THE MARATHON:

The Winter Solstice Music Marathon began in 1992 with a 24-hour event that
showcased some of the first DJs to play house/acid-house music in the San
Francisco underground.  Those DJs included now-legedary DJs such as Spun,
Rick Preston, Tony, Garth, and Jeno.  We are proud, ten years later, to be
continuing in the tradition of the first marathon.

ABOUT KZSU:

KZSU, 90.1FM, Stanford, is one of the Bay Area's leading college radio
stations.  We have a long tradition of broadcasting independent music, and
the Winter Solstice Marathon is one example of our efforts to represent
non-commercial music to the airwaves.  Our station can be heard in many
parts of the East Bay (Oakland, Hayward, Castro Valley, Fremont) and
Peninsula (San Mateo, Redwood City, Palo Alto, Sunnyvale, and some parts of
San Jose & San Francisco) on your dial at 90.1FM.  We are also a leading
Internet-streaming station - please visit http://kzsulive.stanford.edu

FOR MORE INFO ON GUEST DJs:

DJ Donovan			http://www.donovansf.com
Mixed Elements			http://www.mixedelements.com
PhutureNow Productions		http://www.phuturenow.net
Kings of Tomorrow Records	http://www.kingsoftomorrow.com
OndaUnda Records		http://www.ondaunda.com
Goodbeats Productions		http://www.goodbeats.com
Sister SF Collective		http://www.sistersf.com
El Otro Mundo			http://www.elotromundo.com
Proton Radio			http://www.protonradio.com
DJ Cantos			http://www.djcantos.com

-- 
"An Epiphany of Sound" - 90.1 FM Thursdays from 9AM-Noon Pacific.
(Also on the web at http://kzsulive.stanford.edu/).  Playlists
and humor list archives at http://www.kzsu.org/~dougm

"Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of
KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that effect.)

Tengo un poco dreidel. Lo hice fuera de la arcilla. Y cuando es seca y
alista, mi dreidel que jugar=E9. Dreidel del dreidel del dreidel del Oh, lo
hice fuera de la arcilla. Dreidel del dreidel del dreidel del Oh, mi dreidel
que jugar=E9. Tiene un cuerpo encantador, con cortocircuito de la pierna ta=
n y
enrarece, y cuando consigue todo el cansado, cae y entonces gano. El dreidel
del dreidel del dreidel del Oh, con de la pierna cortocircuito tan y
enrarece, dreidel del dreidel del dreidel del Oh, cae y entonces gano. Mis
dreidel siempre juguetones. Ama bailar y hacer girar. Un juego feliz del
dreidel, viene juego ahora vamos comenzar. Dreidel del dreidel del dreidel
del Oh, ama bailar y hacer girar. El dreidel del dreidel del dreidel del Oh,
viene juego ahora vamos comenzar. Tengo un poco dreidel. Lo hice fuera de la
arcilla. Y cuando es seca y alista, mi dreidel que jugar=E9. Dreidel del
dreidel del dreidel del Oh, lo hice fuera de la arcilla. Dreidel del dreidel
del dreidel del Oh, mi dreidel que jugar=E9.=20

Subject: [sfraves] Cirque Du Soliel = les miz, phantom

There are better shows  than  Cirque Du Soliel, though none with such
professional polish.
I think the "polish" is what put them on the top.

San Francisco is fast becoming a circus town ( in the worlds eyes). And
right now circus and cabaret is what is happening in the non-dance
underground.

In fact,  Circus has leaked over into the dance party environment.

Check out  Transister, Zenodrome, Mystic Family Circus,  for a fine mix of
vinyl and electronic beats along with  burgeoning circus performers.

If you prefer underground music parties to massive music parties, than you
will prefer zenodrome or Mystic to Cirque any day of the week.


For those of you that are promoters looking for something different, check
into the burgeoning SF Circus scene. Them kids need the money. Lots of it.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] SFR AvantGo Channel (fwd)

This should be fixed as of now, using the new calendar data.

Instructions on how to access the SFR AvantGO Channel:

SFRaves.org PDA Calendar v.2.0

REQUIREMENTS: To use the SFRaves.org PDA Calendar and AvantGo.com, you
need a PDA which runs Palm OS 4.x or above, supports synchronization on
http port 80, and an OS supported by AvantGo.com Software.

What is Avant Go?  http://www.avantgo.com

- Avant Go is PDA software with dual interfaces: a web application
interface coupled with the functionality of Avant Go Sofware to sync any
device running Palm OS. Avant Go provides access to online web content via
Avant Go web Channels. These channels point to content which is hosted and
maintained by outside sources. SFRaves.org PDA Calendar content source is
@ http://www.sfraves.org/calendar/sfrcalpda.txt

What is the SFRaves.org PDA Calendar?

- A condensed ascii text format of the SFRaves.org Calendar, coupled with
the functionality of Avant Go Software and a Palm OS Device.

TO ACCESS THE SFRAVES.org PDA CALENDAR

AVANT GO USERS
New Users Sign Up HERE http://avantgo.com/setup/index.html
Existing Users login HERE: http://avantgo.com/login/index.html

Go to the following AvantGo URL to add the SFRaves.org PDA Calendar to
your account and PDA device.

http://avantgo.com/mydevice/autoadd.html?title=SFRaves.org%20Calendar&url=http%3
A%2F%2Fwww.sfraves.org%2Fcalendar%2Fsfrcalpda.txt&max=175&depth=0&images=0&links=0&r
efresh=always&hours=2&dflags=127&hour=0&quarter=00&s=00

PALM OS USERS

You can download the most current SFR PDA Calendar @:
http://www.sfraves.org/calendar/sfrcalpda.txt

Regards,

Karina

Message-ID: <Pine.LNX.4.33.0212231341120.17803-100000@charm>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Creating sound files from an outside source

I'm assuming you're running Windows...

Take a look at the mixer app, either the one that comes with Windows
(attached to the main volume control) or one that comes with your sound
card. There should be configuration options for setting the levels of the
various inputs, as well as turning them off and on. You should be
recording off the line in, if you are not getting a signal there it means
that you probably have the line in muted.

As far as burning CD's of Talking Heads albums, it'll probably be easier
(and sound better) if you download the tracks as mp3 and burn from those.
Just be sure to get 192k or higher encodings.

dan

Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR:  The Twelve Days of Xmas

And on that note:

A Politically Correct Seasons Greetings

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
---

Best wishes for an environmentally conscious, socially responsible, low
stress, non-addictive, gender-neutral, winter solstice holiday, practiced
within the most joyous traditions of the religious persuasion of your choice
, but with respect for the religious persuasion of others who choose to
practice their own religion as well as those who choose not to practice a
religion at all; plus...

A fiscally successful, personally fulfilling, and medically uncomplicated
recognition of the generally accepted calendar year 2003, but not without
due respect for the calendars of choice of other cultures whose
contributions have helped make our society great, without regard to the
race, creed color, religious, or sexual preferences of the wishes.

Disclaimer: This greeting is subject to clarification or withdrawal. It
implies no promise by the wisher to actually implement any of the wishes for
her/himself or others and no responsibility for any unintended emotional
stress these greetings may bring to those not caught up in the holiday
spirit.


Found this the other day while coming up with a lesson plan to teach my
preschoolers about Winter Solstice and thought it was amusing

Jennifer

A POLITICALLY CORRECT "Twelve Days of Christmas" from Fraser Clark:

On the 12th day of Xmas - I mean the Eurocentrically imposed midwinter
festival,
My Significant Other in a consenting adult, monogamous relationship
Gave to me...

TWELVE males reclaiming their inner warrior through ritual drumming,

ELEVEN pipers piping (plus an 18-member pit orchestra made up of members in
good standing of the Musicians Equity Union as called for in their contract
even though they won't be asked to play a note),

TEN melanin deprived, testosterone-poisoned scions of the patriarchal
ruling class system a'leaping,

NINE persons engaged in rhythmic self-expression,

EIGHT economically disadvantaged female persons stealing milk-products from
enslaved Bovine-Americans,

SEVEN endangered swans swimming on federally protected wetlands,

SIX enslaved Fowl-Americans producing stolen non-human animal products,

FIVE golden symbols of culturally sanctioned enforced domestic
incarceration,

(NOTE: after members of the Animal Liberation Front threatened to throw red
paint at our computer, the calling birds, French hens and partridge have
been reintroduced to their native habitats. To avoid further
Animal-American enslavement, the remaining gift package has been revised.)

FOUR hours of recorded whale songs

THREE deconstructionist poets

TWO Sierra Club calendars printed on recycled processed tree carcasses

AND a Spotted Owl activist chained to an old-growth pear tree!
[from zenbaba]


Moksha Tribe

Subject: [sfraves] Hobbits, Elves and Raves

--=====================_17654249==_.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Last night many of the Moksha Tribe collective went to see Lord of the 
Rings:  Twin Towers.

I was thinking after the film how nice it would be to live again in a world 
of elves, hobbits, walking trees and magical things. This morning I 
realized that we can, for the mind may live where it wants. One need not 
succumb to the banality and materialism of modern life. One can create 
one's own magik -- or, conversely, one's own hell.

The Ring Trilogy was an important part of the spiritual growth of my 
generation -- a revival of the epic form. Tolkein eloquently expressed the 
modern struggle of the body and soul against the spiritless forces of greed 
and power. Unambiguous evil is manifest in the epic. The evils we face in 
our own lives are far more subtle yet just as destructive.

For example, Xmas, both a pagan and Christian holiday, once meant the birth 
of hope and light in the darkness of the winter of the soul.  These days it 
seems to be defined by the level of consumption.  Will the retailers make 
their sales goals this holiday?  Have we, as patriotic Americans, fulfilled 
our obligations as consumers?  Some of us are unemployed.  Is our 
self-esteem vanquished in a construct that equates work with being and 
level of acquisition with status and self validation?

The armies of darkness are all around us.  But we need not succumb to 
them.  As Tolkein showed us, the struggle of the soul against materialism 
and the thirst for power is a daily event.  The victories of the soul and 
good are not usually rapid or easy.

The rave community is a magical tribe of elves and hobbits. I think we 
strive in our own little way to fight the mechanistic, materialistic evils 
of post-industrial civilization with our own swords and spells: music and 
dance. Ancient rites, facilitated by the humane use of technology = 
raves.  We have magik on our side.  As long as there are life-giving, 
soul-nourishing celebrations of music and dance the evil wizards of the 
world cannot ultimately prevail.

I wish you all a spirit-enriching holiday, and bright prospects for growth 
in the new year.  Be you hobbit or elf, you have the magik within to bring 
light to the dark world, ravers.

Much love,

Apollo



Moksha Tribe

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Many persons have a wrong idea of what constitutes true happiness.  It is 
not attained through self-gratification, but through fidelity to a purpose."
-Helen Keller

"As long as you haven't experienced this:  to die and so to grow, you are 
only a troubled guest on the dark earth."
-Johann Wolfgang Von Goethe

"Chaos often breeds life, where order breeds habit."
-Henry Adams
--=====================_17654249==_.ALT--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Hobbits, Elves and Raves

"The armies of darkness are all around us.  But we need not succumb to
them.  As Tolkein showed us, the struggle of the soul against materialism
and the thirst for power is a daily event.  The victories of the soul and
good are not usually rapid or easy."

So long as Bruce Campbell is still around the Armies of Darkness will never
take over. Long live Evil Dead.

A more appropriate respone...

I'm not a big fan of the holidays. The season is overrated and has lost any
meaning for me. I find myself contantly wishing that I could just skip
forward a few weeks and be done with it all. It's not so much that I'm a
Scrooge, but more about how I can't stand the false *peace on earth and good
will to men* crap that gets thrown about this time of year. It's the same
thing as running around and saying *plur*  Either you do it because it's a
part of who you are or you don't. If you feel morally obligated to be nice
this time of year and emody some *plur* like attitude, don't. It's not real.
Instead think about how you can change your life so that you truly believe
in some good will and peace on earth. Make it so that it's a part of your
daily life rather than an imposed attitude for a few weeks a year. If that
doesn't work for you then carry on as normal.

For me the holidays symbolize bling bling cash money yo. I enjoy doing
little things for friends all year long. I think that is more true than any
*holiday spirit* that gets tossed about. I participate regardless, but I
wish that it didn't feel so plastic fake to me. With that I say happy
holidays and welcome in the longer days as the winter solstice has passed.
It's all down hill from here.

ryan.bailey
sninesix.design
design :: www.sninesix.com
photography :: www.innocentchild.com


ps...

It's kinda like taking E. Either you learn something from doing it and carry
it over into your daily life or you don't. I learned that I could love and
was capable of love. Ever since that first time I learned I didn't like that
drug but I liked what I learned from being on it. So many parallells...

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Creating sound files from an outside source

If you're running an SB Live or similar card you need to select the
recording source. In the sblive mixer you can shoose what input you're
recording from. If you choose *what you hear* it will take every input and
any effects and record that. You merely need to select the line in as your
recording input. It seems you figured this out already though. Never use a
mic input for a line level input. The mic input has a preamp gain on it and
will distort the hell out of the line level signal.

ryan.bailey
sninesix.design
design :: www.sninesix.com
photography :: www.innocentchild.com

----- Original Message -----
From: "Dan Haskovec" <dan@pry.com>
To: "adams, n." <mdsterbal@hotmail.com>
Cc: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Monday, December 23, 2002 4:45 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Creating sound files from an outside source


I'm assuming you're running Windows...

Take a look at the mixer app, either the one that comes with Windows
(attached to the main volume control) or one that comes with your sound
card. There should be configuration options for setting the levels of the
various inputs, as well as turning them off and on. You should be
recording off the line in, if you are not getting a signal there it means
that you probably have the line in muted.

As far as burning CD's of Talking Heads albums, it'll probably be easier
(and sound better) if you download the tracks as mp3 and burn from those.
Just be sure to get 192k or higher encodings.

dan

Piece Of Earth

By Oscar Gonzalez, AlterNet
December 23, 2002

Washington, DC (Neuters) =96 Concerned that messages of love and peace may=
 be=20
hampering its War on Terrorism, the Bush Administration is calling on=20
Americans during this holiday season to think "Piece Of Earth" instead of=20
"Peace On Earth."

According to U.S. Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld, "Peace is so=20
elusive, especially when you're not looking for it. So why not promote=20
something that you actually want =96 a piece of the Earth? Right now the=20
piece of Earth is Iraq, but it could apply nicely to any prime real estate=
=20
worth fighting for. Heck, I've got visions of Venezuela's oil fields=20
playing in my head even as we speak."

Mr. Rumsfeld also urged family members of US troops not to mail cards and=20
letters that mention peace.

"We don't want to confuse our soldiers about what their main mission is out=
=20
in the field. If you send cards, use a Sharpie to cross out love, peace,=20
and any other offending or unpatriotic words or phrases. If you must=20
mention Jesus, don't refer to him as the "Prince of Peace." Try the "The=20
Rocking Redeemer" or "Subcomandante J" instead."

Senator Bill Frist of Tennessee, who is likely to replace Trent Lott as the=
=20
Senate's Republican leader, claims to have the votes to amend the U.S.=20
Patriot Act to punish as treason the waging of peace during Christmas.

According to Senator Frist, "Now that we're at war with Saddam, oops, I=20
mean, IF we go to war with Saddam, we can't think of peace. While peace is=
=20
a nice thought, it should be an afterthought. We should think about it=20
after we win the never-ending War on Terrorism. We can address peace after=
=20
we've killed all our enemies."

Civil rights groups criticized the Bush Administration's policy, but took=20
great pains to make it clear that they were not attacking the President.=20
One prominent civil rights advocate said, "Doing away with the First=20
Amendment does concerns us somewhat, but we don't mean any disrespect=20
toward President Bush. We can and do distinguish between the man and his=20
policies. We think George Bush is adorable and that his every command,=20
however quirky and bizarre, should be obeyed without pause. However, we do=
=20
think his policies are a little Nazi-like =96 er, you did say this was off=
=20
the record, right?"

Polls reveal that 30 percent of Americans believe that the difference=20
between peace and piece is pure semantics. Fifty-five percent believe that=
=20
the Augusta National Golf Club should invite Saddam Hussein and Osama bin=20
Ladin before allowing any women to join. And 73 percent think that buying=20
holiday greeting cards that say "Peace on Earth," especially those=20
featuring Snoopy and Woodstock, are the best way to achieve world peace.


Oscar Gonzalez is a lawyer and writer who lives in Dallas, Texas.

http://www.alternet.org/story.html?StoryID=3D14845

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Piece of Earth


Piece Of Earth

By Oscar Gonzalez, AlterNet
December 23, 2002

Washington, DC (Neuters) - Concerned that messages of love and peace may be
hampering its War on Terrorism, the Bush Administration is calling on
Americans during this holiday season to think "Piece Of Earth" instead of
"Peace On Earth."

According to U.S. Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld, "Peace is so
elusive, especially when you're not looking for it. So why not promote
something that you actually want - a piece of the Earth? Right now the
piece of Earth is Iraq, but it could apply nicely to any prime real estate
worth fighting for. Heck, I've got visions of Venezuela's oil fields
playing in my head even as we speak."

Mr. Rumsfeld also urged family members of US troops not to mail cards and
letters that mention peace.

"We don't want to confuse our soldiers about what their main mission is out
in the field. If you send cards, use a Sharpie to cross out love, peace,
and any other offending or unpatriotic words or phrases. If you must
mention Jesus, don't refer to him as the "Prince of Peace." Try the "The
Rocking Redeemer" or "Subcomandante J" instead."

Senator Bill Frist of Tennessee, who is likely to replace Trent Lott as the
Senate's Republican leader, claims to have the votes to amend the U.S.
Patriot Act to punish as treason the waging of peace during Christmas.

According to Senator Frist, "Now that we're at war with Saddam, oops, I
mean, IF we go to war with Saddam, we can't think of peace. While peace is
a nice thought, it should be an afterthought. We should think about it
after we win the never-ending War on Terrorism. We can address peace after
we've killed all our enemies."

Civil rights groups criticized the Bush Administration's policy, but took
great pains to make it clear that they were not attacking the President.
One prominent civil rights advocate said, "Doing away with the First
Amendment does concerns us somewhat, but we don't mean any disrespect
toward President Bush. We can and do distinguish between the man and his
policies. We think George Bush is adorable and that his every command,
however quirky and bizarre, should be obeyed without pause. However, we do
think his policies are a little Nazi-like - er, you did say this was off
the record, right?"

Polls reveal that 30 percent of Americans believe that the difference
between peace and piece is pure semantics. Fifty-five percent believe that
the Augusta National Golf Club should invite Saddam Hussein and Osama bin
Ladin before allowing any women to join. And 73 percent think that buying
holiday greeting cards that say "Peace on Earth," especially those
featuring Snoopy and Woodstock, are the best way to achieve world peace.


Oscar Gonzalez is a lawyer and writer who lives in Dallas, Texas.

http://www.alternet.org/story.html?StoryID=14845

---------- Forwarded message ----------

High-tech billboards tune in to drivers' tastes
Roadside signs coming to Bay Area listen to car
radios, then adjust pitch

Robert Salladay, Chronicle Staff Writer   Sunday,
December 22, 2002

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------




The billboard is listening.

In an advertising ploy right out of Steven Spielberg's
"Minority Report," electronic billboards in the Bay
Area and Sacramento are being equipped to profile
commuters as they whiz by -- and then instantly
personalize freeway ads based on the wealth and habits
of those drivers.

For example, if the freeway were packed with country
music listeners, the billboards might make a pitch for
casinos. If National Public Radio were on, the
billboards could change to ads for a high-quality car
or a gourmet grocery.

The billboards -- in Palo Alto, Daly City and Fremont
-- will pick up which radio stations are being played
and then instantly access a vast databank of
information about the people who typically listen to
those stations. The electronic ads will then change to
fit listener profiles.

In the buzzy hum of 21st century commercialism, it's
the latest way for businesses to target consumers
without wasting money on scattershot appeals. Many
auto dealerships already use a similar system to
identify the stations people are listening to as they
pull into a car lot -- and then place ads on those
stations.

"You know what this is about? Accountability," said
Tom Langeland, president of the Sacramento firm Alaris
Media Network, which owns the 10 video screen
billboards in California. "People are struggling, the
world is becoming a more competitive place, and
advertising dollars have been a huge, misplaced
factor. Advertisers don't know where their money is
going."

Langeland said the technology should be in place
within a few weeks on electronic billboards off
Interstate 280 at Serramonte Shopping Center and off
Interstate 880 at Southland Mall near Fremont. Another
sign on Highway 101 in Palo Alto also is being
outfitted. Billboards in Sacramento, nearby Roseville
(Placer County) and Los Angeles also will use the
technology.

In Spielberg's "Minority Report," Tom Cruise's
character makes his way through city streets as
billboard advertisements scan his retina and then
personalize ads for products.


BIG BROTHER WORLD
Several of the Bay Area residents contacted by The
Chronicle said they were mostly resigned to a Big
Brother world where government and corporations
collect large amounts of information on citizens,
often without permission.

Many worried about the distraction of the large,
video-screen billboards. Vernon Burton of San Leandro
called it "junk capitalism" motivated by shameless
greed. Lowell Young of Mariposa said, "Everyone should
turn off their radios until they let us have our
privacy back."

"What's next?" asked Rob Blackwelder of Oakland. " . .
. It would be as if someone knocked on your front door
and said, 'I couldn't help notice through your window
that you're watching Fox News. . . . Could I interest
you in a subscription to (the conservative magazine)
National Review?' "

The California system uses a "consumer monitoring
system" developed by Mobiltrak of Chandler, Ariz., to
pick up radio waves "leaked" from the antennas of up
to 90 percent of all cars passing by and pinpoint the
stations being played.

Each station has a typical listener profile derived
from detailed consumer surveys. The system will assess
the most popular radio station during a given hour and
target the ads to those drivers.

"I can tell you how much money they spent on fast food
in the last week. I can tell you where they are
shopping," said Phyllis Neill, chief operating officer
of Mobiltrak. "I can tell you what percentage of them
were married and shop at Petsmart and made more than
$100,000 a year and potentially could come to Office
Max in the next six months."


DATA COLLECTED AND PASSED ON
Neill envisions a system of Mobiltrak-equipped
billboards along, say, a six- mile stretch of freeway.
The first billboard's receiver would collect data on a
block of cars and send it to the billboards farther
on, which would then switch to the appropriate ads.

"We have only just begun to scratch the surface of
what the technology can do," Neill said.

Privacy experts are not particularly worried about the
new billboards, as long as society continues to allow
people to remain anonymous. But they do notice a shift
in focus: Where the big concern used to be Internet
privacy, now it's physical space, from closed-circuit
monitoring to red-light cameras.

"I don't think it's really so much about stopping
technology or pulling the shades a little tighter,"
said Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the
nonprofit Electronic Privacy Information Center in
Washington, D.C. "It's about making sure there are
safeguards on the personal information that businesses
collect."

Neill said the technology doesn't have the ability to
listen to people's conversations or CD players, nor
would advertisers even care about such things.

The technology is designed to be anonymous and
passive, she said, and relies on information about
large numbers of drivers.

Hollywood already is installing similar technology in
movie theater ads -- electronic "posters" that
interact with customers to show moving digital images.
Walk by an electronic poster of Jennifer Lopez, and
she might wink at you.

"Minority Report" producer Bonnie Curtis, in a recent
New York Times article about the new medium, said she
could envision interactive posters that talk to
moviegoers, perhaps in Spielberg's voice.

"When I hear him say, 'Hey, Bonnie, I like that
blouse. Why haven't you come to see my movie yet?' "
Curtis told the Times, "then I'd say we are getting
very close."

E-mail Robert Salladay at rsalladay@sfchronicle.com.

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

>world
>-&e->of elves, hobbits, walking trees and magical things. This morning I
>-&e->realized that we can, for the mind may live where it wants. One need not
>-&e->succumb to the banality and materialism of modern life. One can create
>-&e->one's own magik -- or, conversely, one's own hell.
>-&e->
>-&e->The Ring Trilogy was an important part of the spiritual growth of my
>-&e->generation -- a revival of the epic form. Tolkein eloquently 
>expressed the
>-&e->modern struggle of the body and soul against the spiritless forces of 
>greed
>-&e->and power. Unambiguous evil is manifest in the epic. The evils we face in
>-&e->our own lives are far more subtle yet just as destructive.
>-&e->
>-&e->For example, Xmas, both a pagan and Christian holiday, once meant the 
>birth
>-&e->of hope and light in the darkness of the winter of the soul.  These 
>days it
>-&e->seems to be defined by the level of consumption.  Will the retailers make
>-&e->their sales goals this holiday?  Have we, as patriotic Americans, 
>fulfilled
>-&e->our obligations as consumers?  Some of us are unemployed.  Is our
>-&e->self-esteem vanquished in a construct that equates work with being and
>-&e->level of acquisition with status and self validation?
>-&e->
>-&e->The armies of darkness are all around us.  But we need not succumb to
>-&e->them.  As Tolkein showed us, the struggle of the soul against materialism
>-&e->and the thirst for power is a daily event.  The victories of the soul and
>-&e->good are not usually rapid or easy.
>-&e->
>-&e->The rave community is a magical tribe of elves and hobbits. I think we
>-&e->strive in our own little way to fight the mechanistic, materialistic 
>evils
>-&e->of post-industrial civilization with our own swords and spells: music and
>-&e->dance. Ancient rites, facilitated by the humane use of technology =
>-&e->raves.  We have magik on our side.  As long as there are life-giving,
>-&e->soul-nourishing celebrations of music and dance the evil wizards of the
>-&e->world cannot ultimately prevail.
>-&e->
>-&e->I wish you all a spirit-enriching holiday, and bright prospects for 
>growth
>-&e->in the new year.  Be you hobbit or elf, you have the magik within to 
>bring
>-&e->light to the dark world, ravers.
>-&e->

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Hobbits, Elves and Raves

>I was thinking after the film how nice it would be to live again in a world
>of elves, hobbits, walking trees and magical things. This morning I
>realized that we can, for the mind may live where it wants. One need not
>succumb to the banality and materialism of modern life. One can create
>one's own magik -- or, conversely, one's own hell.

Er, I dunno ... consider the following, from Salon a few days back:
(http://archive.salon.com/ent/feature/2002/12/17/tolkien_brin/)

"... Now ponder something that comes through even the party-line
demonization of a crushed enemy -- this clear-cut and undeniable fact:
Sauron's army was the one that included every species and race on Middle
Earth, including all the despised colors of humanity, and all the lower
classes.

Hmm. Did they all leave their homes and march to war thinking, "Oh, goody,
let's go serve an evil Dark Lord"?

Or might they instead have thought they were the "good guys," with a
justifiable grievance worth fighting for, rebelling against an ancient,
rigid, pyramid-shaped, feudal hierarchy topped by invader-alien elfs and
their Numenorean-colonialist human lackeys?

Picture, for a moment, Sauron the Eternal Rebel, relentlessly maligned by
the victors of the War of the Ring -- the royalists who control the bards
and scribes (and moviemakers). Sauron, champion of the common Middle
Earthling! Vanquished but still revered by the innumerable poor and
oppressed who sit in their squalid huts, wary of the royal secret police
with their magical spy-eyes, yet continuing to whisper stories, secretly
dreaming and hoping that someday he will return ... bringing more rings."

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Hobbits, Elves and Raves

--=====================_3839668==_.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

At 11:56 PM 12/23/2002 -0800, Mike Migurski wrote:
> >I was thinking after the film how nice it would be to live again in a world
> >of elves, hobbits, walking trees and magical things. This morning I
> >realized that we can, for the mind may live where it wants. One need not
> >succumb to the banality and materialism of modern life. One can create
> >one's own magik -- or, conversely, one's own hell.
>
>Er, I dunno ... consider the following, from Salon a few days back:
>(http://archive.salon.com/ent/feature/2002/12/17/tolkien_brin/)
>
>"... Now ponder something that comes through even the party-line
>demonization of a crushed enemy -- this clear-cut and undeniable fact:
>Sauron's army was the one that included every species and race on Middle
>Earth, including all the despised colors of humanity, and all the lower
>classes.

Or:

"If that's going too far, here's a milder version. Those orcs and low elves 
and dwarves and dark-skinned or proletarian men who fought for the Ringlord 
were fooled by Sauron's propaganda.
Fair enough. Even that slight variation adds flavor to an already-great 
tale, making you pity Sauron's dupes a little, even though you still cheer 
as they're slaughtered down to the last private and orcoral.
Come on, folks, a little empathy!
Instead of railing against "evil," try to understand it. That's always been 
the best way to defeat it."--- also from Salon.

I've always had some sympathy for the devil:)  God's most beautiful angel....

Literary exegesis, like the biblical variety, seems to be to be expressive 
of the views of the interpreter and all that's fine and dandy.  In the 
film, at least, evil is clear cut.  The book has always been much more 
challenging.  But all art reflects the times and yearnings of the artist 
and his/her culture.

I certainly don't have the unqualified faith in the future of technology 
that the Salon writer seems to have, and in my soul I believe in magik.  Is 
magik the manifestation of undemocratic powers?  Perhaps.  Or maybe it is 
available to all of us if we open our minds and hearts to it.

I prefer walking and talking trees to smelly factories:)  I also believe in 
the humane uses of technology, which probably places me at variance with 
Tolkein, but JRR was the product, really of the Romantic age.

Me...I prefer the dialectic.  Take the past and the present and find some 
compromise.

Love,

Apollo



Moksha Tribe

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

not attained through self-gratification, but through fidelity to a purpose."
-Helen Keller

"As long as you haven't experienced this:  to die and so to grow, you are 
only a troubled guest on the dark earth."
-Johann Wolfgang Von Goethe

"Chaos often breeds life, where order breeds habit."
-Henry Adams

Subject: [sfraves] Holiday Wishes

Merry xmas, Happy holidays, and Solstice blessings to my extended SFR
family.

Regardless what this time of year means to you, I wish peace,
happiness, and meaning this holiday season.

Below are a few choice URLs I regarding the holidays, et al. It's extended
reading; I added brief summaries above each URL so you can pick-and-choose
if you want.

take care,

-terry

History of Christmas, a bit boilerplate and with a Christian spin...
http://www.christmas.com/pe/1446

History of Christmas, from a psychedelia and shamanistic spin...
http://www.shamanshop.net/mushrooms2.htm

History of Christmas, from a Pagan spin...
http://www.witchvox.com/holidays/yule/yulehistory.html

Writings on the origins of Kris Kringle...
http://www.geocities.com/utherworld/seasons/santa.html

Someone's graduate paper on xmas trees, an object study....
http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~loribrod/Term2_Object.htm

Same paper as above, in a social context....
http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~loribrod/Term2_Social.htm

How different countries celebrate christmas, rest of site is
kiddie-oriented...
http://www.soon.org.uk/country/christmas.htm

Funny interpretation of 12 days of xmas email stylee...
http://www.netfunny.com/rhf/jokes/87/8036.html

------------------------------------------
terry estioko     | terry@hyperreal.org
SFRaves moderator | http://www.sfraves.org

it, as you can well imagine.

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Christmas, Christianity and Holiday Blues

------=_NextPart_000_013D_01C2AC02.09B23060
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

    I just got home from taking my Mother to church for Christmas Eve =
services, and I had a lot of strong feelings. I was raised Episcopalian =
(Catholic-Lite for those who don't know what that is.) My Mother took me =
to church every Sunday, the same church from the time I was 3 until I =
left for college at age 18. I loved it! Through going to different =
schools and being around different people, church was the most constant =
thing in my life. If I were to go there some Sunday, I'm sure there'd =
still be some old women there who would talk about what a devil I was =
when I was little. As I became a teenager, I began to understand the =
meaning of the prayers I was reciting, and could feel the presence of =
God when we worshiped. Growing up in East Oakland (near Eastmont Mall) =
everyone around me was Christian, be they Black and most likely Baptist, =
or Latino and most likely Catholic, so I never questioned my faith.
    When I was 18 I left for college in Santa Barbara, and from that =
moment on, I have primarily been surrounded by Atheists, Agnostics, =
Jews, Muslims, and most recently, people who are spiritual in many other =
ways . After my Dad died 3 years ago, I started picking my Mom up every =
Sunday and taking her to church. She loved it, but I found that no =
matter how hard I tried, I couldn't get into it. I could never recapture =
that feeling. The only part of it that I liked was having the chance to =
slow down for a little while, kneel in silence, think about what was =
going in my life and to give thanks to God for all that I have in my =
life, no matter how bad things might seem as I burn the candles at both =
ends. My Mom and I started church shopping, but I could never find =
anyplace that I could get into. I know that part of it is that everyone =
else there was either a child, a parent, or an elder.
    All the things about Christianity that have been bugging me for =
years, such as the racial and gender biases that dominate societies such =
as our own, and the fact that the bible has been translated repeatedly =
as it has passed from the hands of one ruler to the next have caused me =
to have a lot of doubts about Christ. Plus the fact that since the =
disciples all thought that Jesus was coming back in their lifetimes, =
nothing was written down on paper by anyone for like 100 years (don't =
remember the exact timeframe.) We all know how stories can change and =
grow when it's all he said/she said. Did Jesus really walk on water, or =
was he just standing in really shallow water and the story grew with his =
fame? Recently I have decided that I while I still believe in God or =
Goddess or something, I don't believe that Jesus was the son of God, any =
more than the rest of us are. I've avoided taking my Mom to church for =
the last couple of months, but I knew that she would really love to go =
tonight so I called her today and told her I would come pick her up.
    Tonight's service is the Lessons and Carols service, in which 9 =
hymns are sung in between 9 reading from the bible. The nine readings =
are supposed to tell the story leading up to the birth of Jesus, =
starting in Genesis, going into the prophecies and culminating with the =
birth story. When I was a kid at the Episcopal church, this service =
started at 10pm and went until midnight. I was actually a little =
excited, because I figured that here was my chance to hear the evidence =
of Jesus' divinity presented to me in black in white, which should help =
clear up any confusion. At the Methodist church where we went tonight, =
the service started at 7pm and ended at 7:45pm. They trimmed back a lot =
of verses from the readings and songs. But even what little I did hear =
did nothing to change my mind. I felt like a hypocrite for sitting there =
singing songs of praise about Jesus. When Mary asks the Angel how she =
could possibly have a baby when she wasn't married, it reminded me of =
the ways that marriage has been used to control both men and women over =
the years. When the 3 kings followed a star to the manger...we all know =
that's impossible, since the stars are not just a few hundred feet up =
like we used to think they were.
    So, I could honestly pray to God, but whenever Jesus or Christ was =
mentioned, I said the words but felt like a total hypocrite. The people =
around us were very nice and pleasant folks, and I felt like I was =
mocking their beliefs by saying one thing but not believing it in my =
heart. So, I have to figure out what to do, since I can't in good =
conscience keep avoiding taking my Mom to church. I haven't talked to =
her yet about my struggle, although I have talked to several friends =
about it. Just the other night I saw the episode of the Simpsons where =
Lisa rejects Christianity and discovers that she's a Buddhist. That =
episode makes a lot of sense to me. I know that I am a spiritual person =
but I'm still trying to figure out what form that spirituality will =
take.
    The other emotional thing tonight was about my Dad. My Dad died =
about 3 1/2 years ago, but he had a stroke 11 years ago, was knocked =
completely flat, and had to relearn how to think and talk, but never =
relearned how to walk. He stopped being the person that he was and =
became a completely new person. One of the things I miss most about my =
Dad from when I was a kid, was that he had a beautiful singing voice. It =
was really deep, and at Christmas time he would walk around the house =
singing Christmas songs. I really miss that. Even as I type this, my =
eyes are clouding up, and I haven't heard him sing in many years. I =
almost cried in church tonight when they sang The First Noel. I have no =
real feelings anymore on his birthday, Father's day, or the day that he =
died, but every year at Christmas, I miss his singing. I wonder if it's =
going to be like this for the rest of my life.

Happy  :-)

PS:    I don't want you to think that I'm all depressed, lonely and =
suicidal! Tomorrow I grub down with my Mom and nephews at my =
sister-in-law's house out in scenic Newman. That's the part I love about =
holidays, getting to be with the people you love and who love you no =
matter what!

------=_NextPart_000_013D_01C2AC02.09B23060--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: he knows what radio you are tuned to (fwd)

        The California system uses a "consumer monitoring
        system" developed by Mobiltrak of Chandler, Ariz., to
        pick up radio waves "leaked" from the antennas of up
        to 90 percent of all cars passing by and pinpoint the
        stations being played.
        
That means it is sensitive enough to pick up a signal of a few
microwatts.  Suppose someone were to key up their mobile ham
transmitter as they drove by those things.  Those put out between
50 and 1500 watts, which is up to 100,000,000 times more power.
I think that would desensitize their receiver for a while.
There is an amateur radio frequency allocation very close to one
of the intermediate frequencies they are trying to detect.

The FCC rules against causing deliberate interference only apply
if you are causing interference to intentional transmissions,
which the IF signal from a radio receiver is not.  

        ...
        Each station has a typical listener profile derived
        from detailed consumer surveys. The system will assess
        the most popular radio station during a given hour and
        target the ads to those drivers.

So everybody tune to KPFA when they go by the billboards,
and see what that makes them do.

...
        Neill said the technology doesn't have the ability to
        listen to people's conversations or CD players, nor
        would advertisers even care about such things.
        
OH YES THEY WOULD.  They just don't know how to do it.


Happy Holidays

Ride the Music

AndyTiedye

on the ornaments and hang them high on the

was covered with sharp metal hooks and only glass
ornaments hanging everywhere...also, my little bear
that i only see once a year, because it is supposed to
be a christmas tree ornament...it looks just like one
that my grandma had, i think she probably gave it to
me...anyway, the little bear is also NOT on the tree. :)

Subject: [sfraves] Anti-Drug Rebuttal Spots, What i'm working on now....

------=_NextPart_000_0010_01C2AC90.1BDAFE00
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

There are a series of ads out, paid for by our Government that state =
unequivacably that drugs fund terrorism.

Below are two drafts of rebuttal ads to that that I've written that i =
want to produce, and soon and am looking for help to make this a =
reality.

I'm clear that this isn't about anything but $$$$$$$$$$$ and power and =
control.

Street price of cannabis is $5,000.00 a pound through the legal clinics =
in California.

It will drop to near zero if it were legal.

If everyone can grow KGB, who would ever buy it, or even have too?

Its 'illicitness' is what has driven up the price, nobody is addressing =
that aspect of it yet.

The 'mark-up' on heroin is 5,000 percent because it is illegal.

The amount of heroin needed to provide for every sick junky on earth for =
a year can fit on the lot I am writing this from.=20

it's *only* 400 metric tons a year, AND given the computers we have it =
is child's play to make sure it gets distributed sanely.

That won't happen because the 'mark-up' is 5,000 percent and it creates =
a lot of employment via police, lawyers, re-habs, jails, etc....

It's bullshit.

Here's the draft of the first rebuttal to the 'Drugs fund Terrorism' =
commercials, it's a lil rough, but here's the gist:

(V.O. child's voice):

This is the Poppy.

This is the Poppy that is cheap to grow, process and distribute.

This is the Person.

This is the Person that uses and buys the Poppy.

This is the Person who is in jail because they stole the Money to use =
the Poppy.

Why did they steal the Money for the Poppy if it is cheap to grow, =
process and distribute?

This is the Congress that doesn't like the Person that uses the Poppy =
that is cheap to grow, process and distribute.

This is the Congress that wrote the Bill to outlaw the Poppy and its use =
by the Person who is in jail because they stole the Money to buy the =
Poppy that is cheap to grow and distribute.

This is the President that signed the Bill that became The Law.

This is the Law that drove the price of the Poppy up by 5,000 percent

This is the Cartel.

This is the Cartel, that was created by the Law, that was willing to =
take the risk for the=20
Money that comes from the difference in the price between the legal and =
illegal Poppy and sell it to the Person that will buy the Poppy, no =
matter the cost.

This is the Cartel that doesn't care if the Person goes to jail because =
they use the Poppy.

This is the Cartel that doesn't have to follow any rules and can sell =
whatever they want, to the Person that uses the Poppy, and if it's not =
tested and too strong and kills you, they don't care, they've already =
got the money from the Person.

This is the Cartel that will buy the Congress to sell their 'War' =
because it keeps them in business.

This is the Cartel that will kill you and anyone else who gets in the =
way of the Money, which they get from the Person, who they don't care =
about, as long as they get the Money.

Any Questions?

Heroin is a lil too emotionally loaded for most people to handle, and =
the above is a lil too provocative, so my focus is prolly going to be =
more along the lines of working with the cannabis issue, to wit, here's =
another one I just came up with, and keep in mind, it's a lil rough and =
it's right off the top of my head, so please bear with.

(V.O.  child's voice):

This is the Plant.

This is the Plant that grows freely in the ground, anywhere on Earth.

This is the Plant that is the Medicine that helps the person who is =
dying.

This is the Plant that costs the sick person who is dying $5,000.00 a =
pound.

Why does the plant cost so much if it grows freely in the ground, =
anywhere on Earth?

This is the man that sold the Paper to the Government that needed the =
Paper to fight the war to stop The Hitler.

This is the plant that can also make the Paper the Government needs to =
fight the War to stop the Hitler for much cheaper than the Man can sell =
his Paper to the Government.

This man didn't like that Plant because if the Plant was around, he =
couldn't sell his Paper for the money, so he made a movie that said the =
plant was Bad and made the People who used the Plant Mad.

This is the Man who spent the Money to make the movie that said the =
Plant is bad and this is the Congress that made the Law, so no one could =
use the Plant and the Man could sell his Paper to the Government for the =
Money, that he used to build his Castle.

These are the People that did not listen to the Man who made the Movie.

These are the People that said is OK for the sick people who are dying, =
who need The Plant as Medicine to feel better to have it.

This is the Government who still listens to the Man who made the Movie =
that has The Castle that the Paper paid for that.

This is the Government with the Gun.

This is the Government with the Gun that they shoved in the face of the =
Quadrapalegic that helps grow the Plant that the sick people who are =
dying need.

This is the Government with the Gun that they used to tell the =
Quadrapalegic to GET UP We are going to arrest you for growing the =
Plant.

Any Questions?



Admittedly it's a lil rough and really needs to be broken into a couple =
of different spots covering different aspects of it because it covers =
too much ground at once, and the message gets a little muddied.

Like I said this is only the first draft.

The point is to make them as simple as possible and get them distributed =
as widely as possible, since no other view is getting out through =
conventional outlets.

I need help in creating these, some Flash wizzes would be a great help.

It strikes me that a rave list such as this might be a place to start, =
so if you have any interest, contact me back here, and feel free to =
forward these drafts to anyone who may have in interest in helping out.

Thanks,

nic

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Good Vinyl Storage / DJ Furniture?

on 12/26/02 1:08 AM, AndyW at andy@saturn5.com wrote:

> I'm looking for something that can store lots of records that I can put my
> decks on.


the cheapest solution i've found is to get an 18" x 48" Metro wire shelf
set, with 3 shelf racks. that's just enough room on the top for 2 decks and
a medium-width mixer (i have an old numark 1260x, and it's *just* right),
plus it'll give you 8 feet of shelf space for records.

http://www.industrialhouse.com/Storage/Metro/SplitSleeves.html has a photo
of the shelf assembly. you've probably seen them before.

while most of the shelf racks have the wires running across the width
(almost useless for storing records, cuz they just fall through the holes in
the shelf), the 48" shelves have the wires running lengthwise.

you can usually find these shelves at restaurant supply stores, or better
yet, at liquidators that specialize in restaurant furniture. they're not the
prettiest solution, but they're cheap and extremely sturdy.

Orchard supply might also carry them in that size, but i think they only
sell complete sets... not sure how many shelves come with it.

good luck!

philip

ps> for the price of some of that furniture you showed, you could get
yourself a table saw and make your own. just a thought. :-)

you think?

heheh, well, now the feeling is mutual, the diff being that they don't hate
him for the color of his skin, but the content of his character.

ouch, that smarts.

I went to my first local massive in DC last saturday, and my new g/f is a
CSpan/npr freak, which is cool to a point, cuz I want my MTV as well...

diff is, i can do both, she won't.

I was making lunch and doing other things and the local npr was on in the
background and they were running Strom Thurmond's Dixiecrat acceptance
speech from 1948.

Don't let the 'old man' cleaned up present day media demeanor he presents
fool you.

Demagogue is what he is, and was.

Pure vitriol.

After the party we were walking around the Mall just bef ore dawn and it
turns out she was listening to it upstairs too.

We both noticed the same thing, the man's cadences were almost the same as
Hitler's.

Ooops.

The thing is, i had that shit stuck in my head all afternoon and meditated
on it.

When we arrived at the party I saw and felt something diff.

Pat buchanan looked at the coming demographic of the USA and doesn't like
what he sees, wrote a book about it in this past year.

he sees that the reign of the dead, white european male is coming, and soon,
and he sees it as a bad thing.

i don't.

we've done enough good, and for that matter, enough damage, and it's time
for us to leave the stage.

this whole event is the death rattle for this generation, sort of akin to
Windows Millenium being the end of DOS.

Kind of crashy, wasn't it?

Same thing.

We ravers are the future, they might try and fight us, but our day is coming
and the likes of Trent Lott and his ilk?

Their day is past, they just haven't come to terms with that yet, but the
truth is, they're history.

They will try to hold on, and it will be ugly, but in the end....

It's us.

let's try not to make a botch of things.

<<i will join you in celebrating the simplicity of my festivus pole. :)
>>>>>>>>>.

that was yesterday.

today through the first *really* IS Kwanzaa, and it has a special meaning
for me this year.

Friday, December 27, 2002 ** Weekly: Stir-Fri-Day
**

Every Friday, early evening, Stir-Fri-Day - With
DJs Jason Fluid and Maneesh the Twister plus weekly
guests stirring beats & rhythms. Stir-Fri-Day is a
free gathering of friends and strangers at a
down-low crossroads gallery. Designed to be a
recurring occasion for mental, personal, and
spiritual expansion and expression, Stir-Fri-Day
offers a sensory collage to entice the soul into
action. Stir-Fri-Day has hosted more than 200 DJs
and performers in many musical and visual styles
over the past 5 years. No cover, 21+. Located @ 111
Minna St. (between New Montgomery & 2nd), SF

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D203
San Francisco California, USA

Friday, December 27, 2002 ** Weekly: Vibes Ahead **

Fridays (Early Evening) - Vibes Ahead

Downtempo Happy Hour. Featuring Infiniti, DJ Seven,
plus special guests. Jeff behind the bar. No cover,
21+. Located @ Buzz 9, 139 8th St. (8th @ Minna),
SF

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D256
San Francisco California, USA

Tuesday, December 31, 2002 ** Soulive **

Mystery Machine Productions presents...Soulive Plus
DJ Logic and Lettuce

Soulive is a band whose time has come. This groovy
combo are trailblazers in defining a new branch of
the Hip-Hop tree. Their flawless sound fluidly
combines the soul and jazz of the past with the
inventive sound of today's hip-hop, dub, funk, and
dance music. As a result, this New York City trio
is a melting pot of jazzy harmonies, soul drenched
ballads, hip-hop rhythms, and no-nonsense funk. But
it is Soulive's raucous live performances that have
earned them a devoted legion of fans few of their
contemporaries can brag about. They have sold out
clubs across the nation and show no signs of
letting up soon.

 Be sure to check out Soulive a.k.a. "the Greatest
Band In The World" as they kick off 2003 at the DNA
Lounge in San Francisco with DJ Logic and Lettuce.
DJ Logic will join Soulive after sitting in with

Thursday, January 2, 2003 ** Weekly: Popscene **

Every Thursday evening, Mod Lang Records
present...Popscene! Featuring Britpop, mod, 60s
soul, new wave, indie and electronica grooves With
DJs Aaron & Jeremy. Every Thursday Evening.

Jeremy P. Goldstein, popscene co-founder and DJ, is
"excited to see the club's popularity remain so
vibrant for 5 years now. I cherish the opportunity
to share the music that is so important to me with
an equally passionate fanbase. Our crowd is really
knowledgeable and we love to hear their
suggestions." Aaron Axelsen, fellow popscene co-
founder and DJ agrees. "It's been so rewarding to
present this club for 5 years in a city like San
Francisco, with its rich and varied musical
history, a city that embraces diversity; a city
that allows us to throw a night where our
supporters dance to a eclectic mix of music from
Pulp to The Rolling Stones to the Chemical Brothers
to The Jackson 5."

Presented by the SF Weekly, popscene hosts the
hottest and most unique weekly nightclub every
Thursday 10 pm - 3 am at 330 Ritch Street, where
ages 18 and over groove to the tunes of Britpop,
indie, mod, new wave, electronic and '60s soul.
Popscene features dancing, cocktails, live bands
and record release parties.

18+ information: 415.263.0365, or
www.popscene-sf.com

Thursday, January 2, 2003 ** Weekly: Kit Kat **

(Every Thursday Night) - Kit Kat introduced the
weekly party concept to San Francisco in March 1989
and against all odds established itself as the only
Thursday night party worthy of a monster sweat.
Today Kit Kat sits on a Richter proof funk
foundation which is shaken to the core by local
fanatics determined to dance their ass off. This
party has inexplicably managed to elude the weekend
warrior virus and has a balls to the wall energy
behind it. By default The End Up provides a
comfortable who cares what you are wearing
atmosphere, so all attitude inevitably gets checked
at the door. The party gets started right away and
peaks when the local after hour posse swings on to
the dance floor and pushes the elevator above cloud
line in the nick of closing time.

The knobs are manhandled by resident DJ Marc
Jellybear whom in turn passes the closing baton to
rotating guests Simon, Garth, Miguel Migs, Jonene,
Wyatt Earp & John Howard. In addition the club
hosts monthly special events with the next level of
over hyped DJs that have been, however, thoroughly
Kit Kat tested and do in the end justify having to
pass the hat around for business class airfare.

Overall a guaranteed must call in sick in the next
few hours experience. To join the guest list &
receive passes via e-mail: kitkatVIP@sbcglobal.net

time: 10:30 pm - 4:30 am Free before 11 pm, $12
cover after, 21+ Located @ The End Up, 401 Sixth
St., Corner of 6th and Harrison Streets, San
Francisco - SOMA

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D289
San Francisco California, USA

where women and couples can go and dance the night

sensual side. To keep this atmosphere relaxed, fun

Sunday, January 12, 2003 ** 10 SUI (TCR, Botchit &
Scarper, London, UK) @ Sunday School Sessions **

We just finalized this booking for our monthly
breaks party @ the Galaxy Club & i'm really excited
to be able to share this news:

Broad Spectrum Sounds proudly welcomes

                     10 SUI
      (TCR, Botchit & Scarper, UK)

to San Francisco for Sunday School Sessions, along
with Broad Spectrum residents AJB1200 and Samira.

***********************************************

School is in Session.

Join the Broad Spectrum Crew at the Galaxy Club
(1840 Haight St. @ Stanyan) every 2nd Sunday of the
month for our newest nite: Sunday School Sessions,
covering the entire curriculum of beats and breaks
from 2-step to idm, nu breaks to dub.

As usual, you'll be in good hands with your
favorite resident DJ's Azimuth, AJB 1200 and Baby
J. We're also very proud to announce our newest
resident DJ's: Samira and RawMan.

With a sonic onslaught ranging from downtempo and
Nu-Skool to electro and D&B, this crew is making
quite a name for themselves and gathering a quite a
following along the way.

http://www.hyperreal.org:8080/raves/sf/events/view?identifier=3D155

-------------------------------------------------------
     SFRaves.org Calendar Administrative Notes
-------------------------------------------------------

SFRaves.org serves the greater SF Bay Area, but
reaches beyond the local scene to all corners of
the Terra Firma. Thanks to those of SFRAVES.org
community, whose support and network have been a
honour to serve.

Please notify me regarding new events, event
changes, deprecated event information, or any other
information pertaining to events in the greater SF
Bay Area and beyond. The SFR Calendar is sent via
email every week.

Please contact me @ karina@hyperreal.org

To subscribe to the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a
message to:
sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for
this list:  sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or
sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

Faithfully yours, -- Karina Powers
karina@hyperreal.org

Copyright: All trademarks, product or service
names, brand names and/or logos appearing on
http://www.sfraves.org site, calendar and archives
are the property of their respective owners.

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
